,30,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/image.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(54,1,'2015-02-25 18:46:19','2015-02-25 18:46:19','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLearning how to set goals is crucial for personal development. Since 90% of new years resolutions are self-improvement related or to lose weight, these are what we\'ll focus on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPeople are becoming overly dependent resolutions to start making healthy lifestyle choices. We put things off in order to start on a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. Old habits are hard to break and people don’t change overnight so when we expect ourselves to we are putting a lot of pressure on ourselves. This makes it discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways. Let’s try to break this train of thought. Think goals, not resolutions. The word resolution plays too many mind games.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFirst you have to ask yourself: <strong>What do I want?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are a lot of different types of goals. Once you’ve nailed that down, write it down and put it somewhere you’ll see it every day. A bathroom mirror.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHaving the knowledge is only part of the equation though. You’ll need plan of execution if you want to see results.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo you ask yourself: <strong>How can I get there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAchieving your diet and setting fitness goals is about cultivating healthy habits. A funny thing happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your behavior becomes like clockwork. Once you start seeing and feeling the benefits and you won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you want lasting results, sit down and look at the daily choices you make with regard to food, exercise, sleep, and stress. You might only have to make this resolution once if you do it right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Set attainable goals.</strong>\r\nThere’s no single step from A to Z. Write down a full list of goals and break them up into short-term attainable ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCommon examples of goals:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose weight”\r\n“I’m going to quit smoking.”\r\n“I’m going to make more sales and start saving more money this year.”\r\n“I’m going to work on my personal relationships this year.”\r\netc..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese are great goal ideas but they lack a step-by-step plan on how to achieve them. The language is too distant. One year is a long time and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It can be discouraging if you keep your sights set on 20 pounds. Think 1 pound. How am I going to lose 1 pound?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a plan of action, and set milestones.</strong>\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by eating healthy and going on a walk each evening after work. If I can keep this up for 1 month I will have lost almost 5 pounds.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n1. There is a clear plan\r\n2. There are short-term milestones\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that it’s not the end of the world if you mess up or miss a day!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nShit happens, it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and nobody’s perfect. Things come up from time to time but it’s important that you stick with it. So you skip a day. Maybe add 15 minutes to your routine the next day or whatever - just get back at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI had a friend who quit smoking for 6 months and one night he decided to have a smoke. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day. This is nuts. I understand substance addictions are difficult and complicated, but it’s the thought pattern that lead to the behaviors. So you had one cigarette, big deal. Resist the urge to have that next one and the urge will go away in time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnother buddy all psyched up one year about losing weight and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. These programs can be great but if you haven’t exercised in years, they can be tough. He worked his ass off for about two days and on the third he couldn’t get off the couch because he was so sore. He didn’t ever get back into because it was just too strenuous for him and he associated exercise with bad feelings. He would have been better off going for a few walks and easing his way into a program like that. You can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and your workout becomes counter-productive.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out. Plus, achieving short-term goals achieving them can be really encouraging! When you see and feel the progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Plan your trips to the gym.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more you’ll start to rationalize about not going. It’s easy to allow things to get in the way when you don’t plan for them in your schedule. Write it down &amp; plan on it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind you don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health. Every minutes counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThink you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this, 30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDon’t believe me? Try it sometime.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf your goal is to lose weight, keep in mind that exercise is only a part of the equation. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting junk in you’re going to look and feel like junk. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone. If you hate the taste of most vegetables, throw some into a blender with sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, bananas and some apple juice and to mask the taste. You’ll get them in without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Do what you enjoy.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy exercise. Habits will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get creative!</strong>\r\n\r\nIf running on the treadmill bores the hell out of you, try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. Crank up some crunchy tunes or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make it more enjoyable. The more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep it fresh!</strong>\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again you get bored and your body gets used to it. Diversifying your workouts is not only less boring, but it also helps you burn more calories because your body is not as used to it. It’s called muscle confusion.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get sleep.</strong>\r\n\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Anticipate obstacles.</strong>\r\n\r\nLife is unpredictable. There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps you achieve your goals. Under Armour has some fresh new swag if you wanna look good while you’re at it: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/iXABx7\">http://goo.gl/iXABx7</a>. Feel free to leave a reply and tips of your own in the comments section below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Additional resources:</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://appadvice.com/appguides/show/habit-building-apps\">Goal setting apps</a>\r\nNot sure how to choose the right foods? <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/\">ChooseMyPlate.gov</a> can help.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Goal Setting For Personal Development','','publish','open','open','','goal-setting-for-personal-development','','http://localhost/blog/exercise-tips-every-minute-counts/\nhttp://liveout.org/blog/fuel-for-the-fire-3-nutritious-superfoods-for-active-people/','2015-03-06 22:06:35','2015-03-06 22:06:35','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=54',0,'post','',0),(55,1,'2015-02-21 20:50:27','2015-02-21 20:50:27','People are becoming overly dependent on new years resolutions to start making healthy changes in their lives. We put off healthy choices until a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. The problem is, old habits are hard to break. People don’t change overnight and when we expect ourselves to, we put a lot of unreasonable pressure on ourselves. This makes it all the more discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFirst, you have to ask yourself:<b><i> What do I want?</i></b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAll the math and science in the world might endorse a certain diet or exercise, but having the knowledge is only half the battle. This information is useless without a viable plan for executing them – it’s like having a manual on how to fix a car without any tools.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSo you have to ask yourself: <b><i>How can I get there?</i></b>\r\n<h4>Knowledge + Plan = Lasting Change</h4>\r\n<b><i>Achieving your diet and exercise goals is about cultivating healthy habits.</i></b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nA funny thing happens when what happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your actions become like clock-work, and when these habits are healthy, you’ll start seeing (and feeling) the benefits. <i>You won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b><i>If you want to develop a sustainable plan for change – sit down and look at the day-to day choices you make when it comes to food, exercise, sleep, and stress management. You’ll only have to make this resolution once, if you do it right.</i></b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Set attainable goals.</h4>\r\nIt is better to set small, attainable goals than lofty, long-term ones. You can still dream big – but you’ll need to set some intermediate, attainable milestones along the way in order to get there.\r\n\r\nWhile <i>“I’m going to lose 20 pound this year”</i> may be an appropriate and acceptable goal, it lacks a step-by-step plan on how you’re going to achieve it. The language in this statement is too distant – a year is a long time, and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It makes anything less that 20 lbs loss seem insignificant – and this can be really discouraging.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>Without a plan of action, and achievable milestones, you’re setting yourself up for failure.</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Set intermediate goals.</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by going to the gym on Monday, Wednesday and Friday – and eating less junk food at night. If I can keep this up until June, I will achieve my goal of losing 20 lbs.”</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>There is a clearly defined <b><i>plan of action.</i></b></li>\r\n <li>It includes <b><i>short term, attainable goals</i></b> with <b><i>incremental milestones.</i></b></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4>Important Note: It’s not the end of the world if you slip, falter, or miss a day!</h4>\r\nIf this happens (and it most likely will), it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and we are not perfect. It is reasonable to expect that things will come up from time to time but what’s important is that you <b><i>stick with it</i></b> and seize the next opportunity to start back up again.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI had a friend who had successfully quit smoking for 6 months, then one night he decided to have one single cigarette. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day – after just one minor infraction. Don’t let this be you!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAnother friend of mine got all psyched up one year about getting in shape and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. Now, I’ve heard good things about workout programs like Insanity or P90X, but if you live a sedentary life and haven’t worked out in years, it’s INSANE to expect yourself to be able to keep up with a workout regiment like that. He hung in there for about three days and on the fourth he couldn’t get off the couch because his body was so torn up.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and the exercise becomes counter-productive. In this instance, it would have been better for him to start by taking a walk each day, and slowly easing back into exercise.\r\n\r\n<b>Prepare yourself for long-term change with short-term goals.</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out, so try to focus on setting short, intermediate goals. These are more easily achieved, and achieving them can be really encouraging and keep you coming back! When you see and perceive that  progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Plan your trips to the gym.</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more reasons you will find to not go. It’s easy to allow other things to get in the way when you don’t schedule these things into your day. Write it down. Schedule it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Think you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this:</h4>\r\n<h2>30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.</h2>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTry it sometime if you don’t believe me. Either way, it is important just to move around a little on those days you are not able to get a full workout in. Every minute counts!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Exercise is only a part of it…</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that exercise is only a part of the process. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting heavily processed meals into your body all the time you’re going to feel lousy and sluggish – its like throwing the wrong type of gas or oil into your car and expecting everything to run smoothly. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Trick:</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI personally am not a huge fan of vegetables, but I’ve found if I throw some into a blender with enough sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, a banana and some apple juice, it masks the taste and I can enjoy the benefits of vegetables without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Do what you enjoy.</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy the process of exercising. Habits are easier to get into and will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Get creative!</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you hate running on the treadmill – try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. You could bring an interesting magazine, throw on some good music, or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make the experience of going to the gym and exercising more enjoyable.\r\n\r\n<i>The more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.</i>\r\n<h4>Keep it fresh!</h4>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again, 2 things happen:\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>You get bored</li>\r\n  <li>Your body gets used to it</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhen you change things up, it makes things more interesting and helps you to get more out of your time because it forces your body to work a little harder and burn more calories to adapt to the change.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Get sleep.</h4>\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h4>Anticipate obstacles.</h4>\r\nLife is unpredictable.There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.','Setting Goals','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-v1','','','2015-02-21 20:50:27','2015-02-21 20:50:27','',54,'http://localhost/blog/54-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(56,1,'2015-02-21 20:51:27','2015-02-21 20:51:27','People are becoming overly dependent on new years resolutions to start making healthy changes in their lives. We put off healthy choices until a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. The problem is, old habits are hard to break. People don’t change overnight and when we expect ourselves to, we put a lot of unreasonable pressure on ourselves. This makes it all the more discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFirst, you have to ask yourself:<i> What do I want?</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAll the math and science in the world might endorse a certain diet or exercise, but having the knowledge is only half the battle. This information is useless without a viable plan for executing them – it’s like having a manual on how to fix a car without any tools.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSo you have to ask yourself: <i>How can I get there?</i>\r\n<h4>Knowledge + Plan = Lasting Change</h4>\r\n<i>Achieving your diet and exercise goals is about cultivating healthy habits.</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nA funny thing happens when what happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your actions become like clock-work, and when these habits are healthy, you’ll start seeing (and feeling) the benefits. <i>You won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.</i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>If you want to develop a sustainable plan for change – sit down