 decrease in BMI in women and a .04 drop in men. This may not seem like a lot, but these minutes add up after a while and manifests into real muscle and fitness results.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMost people think if they can’t make it to the gym, then why bother at all? Don’t think like that. You don’t need to go out and buy a workout plan like Insanity or P90x. If you haven’t exercised in a while, these programs can be discouraging and lead to burnout. Just do things to get your heart rate up a few times throughout the day. Start with a walk, then try to add some new exercises each week. One week you take a walk, the next week you get off the bus one stop early and walk home those extra 5 minutes. Every minute of physical activity counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHere are a few home workout ideas to get you thinking..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Crank up your iPod and clean the house once a week\r\n- Wash your car by hand instead of driving through a carwash\r\n- Have access to a pool? Swim a few laps occasionally\r\n- While cooking, chop the veggies by hand or stir the batter manually instead of using an electric mixer\r\n- Park further from the building at the grocery store or at your office so you can get in an extra 2-3 minutes in before and after\r\n- Get off the bus a stop early on your way home and walk the rest of the way\r\n- Take a 5 minute walk when you get home from work, before sitting on the couch or cooking dinner. Going outside for a while can literally melt away both fat and stress\r\n- Have a dog? Take them on an extra walk each day\r\n- Get a friend or family member involved with you and challenge them to join you\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou get the point. Don’t give up on a workout if you can’t make it to the gym, each minute of physical activity counts as exercise. If you don’t want to pay for a gym membership, Horizon Fitness equipment to help you lose weight: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/ovv4FG\">http://goo.gl/ovv4FG</a>. Bottom line, get creative &amp; do things you enjoy. If you’re moving, you’re burnin’ calories, and if you’re not.. well, you’re burnin’ daylight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Exercise Tips: Every Minute Counts','','publish','open','open','','exercise-tips-every-minute-counts','','http://localhost/blog/fuel-for-the-fire-3-nutritious-superfoods-for-active-people/\nhttp://liveout.org/blog/goal-setting-for-personal-development/','2015-03-06 22:12:20','2015-03-06 22:12:20','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=67',0,'post','',0),(68,1,'2015-02-22 02:43:46','2015-02-22 02:43:46','New research proposes something reassuring for those of us who don’t have hours to devote to going to the gym each day: Each and every minute counts when it comes to the 150 minutes of moderate intensity physical activity that all of us are supposed to be getting per week (according to the Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans). Researchers at the University of Utah discovered that every single minute spent participating in some form of mild to strenuous exercise was linked to decreased body mass index and lower body weight.\r\n\r\nNow this all may seem very intuitive, but based on the current physical exercise national recommendations, “aerobic activity should be performed in episodes of at least 10 minutes,” implying that the day-to-day activities, like taking a lap around the office on your lunch break or choosing to take the stairs aren’t sufficient enough to count when it comes to meeting the Guidelines. This recently released report by the American Journal of Health Promotion, shows that getting to these 2 1 / 2 hrs little by little, minute by minute is perfectly fine.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n“The idea is, that you can do one minute at a time and that’s not a problem,” says Jessie Fan, family and consumer studies teacher with the University of Utah and head author of the new report.\r\n\r\nFor each woman studied, every minute invested in greater intensity, mild to strenuous exercise was associated with a .07 decrease in bmi, a measure of body fat determined by weight and height. For a 5’4″ female, this means a reduced excess fat of practically a half a pound. The result from the men was slightly less significant: one minute of physical exercise was linked to a .04 drop in body mass index- translating into a .27-lb drop in bodyweight for a 5’8″ guy. Now this might not sound like a lot, and yes it is certainly not by itself – but keep in mind that’s only one minute, suggests Miriam Nelson, a nutrition science professor at Tufts University who had been on the board that developed the 2008 Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans. Multiply that by 10, or 30, or 150, and you have got some actual benefits – all accomplished by small amounts of high-intensity activity performed here and there throughout the course of your day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n“High intensity,” Fan claims, essentially means moving with a little pep in your step- enough to get your heart rate up for a short period of time: it’s not doing sprints or power walking , for instance, but it’s also not simply just moseying down the sidewalk, either.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n“I think it’s easier for people to process that message,” Fan suggests. “Otherwise, if they don’t have a block of time they might be discouraged, and they don’t do anything.”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFan and fellow workers collected their information using the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, a study method that utilizes interviews and actual physical tests to monitor the fitness of a wide variety of US children and adults. For this analysis, investigators obtained the Body mass index and body weight of 4,511 adults ages 18 to 64, and compared that with their physical activity level, that was monitored by an accelerometer, a tool that measures movement.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe results, experts say, provide some statistical proof to the notion that “every minute counts.”\r\n\r\n“Time is precious,” says Michael Mantell, Ph.D., a behavioral science professional with the American Council on Exercise. He admits that the “all or nothing” approach – as in, “If I can’t make it to the gym for an hour every day, why bother at all?” – is undoubtedly an explanation that all too often prevents people today from doing any kind of physical exercise. “This study identifies why that belief is inaccurate.”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are many ways to put this concept into practice: You might crank up your iPod with some upbeat music and clean the house, or head out for a while to hand wash and wax your car. You could do the dishes manually, chop the veggies by hand or manually stir the batter as opposed to using an electric mixer. You could get off a stop early on your way to work to walk the rest of the way, or simply park a little further from the building each day and at home.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe main message here is to take a minute each day for yourself and for your health. If you’re just getting back into the swing of things, a program like “Insanity” might not right for you – intense regiments like this can be discouraging and lead to burnout or even increased physical stress if you try to just jump right in. If physical activity isn’t a regular habit for you, for whatever reason, start by taking small steps – like going for a walk – every minute counts.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n<b>SEO URL:</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Meta Keywords:</b>\r\n\r\n<b>SEO Title:</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Meta Description:</b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Every Minute Counts: What New Research Reveals On Exercise','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 02:43:46','2015-02-22 02:43:46','',67,'http://localhost/blog/67-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2015-02-22 02:45:24','2015-02-22 02:45:24','New research proposes something reassuring for those of us who don’t have hours to devote to going to the gym each day: Each and every minute counts when it comes to the 150 minutes of moderate intensity physical activity that all of us are supposed to be getting per week (according to the Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans). Researchers at the University of Utah discovered that every single minute spent participating in some form of mild to strenuous exercise was linked to decreased body mass index and lower body weight.\r\n\r\nNow this all may seem very intuitive, but based on the current physical exercise national recommendations, “aerobic activity should be performed in episodes of at least 10 minutes,” implying that the day-to-day activities, like taking a lap around the office on your lunch break or choosing to take the stairs aren’t sufficient enough to count when it comes to meeting the Guidelines. This recently released report by the American Journal of Health Promotion, shows that getting to these 2 1 / 2 hrs little by little, minute by minute is perfectly fine.\r\n\r\n\r\n“The idea is, that you can do one minute at a time and that’s not a problem,” says Jessie Fan, family and consumer studies teacher with the University of Utah and head author of the new report.\r\n\r\nFor each woman studied, every minute invested in greater intensity, mild to strenuous exercise was associated with a .07 decrease in bmi, a measure of body fat determined by weight and height. For a 5’4″ female, this means a reduced excess fat of practically a half a pound. The result from the men was slightly less significant: one minute of physical exercise was linked to a .04 drop in body mass index- translating into a .27-lb drop in bodyweight for a 5’8″ guy