r elevation and peak. This comes in handy and can lift your spirits when you start to get that ”Are we there yet?” feeling as you’re trudging up a mountain whose peak is discouragingly hidden by fog. The Point de Vue is highly practical and conveniently priced at just $1.99.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nA less expensive alternative to the Gaia GPS is the EveryTrailPro ($3.99). User friendly and packed with great hikes, it allows you to take video and picture of your trip to record your journey, and is loaded with over 400,000 trails. You can record audio notes to self, for a more detailed account of notable points of interest along the way.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAllTrails (Free) is especially helpful for finding new spots. It doesn’t provide the actual topo maps, but it will help you find some great trails. It gives you tons of useful information like user ratings, difficulty, distances, elevations and path type. Bottom line, if you’re just looking to find new hikes, this might be all you need.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you just want to log your hikes and aren’t concerned about topographical info or other technical data, try iMapMyHike (Free). The app is simple, but sufficient for tracking your trips- and it’s free.\r\nTrails (Free) is an alright alternative to the AllTrails app. It gives you the trails maps with a paid subscription, but some users have complained about it not being user-friendly and having too many advertisements.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMotionX GPS ($1.99) is highly attractive for outdoor fans. It allows you to download road and terrain maps, and even marine charts for free. The app is fantastic, but some of the other apps are more comprehensive when it comes to providing practical information specifically for hiking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out (Free) …\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Scott McGuire\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network','Best Hiking Apps','','inherit','open','open','','73-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 02:51:28','2015-02-22 02:51:28','',73,'http://localhost/blog/73-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(78,1,'2015-02-22 02:52:28','2015-02-22 02:52:28','New research proposes something reassuring for those of us who don’t have hours to devote to going to the gym each day: Each and every minute counts when it comes to the 150 minutes of moderate intensity physical activity that all of us are supposed to be getting per week (according to the Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans). Researchers at the University of Utah discovered that every single minute spent participating in some form of mild to strenuous exercise was linked to decreased body mass index and lower body weight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow this all may seem very intuitive, but based on the current physical exercise national recommendations, “aerobic activity should be performed in episodes of at least 10 minutes,” implying that the day-to-day activities, like taking a lap around the office on your lunch break or choosing to take the stairs aren’t sufficient enough to count when it comes to meeting the Guidelines. This recently released report by the American Journal of Health Promotion, shows that getting to these 2 1 / 2 hrs little by little, minute by minute is perfectly fine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“The idea is, that you can do one minute at a time and that’s not a problem,” says Jessie Fan, family and consumer studies teacher with the University of Utah and head author of the new report.\r\nFor each woman studied, every minute invested in greater intensity, mild to strenuous exercise was associated with a .07 decrease in bmi, a measure of body fat determined by weight and height. For a 5’4″ female, this means a reduced excess fat of practically a half a pound. The result from the men was slightly less significant: one minute of physical exercise was linked to a .04 drop in body mass index- translating into a .27-lb drop in bodyweight for a 5’8″ guy. Now this might not sound like a lot, and yes it is certainly not by itself – but keep in mind that’s only one minute, suggests Miriam Nelson, a nutrition science professor at Tufts University who had been on the board that developed the 2008 Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans. Multiply that by 10, or 30, or 150, and you have got some actual benefits – all accomplished by small amounts of high-intensity activity performed here and there throughout the course of your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“High intensity,” Fan claims, essentially means moving with a little pep in your step- enough to get your heart rate up for a short period of time: it’s not doing sprints or power walking , for instance, but it’s also not simply just moseying down the sidewalk, either.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I think it’s easier for people to process that message,” Fan suggests. “Otherwise, if they don’t have a block of time they might be discouraged, and they don’t do anything.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFan and fellow workers collected their information using the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, a study method that utilizes interviews and actual physical tests to monitor the fitness of a wide variety of US children and adults. For this analysis, investigators obtained the Body mass index and body weight of 4,511 adults ages 18 to 64, and compared that with their physical activity level, that was monitored by an accelerometer, a tool that measures movement.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe results, experts say, provide some statistical proof to the notion that “every minute counts.”\r\n“Time is precious,” says Michael Mantell, Ph.D., a behavioral science professional with the American Council on Exercise. He admits that the “all or nothing” approach – as in, “If I can’t make it to the gym for an hour every day, why bother at all?” – is undoubtedly an explanation that all too often prevents people today from doing any kind of physical exercise. “This study identifies why that belief is inaccurate.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are many ways to put this concept into practice: You might crank up your iPod with some upbeat music and clean the house, or head out for a while to hand wash and wax your car. You could do the dishes manually, chop the veggies by hand or manually stir the batter as opposed to using an electric mixer. You could get off a stop early on your way to work to walk the rest of the way, or simply park a little further from the building each day and at home.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe main message here is to take a minute each day for yourself and for your health. If you’re just getting back into the swing of things, a program like “Insanity” might not right for you – intense regiments like this can be discouraging and lead to burnout or even increased physical stress if you try to just jump right in. If physical activity isn’t a regular habit for you, for whatever reason, start by taking small steps – like going for a walk – every minute counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network','Every Minute Counts: What New Research Reveals On Exercise','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 02:52:28','2015-02-22 02:52:28','',67,'http://localhost/blog/67-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(79,1,'2015-02-25 18:54:54','2015-02-25 18:54:54','For those who enjoy outdoor activities, here’s 3 nutrient-dense superfoods to supercharge your active lifestyle and improve your overall health and wellness.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Spirulina</strong>\r\nSpirulina is a form of algae loaded with nutrients. It’s made up of high quality, healthy proteins, B vitamins, and numerous other minerals with various health benefits. It boosts your immune system by kick starting antibody production and raising the number of cells in your body that help you fight disease. It also helps regulate fat and carbohydrate metabolism.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome studies indicate that spirulina may also help:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Regulate blood sugar levels and fat levels in diabetes\r\n- Slow the growth of cancer\r\n- Prevent and suppress viral infections\r\n- Detoxify the liver and kidneys\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis superfood is commonly sold as a powder, so it’s easy to stir into a glass of juice or water, but be warned, it does have a distinct flavor, so first-time users may want to start by blending a spoonful into a green smoothie for a healthy breakfast.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Broccoli</strong>\r\nIt’s cliche’, but it’s true. Broccoli will turn you into a badass. Loaded with nutrients, this vegetable helps you fight stress, fatigue, maintain weight, keep your blood sugar in check and boost your immune system - all at the same time. Here’s some of the nerd stuff to back it up:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBroccoli is packed with Vitamin C, which helps you recover from physical and emotional stress by balancing cortisol. Too much cortisol production leads to exhaustion and a fat belly, and you don’t want that. Broccoli’s stem’s have a lot of fiber and chromium to help you maintain weight and stabilize blood sugar. Stable blood sugar = balanced energy and less stress. The florets are packed with Beta-carotene - a powerful antioxidant that supercharges your immune system.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf a steamy side dish of roasted broccoli isn’t your thing, try blending some into a pesto sauce, finely chop to add to scrambled eggs, or add a bunch of small florets to your favorite soup, pasta sauce, or salad.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Green Tea</strong>\r\nGreen tea will turn you into Bruce Li. Chock full of nutrients, antioxidants, and caffeine, the list of things green tea has been claimed to fix include helping you burn fat, lowering your risk of cancer, improving brain function, killing bacteria and helping you fight infection, lowering your risk of diabetes and heart disease, and helping you live longer. Phew... As you can see, it’s worth looking into.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re bored by the thought of another hot beverage, think beyond the mug - use green tea in oatmeal, smoothies, salad dressings, marinades, juice blends, or even mixers!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese three foods pack a Mighty Man punch when you take them together. Not only do you get the individual benefits of each, but the combination helps you break down food easier and absorb more from what you put in. Better nutrient absorption = more energy, strength, and immunity and BOOM. You’re a badass. Now go be America’s next Ninja Warrior.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBy the way, Under Armour has some good deals going on on fresh swag right now  if you want to stay ahead of the curve &amp; lose weight in style: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/Y305lE\">http://goo.gl/Y305lE</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDisclaimer: I’m not a doctor; consult your doctor before starting a new diet. Yada yada yada...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Fuel For The Fire: 3 Nutritious Superfoods for Active People','','publish','open','open','','fuel-for-the-fire-3-nutritious-superfoods-for-active-people','','http://www.liveout.org/blog/exercise-tips-every-minute-counts/\nhttp://liveout.org/blog/goal-setting-for-personal-development/','2015-03-06 21:55:56','2015-03-06 21:55:56','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=79',0,'post','',0),(80,1,'2015-02-22 13:07:02','2015-02-22 13:07:02','I recently read an article about a 101 year old man  who  ran a marathon in under 6 hours at the ridiculous age of 101. He also apparently holds 5 new world records (for his age) in different running events. What was his secret?\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen asked what his secret was, he confessed that eating a certain combination of foods gives him limitless energy. He discovered that when he ate broccoli, green tea and spirulina his energy levels just skyrocketed. He had no idea why, or how – he just knew that he felt great when he did and ate it every day from then on.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNote: At this point, I realized that whoever wrote the article was now going to try to now promote some sort of supplement containing these foods. For all I know, the story about the marathon runner could be made up as a part of their pitch – but I was more interested in finding out if the part about the broccoli, spirulina and green tea was true. I’m not here to sell any products or supplements, but I did do a little research on why/how this specific combination of foods might have this effect and I thought I’d share what I found.\r\n\r\n\r\nSpirulina\r\nSpirulina is a form of algae and evidently just loaded with nutrients. It’s made up of high quality, healthy proteins, B vitamins, numerous other minerals with various health benefits.\r\n\r\nIt boosts your immune system by kick starting antibody production and raising the number of cells in your body that help you fight disease and also helps regulate fat and carbohydrate metabolism.\r\n\r\n\r\nStudies indicate that spirulina may also help:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Regulate blood sugar levels and fat levels in diabetes</li>\r\n <li>Slow the growth of cancer</li>\r\n  <li>Prevent and suppress viral infections</li>\r\n  <li>Detoxify the liver and kidneys</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h2>Broccoli</h2>\r\nVitamin C\r\n\r\nBroccoli can help fight stress and fatigue. It is packed with vitamin C which helps you recover from physical and emotional stress. Broccoli also has a lot of fiber, which helps stabilize blood sugar. Recent studies suggest consuming vitamin C before, during and after exercise helps balance cortisol (stress hormone) levels following physical activity. Your body releases cortisol when under stress, and overproduction of this hormone leads to exhaustion. This explains why people taking vitamin C report feeling more relaxed in stressful situations, according to studies.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nChromium\r\n\r\nChromium helps balance blood sugar by decreasing insulin resistance – helping your body process glucose more easily. Steady blood sugar means balanced energy and a breather for your adrenal glands.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFiber\r\n\r\nBroccoli is chock full of fiber – which can help you maintain weight by making you feel more full so you eat less. This means less fat for your mid section – an area that collects stress weight from cortisol production. Fiber also helps to slow the metabolism of glucose – which goes back the benefits of maintaining normal blood sugar levels that were previously mentioned.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nDark color = nutrient dense\r\n\r\nThe shade of broccoli is a reflection of the amount of beta-carotene it contains. Beta-carotene is a powerful antioxidant that fights free radicals and boost the immune system. The most health benefits are achieved when broccoli is eaten raw or lightly cooked. The stems are higher in fiber that the florets and the leaves have the most beta carotene –  so don’t forget those!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h2>Green Tea</h2>\r\nGreen tea has shown to boost exercise performance in many studies. Some of this can be attributed to the caffeine content, the rest to it’s nutritional value. There are different types of green tea- one of which is called matcha green tea, that allegedly contains 10 times the nutritional content and produces a more substantial boost in energy than normal green tea.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<h2>The kicker…</h2>\r\nWhen taken together, your digestive system not only receives the nutritional benefits you would get by consuming these foods individually, but this combination somehow also helps your digestive enzymes (the chemicals in your stomach that breaks down food) to absorb more of the nutrients in your system already – so you’re getting more bang for your buck with the food you eat if you include broccoli, spirulina and green tea in your regular diet. Better nutrient extraction = more energy, more strength, better immunity, better mood. Makes sense. Supposedly it takes about a week before you start feeling a real noticeable difference in your energy levels.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>Again, I’m not endorsing any products or supplements, and I can’t personally vouch from doing this (although I might try it!), I just thought I’d share what I found after a little digging. Cheers </i>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Fuel For The Fire: 3 Foods For Long Lasting Energy','','inherit','open','open','','79-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:07:02','2015-02-22 13:07:02','',79,'http://localhost/blog/79-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(81,1,'2015-02-22 13:07:51','2015-02-22 13:07:51','I recently read an article about a 101 year old man  who  ran a marathon in under 6 hours at the ridiculous age of 101. He also apparently holds 5 new world records (for his age) in different running events. What was his secret?\r\n\r\n\r\nWhen asked what his secret was, he confessed that eating a certain combination of foods gives him limitless energy. He discovered that when he ate broccoli, green tea and spirulina his energy levels just skyrocketed. He had no idea why, or how – he just knew that he felt great when he did and ate it every day from then on.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNote: At this point, I realized that whoever wrote the article was now going to try to now promote some sort of supplement containing these foods. For all I know, the story about the marathon runner could be made up as a part of their pitch – but I was more interested in finding out if the part about the broccoli, spirulina and green tea was true. I’m not here to sell any products or supplements, but I did do a little research on why/how this specific combination of foods might have this effect a