nal glands.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Fiber</strong>\r\n\r\nBroccoli is chock full of fiber – which can help you maintain weight by making you feel more full so you eat less. This means less fat for your mid section – an area that collects stress weight from cortisol production. Fiber also helps to slow the metabolism of glucose – which goes back the benefits of maintaining normal blood sugar levels that were previously mentioned.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDark color = nutrient dense\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe shade of broccoli is a reflection of the amount of beta-carotene it contains. Beta-carotene is a powerful antioxidant that fights free radicals and boost the immune system. The most health benefits are achieved when broccoli is eaten raw or lightly cooked. The stems are higher in fiber that the florets and the leaves have the most beta carotene –  so don’t forget those!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Green Tea</strong>\r\nGreen tea has shown to boost exercise performance in many studies. Some of this can be attributed to the caffeine content, the rest to it’s nutritional value. There are different types of green tea- one of which is called matcha green tea, that allegedly contains 10 times the nutritional content and produces a more substantial boost in energy than normal green tea.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe kicker…\r\nWhen taken together, your digestive system not only receives the nutritional benefits you would get by consuming these foods individually, but this combination somehow also helps your digestive enzymes (the chemicals in your stomach that breaks down food) to absorb more of the nutrients in your system already – so you’re getting more bang for your buck with the food you eat if you include broccoli, spirulina and green tea in your regular diet. Better nutrient extraction = more energy, more strength, better immunity, better mood. Makes sense. Supposedly it takes about a week before you start feeling a real noticeable difference in your energy levels.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAgain, I’m not endorsing any products or supplements, and I can’t personally vouch from doing this (although I might try it!), I just thought I’d share what I found after a little digging. Cheers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Fuel For The Fire: 3 Foods For Long Lasting Energy','','inherit','open','open','','79-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:21:26','2015-02-22 13:21:26','',79,'http://localhost/blog/79-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(86,1,'2015-02-25 16:13:45','2015-02-25 16:13:45','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFinding the right activity for someone with Aspergers can be a great way to manage the disorder. Geocaching allows those with autism to utilize their unique minds and improve their social skills at the same time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger\'s understands the complex challenges these men and women face in life. Those with Aspergers often have difficulties in social situations as well as repetitive behavior patterns and interests. They also tend to have extremely high IQ’s as a result of their dedication to their intense interests.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCertain careers and hobbies are more common among those with autism - those that involve technology, small environments, and few people. This is why Geocaching can be a great activity for those with Aspergers and other LD’s in the autism spectrum because it challenges them to use to exercise their sharp minds and encourages participation in group activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreation activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers called “geocaches” all over the world - like a real world treasure hunt. It’s one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks. Some parks are now even offering workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this relatively new activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual. You have to piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete interrelated challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you have to create a puzzle and leaving clues so people can follow your coordinates and find the treasure - or geocache. The acute problem solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers is precisely why they might love and be good at geocaching. It’s challenging, fulfilling, and it opens new opportunities to make new friends with the same interests and spend time outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers or other autism spectrum learning disabilities, you might gently recommend geocaching. There are places online where you can meet and make new friends who like these types of outdoor activities too. Try Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps someone. You can get all the geocaching stuff you need at Mountain Gear: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/zkeQYf\">http://goo.gl/zkeQYf</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGood luck!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Managing Aspergers With Geocaching','','publish','open','open','','managing-aspergers-with-geocaching','','','2015-03-06 22:38:34','2015-03-06 22:38:34','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=86',0,'post','',0),(87,1,'2015-02-22 13:24:16','2015-02-22 13:24:16','A young woman finding a geocache in the forest','Geocache','','inherit','open','open','','geocache','','','2015-02-22 13:24:16','2015-02-22 13:24:16','',86,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Breaking-Through-Aspergers-With-Geocaching.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(88,1,'2015-02-22 13:24:21','2015-02-22 13:24:21','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger syndrome understands the challenges these men and women face in life. But a fascinating article published by the Texas Park and Wildlife Department highlighted how one woman manages her Aspergers – breaking through her social difficulties and secluded life indoors – with geocaching.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAsperger syndrome is a disorder in the autism spectrum that primarily affects one’s social skills. People with Asperger syndrome commonly display intense interest, which often leads to an above average intelligence in select areas and sometimes as a result – a lack of social interest. Because of this, certain careers and hobbies are more common than others among those with the disorder – that is, careers and hobbies that tend to involve technology, small environments, and few people.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreational activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers, called “geocaches”, all over the world – sort of like a real world treasure hunt. It’s actually one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks, and so popular in fact that some State parks – like the Texas Parks and Wildlife – are starting offer geocaching workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this new (but also ancient) activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual, as is requires that you piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete other challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you’re basically creating a puzzle and leaving clues so people can find your coordinates – markers that lead to the next clue and ultimately to the treasure – or geocache. This type of challenge requires the acute problem-solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNot only can geocaching be an extremely fulfilling and challenging activity for participants, but it can also open the door – literally – to new opportunities like making new friends with the same interests and spending time in nature.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers, and looking to help them get outdoors and participate with others, perhaps you might introduce them to geocaching. There are places online where you can meet people with these types of related interests and find places to go- including Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network','Breaking Through Aspergers With Geocaching','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:24:21','2015-02-22 13:24:21','',86,'http://localhost/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(89,1,'2015-02-22 13:25:06','2015-02-22 13:25:06','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger syndrome understands the challenges these men and women face in life. But a fascinating article published by the Texas Park and Wildlife Department highlighted how one woman manages her Aspergers – breaking through her social difficulties and secluded life indoors – with geocaching.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAsperger syndrome is a disorder in the autism spectrum that primarily affects one’s social skills. People with Asperger syndrome commonly display intense interest, which often leads to an above average intelligence in select areas and sometimes as a result – a lack of social interest. Because of this, certain careers and hobbies are more common than others among those with the disorder – that is, careers and hobbies that tend to involve technology, small environments, and few people.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreational activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers, called “geocaches”, all over the world – sort of like a real world treasure hunt. It’s actually one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks, and so popular in fact that some State parks – like the Texas Parks and Wildlife – are starting offer geocaching workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this new (but also ancient) activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual, as is requires that you piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete other challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you’re basically creating a puzzle and leaving clues so people can find your coordinates – markers that lead to the next clue and ultimately to the treasure – or geocache. This type of challenge requires the acute problem-solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNot only can geocaching be an extremely fulfilling and challenging activity for participants, but it can also open the door – literally – to new opportunities like making new friends with the same interests and spending time in nature.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers, and looking to help them get outdoors and participate with others, perhaps you might introduce them to geocaching. There are places online where you can meet people with these types of related interests and find places to go- including Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Breaking Through Aspergers With Geocaching','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:25:06','2015-02-22 13:25:06','',86,'http://localhost/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(90,1,'2015-02-22 13:25:48','2015-02-22 13:25:48','New research proposes something reassuring for those of us who don’t have hours to devote to going to the gym each day: Each and every minute counts when it comes to the 150 minutes of moderate intensity physical activity that all of us are supposed to be getting per week (according to the Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans). Researchers at the University of Utah discovered that every single minute spent participating in some form of mild to strenuous exercise was linked to decreased body mass index and lower body weight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow this all may seem very intuitive, but based on the current physical exercise national recommendations, “aerobic activity should be performed in episodes of at least 10 minutes,” implying that the day-to-day activities, like taking a lap around the office on your lunch break or choosing to take the stairs aren’t sufficient enough to count when it comes to meeting the Guidelines. This recently released report by the American Journal of Health Promotion, shows that getting to these 2 1 / 2 hrs little by little, minute by minute is perfectly fine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“The idea is, that you can do one minute at a time and that’s not a problem,” says Jessie Fan, family and consumer studies teacher with the University of Utah and head author of the new report.\r\nFor each woman studied, every minute invested in greater intensity, mild to strenuous exercise was associated with a .07 decrease in bmi, a measure of body fat determined by weight and height. For a 5’4″ female, this means a reduced excess fat of practically a half a pound. The result from the men was slightly less significant: one minute of physical exercise was linked to a .04 drop in body mass index- translating into a .27-lb drop in bodyweight for a 5’8″ guy. Now this might not sound like a lot, and yes it is certainly not by itself – but keep in mind that’s only one minute, suggests Miriam Nelson, a nutrition science professor at Tufts University who had been on the board that developed the 2008 Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans. Multiply that by 10, or 30, or 150, and you have got some actual benefits – all accomplished by small amounts of high-intensity activity performed here and there throughout the course of your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“High intensity,” Fan claims, essentially means moving with a little pep in your step- enough to get your heart rate up for a short period of time: it’s not doing sprints or power walking , for instance, but it’s also not simply just moseying down the sidewalk, either.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I think it’s easier for people to process that message,” Fan suggests. “Otherwise, if they don’t have a block of time they might be discouraged, and they don’t do anything.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFan and fellow workers collected their information using the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, a study method that utilizes interviews and actual physical tests to monitor the fitness of a wide variety of US children and adults. For this analysis, investigators obtained the Body mass index and body weight of 4,511 adults ages 18 to 64, and compared that with their physical activity level, that was monitored by an accelerometer, a tool that measures movement.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe results, experts say, provide some statistical proof to the notion that “every minute counts.”\r\n“Time is precious,” says Michael Mantell, Ph.D., a behavioral science professional with the American Council on Exercise. He admits that the “all or nothing” approach – as in, “If I can’t make it to the gym for an hour every day, why bother at all?” – is undoubtedly an explanation that all too often prevents people today from doing any kind of physical exercise. “This study identifies why that belief is inaccurate.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are many ways to put this concept into practice: You might crank up your iPod with some upbeat music and clean the house, or head out for a while to hand wash and wax your car. You could do the dishes manually, chop the veggies by hand or manually stir the batter as opposed to using an electric mixer. You could get off a stop early on your way to work to walk the rest of the way, or simply park a little further from the building each day and at home.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe main message here is to take a minute each day for yourself and for your health. If you’re just getting back into the swing of things, a program like “Insanity” might not right for you – intense regiments like this can be discouraging and lead to burnout or even increased physical stress if you try to just jump right in. If physical activity isn’t a regular habit for you, for whatever reason, start by taking small steps – like going for a walk – every minute counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Every Minute Counts: What New Research Reveals On Exercise','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:25:48','2015-02-22 13:25:48','',67,'http://localhost/blog/67-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(91,1,'2015-02-22 13:26:55','2015-02-22 13:26:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPeople are becoming overly dependent on new years resolutions to start making healthy changes in their lives. We put off healthy choices until a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. The problem is, old habits are hard to break. People don’t change overnight and when we expect ourselves to, we put a lot of unreasonable pressure on ourselves. This makes it all the more discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFirst, you have to ask yourself: <em>What do I want?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAll the math and science in the world might endorse a certain diet or exercise, but having the knowledge is only half the battle. This information is useless without a viable plan for executing them – it’s like having a manual on how to fix a car without any tools.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo you have to ask yourself: <em>How can I get there?</em>\r\nKnowledge + Plan = Lasting Change\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAchieving your diet and exercise goals is about cultivating healthy habits.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nA funny thing happens when what happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your actions become like clock-work, and when these habits are healthy, you’ll start seeing (and feeling) the benefits. You won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you want to develop a sustainable plan for change – sit down and look at the day-to day choices you make when it comes to food, exercise, sleep, and stress management. You’ll only have to make this resolution once, if you do it right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSet attainable goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt is better to set small, attainable goals than lofty, long-term ones. You can still dream big – but you’ll need to set some intermediate, attainable milestones along the way in order to get there.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile “I’m going to lose 20 pound this year” may be an appropriate and acceptable goal, it lacks a step-by-step plan on how you’re going to achieve it. The language in this statement is too distant – a year is a long time, and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It makes anything less that 20 lbs loss seem insignificant – and this can be really discouraging.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWithout a plan of action, and achievable milestones, you’re setting yourself up for failure.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSet intermediate goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by going to the gym on Monday, Wednesday and Friday – and eating less junk food at night. If I can keep this up until June, I will achieve my goal of losing 20 lbs.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere is a clearly defined <i>plan of action.</i>\r\n\r\n<i>\r\nIt includes <i>short term, attainable goals</i> with <i>incremental milestones.</i></i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt’s not the end of the world if you slip, falter, or miss a day!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf this happens (and it most likely will), it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and we are not perfect. It is reasonable to expect that things will come up from time to time but what’s important is that you <i>stick with it</i> and seize the next opportunity to start back up again.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI had a friend who had successfully quit smoking for 6 months, then one night he decided to have one single cigarette. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day – after just one minor infraction. Don’t let this be you!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnother friend of mine got all psyched up one year about getting in shape and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. Now, I’ve heard good things about workout programs like Insanity or P90X, but if you live a sedentary life and haven’t worked out in years, it’s INSANE to expect yourself to be able to keep up with a workout regiment like that. He hung in there for about three days and on the fourth he couldn’t get off the couch because his body was so torn up.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and the exercise becomes counter-productive. In this instance, it would have been better for him to start by taking a walk each day, and slowly easing back into exercise.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPrepare yourself for long-term change with short-term goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out, so try to focus on setting short, intermediate goals. These are more easily achieved, and achieving them can be really encouraging and keep you coming back! When you see and perceive that  progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPlan your trips to the gym.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more reasons you will find to not go. It’s easy to allow other things to get in the way when you don’t schedule these things into your day. Write it down. Schedule it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThink you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this:\r\n\r\n30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry it sometime if you don’t believe me. Either way, it is important just to move around a little on those days you are not able to get a full workout in. Every minute counts!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExercise is only a part of it…\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that exercise is only a part of the process. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting heavily processed meals into your body all the time you’re going to feel lousy and sluggish – its like throwing the wrong type of gas or oil into your car and expecting everything to run smoothly. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTrick: I personally am not a huge fan of vegetables, but I’ve found if I throw some into a blender with enough sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, a banana and some apple juice, it masks the taste and I can enjoy the benefits of vegetables without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDo what you enjoy.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy the process of exercising. Habits are easier to get into and will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGet creative!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you hate running on the treadmill – try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. You could bring an interesting magazine, throw on some good music, or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make the experience of going to the gym and exercising more enjoyable.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.\r\nKeep it fresh!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again, 2 things happen:\r\n\r\nYou get bored\r\nYour body gets used to it\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you change things up, it makes things more interesting and helps you to get more out of your time because it forces your body to work a little harder and burn more calories to adapt to the change.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGet sleep.\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnticipate obstacles.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLife is unpredictable.There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.','Setting Goals','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:26:55','2015-02-22 13:26:55','',54,'http://localhost/blog/54-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(92,1,'2015-02-22 13:28:04','2015-02-22 13:28:04','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPeople are becoming overly dependent on new years resolutions to start making healthy changes in their lives. We put off healthy choices until a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. The problem is, old habits are hard to break. People don’t change overnight and when we expect ourselves to, we put a lot of unreasonable pressure on ourselves. This makes it all the more discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFirst, you have to ask yourself: <em>What do I want?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAll the math and science in the world might endorse a certain diet or exercise, but having the knowledge is only half the battle. This information is useless without a viable plan for executing them – it’s like having a manual on how to fix a car without any tools.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo you have to ask yourself: <em>How can I get there?</em>\r\nKnowledge + Plan = Lasting Change\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAchieving your diet and exercise goals is about cultivating healthy habits.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nA funny thing happens when what happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your actions become like clock-work, and when these habits are healthy, you’ll start seeing (and feeling) the benefits. You won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you want to develop a sustainable plan for change – sit down and look at the day-to day choices you make when it comes to food, exercise, sleep, and stress management. You’ll only have to make this resolution once, if you do it right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSet attainable goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt is better to set small, attainable goals than lofty, long-term ones. You can still dream big – but you’ll need to set some intermediate, attainable milestones along the way in order to get there.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile “I’m going to lose 20 pound this year” may be an appropriate and acceptable goal, it lacks a step-by-step plan on how you’re going to achieve it. The language in this statement is too distant – a year is a long time, and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It makes anything less that 20 lbs loss seem insignificant – and this can be really discouraging.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWithout a plan of action, and achievable milestones, you’re setting yourself up for failure.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSet intermediate goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by going to the gym on Monday, Wednesday and Friday – and eating less junk food at night. If I can keep this up until June, I will achieve my goal of losing 20 lbs.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere is a clearly defined <i>plan of action.</i>\r\n\r\n<i>\r\nIt includes <i>short term, attainable goals</i> with <i>incremental milestones.</i></i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt’s not the end of the world if you slip, falter, or miss a day!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf this happens (and it most likely will), it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and we are not perfect. It is reasonable to expect that things will come up from time to time but what’s important is that you <i>stick with it</i> and seize the next opportunity to start back up again.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI had a friend who had successfully quit smoking for 6 months, then one night he decided to have one single cigarette. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day – after just one minor infraction. Don’t let this be you!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnother friend of mine got all psyched up one year about getting in shape and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. Now, I’ve heard good things about workout programs like Insanity or P90X, but if you live a sedentary life and haven’t worked out in years, it’s INSANE to expect yourself to be able to keep up with a workout regiment like that. He hung in there for about three days and on the fourth he couldn’t get off the couch because his body was so torn up.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and the exercise becomes counter-productive. In this instance, it would have been better for him to start by taking a walk each day, and slowly easing back into exercise.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPrepare yourself for long-term change with short-term goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out, so try to focus on setting short, intermediate goals. These are more easily achieved, and achieving them can be really encouraging and keep you coming back! When you see and perceive that  progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPlan your trips to the gym.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more reasons you will find to not go. It’s easy to allow other things to get in the way when you don’t schedule these things into your day. Write it down. Schedule it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThink you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this:\r\n\r\n30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry it sometime if you don’t believe me. Either way, it is important just to move around a little on those days you are not able to get a full workout in. Every minute counts!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExercise is only a part of it…\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that exercise is only a part of the process. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting heavily processed meals into your body all the time you’re going to feel lousy and sluggish – its like throwing the wrong type of gas or oil into your car and expecting everything to run smoothly. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTrick: I personally am not a huge fan of vegetables, but I’ve found if I throw some into a blender with enough sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, a banana and some apple juice, it masks the taste and I can enjoy the benefits of vegetables without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDo what you enjoy.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy the process of exercising. Habits are easier to get into and will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGet creative!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you hate running on the treadmill – try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. You could bring an interesting magazine, throw on some good music, or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make the experience of going to the gym and exercising more enjoyable.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.\r\nKeep it fresh!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again, 2 things happen:\r\n\r\nYou get bored\r\nYour body gets used to it\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you change things up, it makes things more interesting and helps you to get more out of your time because it forces your body to work a little harder and burn more calories to adapt to the change.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGet sleep.\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnticipate obstacles.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLife is unpredictable.There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Setting Goals','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:28:04','2015-02-22 13:28:04','',54,'http://localhost/blog/54-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(93,1,'2015-02-25 20:15:20','2015-02-25 20:15:20','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for fun places to visit for outdoor activities this spring? With fifty-eight to choose from, it can be difficult to pick just which national park to explore next. Spread all over the country, these exquisitely preserved swaths of nature allow for the perfect break from the stress of everyday life. The greatest aspect of America’s National Parks is that there are parks to represent nearly every environment and climate imaginable. So to help you narrow down your options for your next trip, here are five National Parks to add to your bucket list.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-95\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\" alt=\"Yosemite National Park\" width=\"400\" height=\"267\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Yosemite National Park, California</strong>\r\n\r\nYosemite easily makes its way onto this list if for no other reason that it is an icon of a National Park and a go-to destination for outdoor activities. It was formally designated as a national park over 120 years ago and its beautiful scenery lead to its declaration as UNESECO World Heritage Sight in 1984. Few other places in the world can offer such views as those offered by the towering granite cliffs that drop off into the endless forests of Yosemite.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlso, about 95% of the park’s 1,880 square miles is designated as wilderness. So despite the high amount of visitors that come to Yosemite each year, if you’re looking to get completely lost (metaphorically speaking, of course) on a backpacking trek, you will have no problem doing so in such a vast expanse. It’s history, scenic landscapes, impressive size all come together to make this an absolute must see.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Zion-National-Park_-Utah_.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-96\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Zion-National-Park_-Utah_.jpg\" alt=\"Zion National Park\" width=\"400\" height=\"265\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Zion National Park, Utah</strong>\r\n\r\nZion should be high on any backpacker’s to-see list largely due to the gorgeous sights of emerald rivers that have carved out some impressively magnificent rock formations. Zion actually boasts a great deal of environmental diversity. Aside from the desert expanses and red rock caves that the park has become known for, the park also contains large sections of woodland and forested areas perfect for camping, hiking, and climbing. It’s variety in the ecosystems it offers is yet another reason to add Zion to your National Park bucketlist.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Acadia-National-Park_Maine.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-98\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Acadia-National-Park_Maine.jpg\" alt=\"Picturesque Acadia National Park Shoreline\" width=\"400\" height=\"256\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Acadia National Park, Maine</strong>\r\n\r\nArguably the natural gem of the East Coast, the iconic Acadia National Park is comprised of a series of heavily wooded islands off the coast of Maine. It’s considerably smaller than the other parks on the list, but it still offers great opportunities for camping nonetheless. Though it is small, the miles of coastline and the fact that it is located in one of the most beautiful scenic landscapes of the East Coast have given Acadia a reputation for providing some of the most memorable views imaginable.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Denali-National-Park_Alaska.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-99\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Denali-National-Park_Alaska.jpg\" alt=\"Lake on Alaska\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Denali National Park, Alaska</strong>\r\n\r\nAlaska just very well may be the most naturally beautiful state in America. Even if you only have the opportunity to travel in and around Anchorage, the most heavily populated area of the state, you will still be surrounded incredibly beautiful landscapes and fun things to do. There are endless opportunities for hiking, camping and fishing within short driving distance of the city. Though if you’re looking for a great area to go backpacking, Denali National Park is the place to go.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDenali is considerably larger than most other national parks. The park is actually bigger than the entire state of Massachusetts. It encompasses endless mountain ranges, valleys, rivers, woodlands and just one road. Also, it’s home to America’s largest mountain, Mt. McKinley. Even if you don’t make it to the summit of this 20,000-foot behemoth, it certainly provides for some spectacular scenery nonetheless.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Olympic-National-Park_-Washington.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-94\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Olympic-National-Park_-Washington.jpg\" alt=\"Olympik coast\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Olympic National Park, Washington</strong>\r\n\r\nLooking for things to do in Washington? If you’re trying to truly immerse yourself in the backcountry and make your escape from everyday life, Olympic National Park is the perfect place to do just that. Similar to Yosemite, 95% of this massive park is designated as wilderness. The few roads that are in the park barely penetrate this North American rainforest. And if you traverse to the west side of the park, 60 miles of isolated Pacific coastline await. Very few, if any other, parks offer rainforests, snowcapped mountains and pristine rocky shore beaches, which should make Olympic National Park a strong favorite for anyone who enjoys outdoor activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWell, there you have it. Some great places to visit to enjoy your favorite outdoor activities before you kick the bucket. You can make a bucket list and find people to live out your ideas with at Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network. For deals on outdoor gear, Patagonia is your best bet: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/0lSZvz\">http://goo.gl/0lSZvz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFeel free to share some of your best ideas for where to go in the comment section below!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Ryan Quinn\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Five National Parks Great For Outdoor Activities To Add To Your Bucket List','','publish','open','open','','five-national-parks-great-for-outdoor-activities-to-add-to-your-bucket-list','','http://www.liveout.org/blog/hiking-tips-how-to-pack-a-backpack/\nhttp://www.liveout.org/blog/important-backpacking-traits/\nhttp://www.liveout.org/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/\nhttp://www.liveout.org/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes','2015-03-06 21:35:20','2015-03-06 21:35:20','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=93',0,'post','',0),(94,1,'2015-02-22 13:30:47','2015-02-22 13:30:47','Olympic National Park landscapes','Olympik coast','','inherit','open','open','','olympik-coast','','','2015-02-22