e items to achieve balanced weight distribution.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Conservation</strong>\r\nConservation of space is also very important to consider, as simply getting everything to fit can be a huge challenge in itself. Here’s a little advice from experience:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nShare gear. Try to share gear with a partner and eliminate duplication. Note: If you do this, be sure to stick close to your partner! Don’t want them wandering off with the map, food and water.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOnly take what you need. Note: You might not know exactly what you’ll need/use in advance until you’ve been on several hikes, until then, it’s probably best to play it safe. Better safe than sorry! Things NOT to skimp on: A good sleeping pad &amp; clean socks!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAttach gear. Grab a couple carabiners before you go and attach some gear to the outside of your pack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCompress. Try to find compressible gear – there’s a lot of really light, warm, and compressible gear out there and lot of this stuff is becoming more and more affordable. If you haven’t updated your hiking arsenal in the past two decades, it might save your pack and your back by looking into it\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWater on the sides. Carry your water on the sides of your pack. You can even replace hard water bottles with collapsible reservoirs, which will also help with the weight factor.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRepackage food. Sometimes prepackaged backpacking meals can take up a huge amount of space with mostly empty air space inside the bag. Take the food out and repackage it yourself to minimize the space it takes up. Also, try to pack calorie dense food like nuts, dried fruit, and oatmeal to maximize the calories you’re getting per ounce of weight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRoll your clothes. When it comes to packing clothing, you can save space and fit more into your pack by rolling up your clothes. Rolling compresses clothes better than folding\r\nTip: you can fit your socks in that extra pair of boots you’re carrying\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo there you have it, some basic tips on how to pack a backpack. As mentioned, it’s not extremely complex, but it does help to consider a few things and plan ahead to avoid any unnecessary discomfort that might take away from the experience\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Ryan Quinn\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Hiking Tips: Packing a Backpack','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 13:37:29','2015-02-22 13:37:29','',102,'http://localhost/blog/102-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(104,1,'2015-02-22 13:38:12','2015-02-22 13:38:12','Hikers in  mountains','Hiking','','inherit','open','open','','hiking','','','2015-02-22 13:38:12','2015-02-22 13:38:12','',102,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Hiking-Tips-On-Packing-a-Backpack.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(105,1,'2015-02-25 01:15:44','2015-02-25 01:15:44','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome areas out west are moving to ban hunters from using drones to find game. While most sportsmen consider it cheating, lawmakers are deliberating over how to deal with these new gadgets.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Who would regulate it?</strong>\r\nHunting game from the air was outlawed in federal law in 1959. The use of commercial drones for private purposes has become hugely popular in recent years, which is why wildlife rangers are addressing the issue now to clarify the guidelines before it gets out of control, and everyone adds drones to their hunting gear list. Banning the use of these unmanned aircrafts would be a decision left to government authorities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What is the issue at stake?</strong>\r\nThe current law states that is against the law to hunt until 2 days after conducting a scout by air - a “fair game” ethics honored by most game sportsmen.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n$$$. The state reports that hunting yields virtually four hundred mil each year via permit costs, attire, product revenue, accommodations and other associated activities. A ban on drone hunting accessories would cost outfitters and sporting good stores a lot of money. The animals, however are largely in favor of the ban.\r\n<strong>When are they looking to implement these laws?</strong>\r\nPreliminary votes are underway. If passed, the ban would be included as a modification of current hunting regulations.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Why do people care?</strong>\r\nMost people think of the US army using drones for counter terrorism during wartime, but they’re becoming increasingly popular among law enforcement and other gov departments. The issue of privacy has prompted some states to limit their use, even by these agencies. Specifically with regard to hunting, some people just think it’s plain unfair and takes the sportsmanship out of the game.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>How do we regulate the use of drones?</strong>\r\nSome folks are already holding protests about the issue, asking for legislation mandating an additional tax on special drone hunting permits. Not long after introducing the idea to a small town outside of Denver, checks came pouring in from people trying to acquire one of these licenses – an unexpected and unfortunate backfire for those protesting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe deliberations to permit these licenses are ongoing, however the issue has already been disputed in the courtroom – opposing hunters arguing that denying their privilege to use drones would be a criminal offense.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThat just leaves the question of where..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Where does one draw the line between cheating and “fair game”?</strong>\r\n\r\nWhat’s your opinion?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor deals on solid hunting gear from the best brands, check out BlackOvis: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/uzmc57\">http://goo.gl/uzmc57</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','On the Hunt: Is it fair to use hunting drones to track prey?','','publish','open','open','','on-the-hunt-is-it-fair-to-use-hunting-drones-to-track-prey','','','2015-03-06 22:53:44','2015-03-06 22:53:44','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=105',0,'post','',0),(106,1,'2015-02-22 13:41:37','2015-02-22 13:41:37','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome hunting areas out west are considering putting a ban on hunters preventing them from using drones to find game. Lawmakers are deliberating over how to deal with these new gadgets.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Who would regulate it?</strong>\r\nHunting game from the air was outlawed in federal law in 1959. The use of commercial drones for private purposes has become hugely popular in recent years, which is why wildlife rangers are addressing the issue now to clarify the guidelines before it gets out of control. Banning the use of these unmanned aircrafts would be a decision left to government authorities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What is the issue at stake?</strong>\r\nOther than the fact that using drones to hunt game is kind of, well, cheating (in an ethical sense) the state reports that hunting yields virtually four hundred mil each year via permit costs, attire, product revenue, accommodations and other associated activities. A ban on this type of gear would undoubtedly make more than a few people unhappy (although it would be a win for the animals).\r\nThe current law states that is against the law to hunt until 2 days after conducting a scout by air – this, in accordance with the “fair game” ethics honored by most game sportsmen.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>When are they looking to implement these laws?</strong>\r\nPreliminary votes are expected to take place sometime early next year. If passed, the ban would be included as a modification of current hunting regulations.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Why do people care?</stro