,'','writing-internship-with-live-out-the-outdoor-social-network','','\nhttp://liveout.org/blog/make-new-friends-discover-best-places-go-outdoors-live-out/','2015-03-06 21:41:43','2015-03-06 21:41:43','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=124',0,'post','',0),(125,1,'2015-02-22 14:04:11','2015-02-22 14:04:11','\r\n\r\nAre you looking for an exciting marketing internship working with a team of creative, hard working entrepreneurs? Interested in working virtually, setting your own hours, and helping to promote a new social media web app?  \r\n\r\nLive Out is seeking marketing and social media interns to work remotely. This position is unpaid, but offers exceptional resume-building and networking opportunities.  \r\n\r\nThis opportunity is open to those seeking hands on experience. This is an unpaid internship for college credit if desired. We will work with your school  / academic adviser to help you fulfill college credit if needed but please let us know prior to the beginning of your internship so that we can coordinate appropriately with your school.  \r\n\r\nQualifications \r\nInterns applying for this internship should be marketing, business, journalism or new media and communications majors with experience with writing, blogging, and a solid understanding of social media. Must be a dedicated, responsible, creative, articulate, personable and an organized self-starter. The applicant should possess excellent writing and communications skills, be detail oriented and be able to work on a variety of projects simultaneously. Other characteristics we\'re looking for include: \r\n\r\n- Passion for outdoor activities \r\n- Proactive go-getter with an entrepreneurial spirit, high energy, fun, positive can-do attitude and work-ethic \r\n- Excellent communication skills – verbal and written \r\n- Reliable, detail-oriented and extremely motivated \r\n- Honesty, hard work (doing your best) and willingness to learn  \r\n\r\nAdvantages \r\n- Work from comfort of your home \r\n- Set your own hours \r\n- No soul-crushing office maintenance work \r\n\r\nInterested in working with Live Out? \r\ninternships@liveout.org\r\n\r\n\r\nSEO URL:\r\nMeta Keywords:\r\nSEO Title:\r\nMeta Description:\r\n','Want to be a Writer for Live Out?','','inherit','open','open','','124-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 14:04:11','2015-02-22 14:04:11','',124,'http://localhost/blog/124-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(126,1,'2015-02-25 19:40:14','2015-02-25 19:40:14','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI recently read a story on daredevil Jeb Corliss’ Flying Dagger jump - pretty wild. After jumping from a helicopter in a flying squirrel suit he threaded his way through a narrow fissure between two mountain peaks rising 2,677 feet at speeds of nearly 200 miles per hour. The crevice runs 900 feet long and bends and turns between two giant rocks 15 to 60 feet apart. He emerged from the cracks, narrowly escaping death only to realize that he needed to deploy his parachute at full speed otherwise he would miss the only landing zone he had.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe described the experience on Facebook:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I covered 3 football fields in 5 seconds and at about half way the walls were about 25ft wide. I had to sideslip as I flew because the crack was crooked and there was turbulence. I had to pull as I exited the crack in full flight or I would not make it to the only landing area that was behind me. Once I committed to the landing area there were no outs.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis got me thinking: Why do we do stuff like this? What is it about risk taking that’s so appealing? Are we chasing a high? Are some of us just born with a risky appetite? Why has this urge evolved? Why do some of us feel the need to be flying daggers while others are content to ride the pine and watch from the sidelines?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI did a little Googling and found a few common factors.. Sorry the length.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo preface, you can’t just just lump people into two categories: risk takers vs risk avoiders. That would be an oversimplification. There are categories of risk taking behaviors and people’s tendencies can be different depending on the type. You might love scuba diving with sharks but you are scared shitless of public speaking. People are complex and lots of interrelated factors come into play.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are all kinds of risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>- Financial. </strong>The gamblers vs the penny-pinchers.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Health. </strong>The vegan vs Eric Cartman from South Park.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Recreational. </strong>The flying dagger vs the benchwarmer.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Ethical. </strong>Honest Abe vs the liar.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Social. </strong>The hermit vs the party animal.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne study at the University of Michigan categorized risk into evolutionary terms: competition with other individuals; competition with other groups; mating and allocating resources for mate attraction; environmental risks; and fertility risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we don’t live in Jurassic Park days and have to worry about becoming T-Rex’s next meal but we do continue to live in a world with complex challenges involving other people and material investments much like our ancestors. The basics of our social environment hasn’t changed much.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGender. The kinds of risk taking is influenced by the kinds of risks our ancestors experienced throughout many thousands of years of evolution. In a general sense, men are more inclined to be risk takers than women. Men compete for social status and resources to entice mates. Men have far more intra-sexual competition than women do for sex, so they have to sell their sexual fitness with overt and adventurous exploits. Even today the pressure is on men to win women over through acts of bravery and strength. Ever notice how your buddy all of the sudden acts different when a hot girls walk into the bar? Maybe he puffs his chest out or something. I call it peacocking. Men tend to take more recreational and financial risks, but when it comes to risks that threatened fertility women are not impressed. Sorry star of the show ‘Ow, my balls’ - girls don’t think it’s as funny as guys.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile women have a tendency to conduct themselves more responsibly and make restrained decisions, they also take risks. Women tend to take more social risks than men, for instance they may be more likely to switch careers late in life or voice unpopular viewpoints in business conferences. They also take recreational risks and risks related to social status in one’s group. The need to impress does go both ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Age</strong>\r\n\r\nYounger people take more risks, maybe because of hormone levels or just the fact that they have less life experience and less working knowledge of the consequences of their actions.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Relationships</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople tend to seek less risks as they age and enter into stable relationships. Relationship status can actually be a strong predictor in risk-taking behavior. Men’s testosterone level can shoot up again after a divorce and they become more risky.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Chemistry</strong>\r\n\r\nSome scientists point to neurotransmitters levels in the brain to explain risk taking. If you have an imbalance of dopamine, you are more likely to take risks that give you that ‘rush feeling’ because it restores your brain’s chemical balance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Perception</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you perceive a certain behavior as risky, you are less likely to do it. If you are optimistic, you are also more likely to do it. Some people don’t think the rules apply to them because they perceive a high level of control of situations.\r\nIs optimism good if it leads to risk taking?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Pride/ Gratification</strong>\r\n\r\nTaking risks and overcoming challenges can be very gratifying. This alone could be enough to tip the scales towards risky behavior.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I have been jumping for over 15 years and I have never done anything more committing and technical in my life. I am so happy” - Jeb Corliss, after his Flying Dagger jump.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Desperation</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople are more likely to engage in risky behavior when they are desperate. If your or someone you love’s life is on the line, there’s probably not much you wouldn’t do.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Conclusion</strong>\r\n\r\nDespite the many factors that come into play, there are definitely some patterns. An individual’s inclination to take risks correlates with their level of perceived benefit and the level of perceived danger. What’s funny is that as life becomes more cushy in the 21st century, we keep on pushing the limits just to keep this threshold in balance. They invent the airbag, we invented Nascar. They invent the parachute, we jump out of planes in squirrel suits for fun. It seems crazy sometimes, why we take risks. Maybe it’s essential, just a necessary part of life that keeps us moving forward and challenging ourselves to seek new heights, ensuring mankind’s progression as a whole and bringing about our most remarkable successes most devastating failures.. I don’t know, what do you think?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re someone who likes to take risks &amp; do fun stuff, check out our friends at Nectar Shades:<a href=\"%20http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/\"> http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/</a>. They’re all about doin’ epic shit &amp; lookin’ good while you’re at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFeel free to leave some comments below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Scott McGuire\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Risk Taking: Why do we take risks?','','publish','open','open','','risk-taking-why-do-we-take-risks','','','2015-03-06 21:48:45','2015-03-06 21:48:45','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=126',0,'post','',0),(127,1,'2015-02-22 14:43:20','2015-02-22 14:43:20','Why do we take risks?\r\n\r\nI read a story recently on daredevil Jeb Corliss’ most recent wing-suiting endeavor he appropriately nicknamed the “Flying Dagger.” After jumping from a helicopter in a flying squirrel suit he proceeded to thread his way through a narrow fissure between two limestone-conglomerate mountain peaks rising 2,677 ft. at speeds of nearly 200 miles per hour. The crevice runs 900-feet long and bends and turns creating a width that ranges between 15 to 60 feet. He emerged from the cracks, narrowly escaping death only to realize that he needed to to deploy his parachute in full flight – otherwise he would miss the only landing zone he had.\r\n\r\nHe describes the experience on his Facebook page:\r\n\r\n“I covered 3 football fields in 5 seconds and at about half way the walls were about 25ft wide. I had to sideslip as I flew because the crack was crooked and there was turbulence. I had to pull as I exited the crack in full flight or I would not make it to the only landing area that was behind me. Once I committed to the landing area there were no outs.”\r\n\r\nYouTube is packed with videos like this, and it got me to thinking: Why do people take risks? Many people feel the same urge Corliss felt: the desire to venture past the limits of safety in pursuit of a rewarding and highly gratifying experience – but not many of us feel the need to jump out of a helicopter in a wing-suit for god’s sake!\r\n\r\nCorliss was fortunate to make it back alive: Sometimes risky appetites can be fatal, as exemplified by the volume of deadly wing-suiting incidents lately. Certainly, extreme risk-taking drastically lowers one’s life expectancy. Why then has this urge evolved? Precisely what explains the variations in what each of us is ready to wager? Why is it that some people experience the impulse to snowboard down a volcano while others are scared of the Mad Tea Party ride at DisneyWorld? For some, taking risks is almost a need- while others are content to “ride the pine” so to speak and simply watch from the sidelines.\r\n\r\nSo I did a little research on the subject and have identified some common factors among some of the explanations I found.\r\n\r\nPreface\r\n\r\nThe following speculation on risk taking from an evolutionary perspective is based on a study by researchers at The University of Michigan that was recently published in the Journal of Evolutionary Psychology. It that refutes the idea  that you can just lump people into two categories: Risk Taking vs. Risk Avoiding. People are more complicated than this and it would be an oversimplification to pigeonhole everyone into just two categories. A person’s risk tendency in one category suggests very little about their predisposition in another. You might have a skydiver who’s afraid of public speaking, or a guy who’s not scared to scuba dive with the sharks but can’t stand up to his boss. People are complex and many inter-related factors come into play when it comes to explaining our decisions.\r\nTypes of Risk\r\n\r\nThere are all kinds of risks. Natalie Wolchover, of Life’s Little Mysteries categorizes them into: Financial, health/safety, recreational, ethical and social risks. The commentary that follows regarding these types of risks is based on interpretation of her research.\r\n\r\nThe University of Michigan Research study took an evolutionary approach and categorized risk into: Competition with other individuals; competition with other groups; mating and allocating resources for mate attraction; environmental risks (chasing a bear or skydiving); and fertility risks.\r\n\r\nAlthough in many areas of the world, threats from potential predators is confined to those people going on wild expeditions, we continue to live in a world with intricate challenges involving other people and material investments – so you will see the kinds of risks encountered by our ancestry and family history are actually quite similar to the ones we face today. The fundamental aspects of our social environment haven’t changed; we simply live on a significantly larger scale.\r\n\r\nFactors\r\nGender/ Evolution\r\n\r\nMen\r\nThe kinds of risk taking is influenced by the kinds of risks our ancestors experienced throughout many thousands of years of evolution. Studies show that in many areas, men are more inclined to be risk takers than women. Throughout history, men competed for social status and resources as a way to entice mates – Guys have far more intra-sexual competition than girls do for sex, so they have to sell their sexual fitness by way of adventurous exploits and do so more overtly. Even today the pressure is on men to win women over through acts of “boldness and strength.” This would certainly explain why your buddy all of the sudden changes his behavior when a girl walks into the bar. Interestingly, this was not discovered to be true with regards to risks that threatened fertility – as these sorts of antics are not impressive to the ladies (for obvious reasons) – this, being unfortunate for the star of the show “Ow, my balls”. Wolchover’s research shows that men are more likely to take recreational risks and financial risks.\r\n\r\nWomen\r\nWhile women have a tendency to conduct themselves responsibly and make restrained decisions, they also take risks. Studies show that they tend to take more social risks than men; for instance, they may be more likely to switch careers late in life or voice unpopular viewpoints in business conferences. They so also take recreational risks – and take risks related to social status in one’s group – after all, the need to impress does go both ways.\r\n\r\nAge\r\nYounger people tend to take more risks, bottom line. This could have something to do with increased hormone levels or just the fact that they have less life experience and less working knowledge of the consequences of their actions.\r\n\r\nRelationships\r\nResearch indicates that people become less risk-seeking as they age and as they enter into stable relationships, Interestingly, relationship status can actually be a strong predictor in risk-taking behavior. Men’s testosterone level can shoot up again upon getting a divorce, and they again become more risk-prone.\r\n\r\nChemistry\r\nSome scientists point to levels of certain neurotransmitters in the brain to explain risk taking. If you have an imbalance of dopamine, you are more likely to take risks that give you that “rush feeling” and thus restoring your brain’s chemical balance.\r\n\r\nPerception\r\nIf you perceive a certain behavior as risky, you are less likely to do it. If you are optimistic, you are also more likely to do it. Some people don’t think the “rules” apply to them because they perceive themselves as having more control over the situation as others.\r\nThis begs the question: Is optimism good if it leads to risk taking?\r\n\r\nPride/ Gratification\r\nThere’s also a certain level of gratification involved when it comes to the feeling one gets after taking a risk and succeeding in overcoming the challenge. This alone could be enough to tip the scales towards risky behavior in some.\r\n\r\n“I have been jumping for over 15 years and I have never done anything more committing and technical in my life. I am so happy” - Jeb Corliss, after his famous “Flying Dagger” jump.\r\n\r\nI might also throw in…\r\nDesperation\r\nPeople are more likely to engage in risky behavior when they are desperate.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nDespite the many factors that play into risk taking,  people do still follow a somewhat predictable pattern. As it turns out, within a particular domain, an individual’s propensity to take risks correlates with their level of perceived benefit. Risk-taking can bring about remarkable success or devastating failure, and is therefore an essential facet of the human condition\r\n\r\nTo a certain extent however, people’s risk tendency is somewhat inherent and constant – it’s almost as if we all have built in danger thresholds that we must keep in balance. We’ve shown a natural trend, as life has become more and more safe and “cushy” in the 21st century, to keep on pushing the limits just to keep this threshold in balance. They invent the airbag, so now we decide it’s ok to drive faster. They invent the parachute, so now we’ve got to jump out of a plane. It seems a little crazy sometimes why we take risks, but perhaps it’s just a necessary part of life that keeps us moving forward and challenging ourselves to seek new heights, ensuring mankind’s progression as a whole.\r\nIf you have an explanation that was not listed here (and I’m sure there are many), please share them with us in the comment section below!\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n','','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 14:43:20','2015-02-22 14:43:20','',126,'http://localhost/blog/126-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(128,1,'2015-02-22 14:44:38','2015-02-22 14:44:38','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI read a story recently on daredevil Jeb Corliss’ most recent wing-suiting endeavor he appropriately nicknamed the “Flying Dagger.” After jumping from a helicopter in a flying squirrel suit he proceeded to thread his way through a narrow fissure between two limestone-conglomerate mountain peaks rising 2,677 ft. at speeds of nearly 200 miles per hour. The crevice runs 900-feet long and bends and turns creating a width that ranges between 15 to 60 feet. He emerged from the cracks, narrowly escaping death only to realize that he needed to to deploy his parachute in full flight – otherwise he would miss the only landing zone he had.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe describes the experience on his Facebook page:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I covered 3 football fields in 5 seconds and at about half way the walls were about 25ft wide. I had to sideslip as I flew because the crack was crooked and there was turbulence. I had to