ve Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>','Winter Camping Tips','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 17:40:41','2015-02-22 17:40:41','',133,'http://localhost/blog/133-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2015-02-22 17:57:41','2015-02-22 17:57:41','','Winter Camping Tips','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2015-02-22 17:57:41','2015-02-22 17:57:41','',133,'http://localhost/blog/133-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(138,1,'2015-02-22 17:58:04','2015-02-22 17:58:04','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for things to do this winter? Go camping! Camping in cold weather is not as hard as you may think. The key is creating a comfortable environment so everyone is a happy camper. This includes getting there safely, staying hydrated, eating well and frequently (s’mores count), staying warm at night, and sleeping comfortably.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTRAVEL\r\nYou’ll need a solid ride to get in and out of the backcountry in good shape - ideally, something with 4 wheel drive and a winch in case you get stuck. Before you set out on your adventure, there are some basic precautions to consider. First of all, make sure your car battery is in good condition. If it’s questionable, go ahead and replace it - better safe than sorry. Same goes for your oil - make sure you’re not over your miles and you might want to bring an extra quart just in case. You’ll want to choose a thinner oil in the winter; 5w30 should do just fine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHYDRATE\r\nYour body’s metabolism has to work harder in the winter just to stay warm, so staying hydrated by drinking plenty of water is crucial. It might also be a good idea to keep a bottle on your person inside of your jacket so it doesn’t freeze. Clean snow (not the yellow stuff) can also a good water source, and if you’re uncertain about its purity, throw some in a large pot and boil it up.10 qt of snow makes about 1 qt of water.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEAT\r\nYour body expends more energy in cold temperatures