on the go. Carbs are energy dense and best for a quick boost. Peanut butter crackers, cheese, granola bars, beef jerky, and trail mix make excellent solid trail foods high in calories and protein. Keep an eye on your sodium intake with these items though, as too much will dehydrate you. Chicken noodle soup is great for dinner. It provides instant warmth and will keep your metabolism going for hours as protein energy is released throughout the night. You can buy it in dehydrated form which is super lightweight and all you have to do is add hot water. If you get the dehydrated stuff, open the package to let the excess air out and seal it back up - these can take up a ton of empty space in your pack if you don’t.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSLEEP\r\nCots are good for keeping off the hard ground in the summertime but in the winter the cold air that flows beneath will keep you chilly and uncomfortable all night. Try stacking a few sleeping mats. I prefer Therm-A-Rest, but you can also stack egg-crate foam or mix and match other mats to your comfort. Definitely sleep in insulation – mummy bags are great because they trap your body heat inside. To be safe, choose a sleeping bag with a rating 15 degrees below the coldest temperatures you expect to face. Bundle up with beanies, socks, long johns, and light fabric gloves. Be sure to keep your boots in a pack and bring them inside your bag so they don’t ice overnight. And if you really feel like spoiling yourself with comfort, you can wrap rocks in aluminum foil and keep them near the fire (careful, not too close) to allow them to get warm over the course of the night, then place them by your feet inside the tent and they’ll stay warm all night.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlrighty then, hope this helps a bit. CampSaver always has some great deals on camping essentials - like the sleeping mat, mummy bag, and warm winter gear if you need stuff. Here’s a link: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz\">http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow get out there and live out - you’re burnin’ daylight!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Winter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 16:00:51','2015-02-25 16:00:51','',133,'http://localhost/blog/133-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(168,1,'2015-02-25 16:01:18','2015-02-25 16:01:18','Camping tent on mountain with snow. ','Winter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather','','inherit','open','open','','tent-on-snow-2','','','2015-02-25 16:03:13','2015-02-25 16:03:13','',133,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Winter-Camping-Tips_How-to-Camp-in-Cold-Weather-.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(169,1,'2015-02-25 16:11:39','2015-02-25 16:11:39','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFinding the right activity for someone with aspergers can be a great way to manage the disorder. Geocaching allows those with autism to utilize their unique minds and improve their social skills at the same time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger\'s understands the complex challenges these men and women face in life. Those with Aspergers often have difficulties in social situations as well as repetitive behavior patterns and interests. They also tend to have extremely high IQ’s as a result of their dedication to their intense interests.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCertain careers and hobbies are more common among those with autism - those that involve technology, small environments, and few people. This is why Geocaching can be a great activity for those with Aspergers and other LD’s in the autism spectrum because it challenges them to use to exercise their sharp minds and encourages participation in group activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreation activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers called “geocaches” all over the world - like a real world treasure hunt. It’s one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks. Some parks are now even offering workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this relatively new activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual. You have to piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete interrelated challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you have to create a puzzle and leaving clues so people can follow your coordinates and find the treasure - or geocache. The acute problem solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers is precisely why they might love and be good at geocaching. It’s challenging, fulfilling, and it opens new opportunities to make new friends with the same interests and spend time outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers or other autism spectrum learning disabilities, you might gently recommend geocaching. There are places online where you can meet and make new friends who like these types of outdoor activities too. Try Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps someone. You can get all the geocaching stuff you need at Mountain Gear: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/zkeQYf\">http://goo.gl/zkeQYf</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGood luck!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOriginal Article: <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/breaking-through-&lt;strong&gt;aspergers&lt;/strong&gt;-with-&lt;strong&gt;geocaching&lt;/strong&gt;/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/breaking-through-<strong>aspergers</strong>-with-<strong>geocaching</strong>/</a>','Managing Aspergers With Geocaching','','inherit','open','open','','86-revisi