trong>-drones-to-track-prey/</a>','On the Hunt: Is it fair to use hunting drones to track prey?','','inherit','open','open','','105-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 16:35:10','2015-02-25 16:35:10','',105,'http://localhost/blog/105-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2015-02-25 16:37:15','2015-02-25 16:37:15','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFinding the right activity for someone with Aspergers can be a great way to manage the disorder. Geocaching allows those with autism to utilize their unique minds and improve their social skills at the same time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger\'s understands the complex challenges these men and women face in life. Those with Aspergers often have difficulties in social situations as well as repetitive behavior patterns and interests. They also tend to have extremely high IQ’s as a result of their dedication to their intense interests.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCertain careers and hobbies are more common among those with autism - those that involve technology, small environments, and few people. This is why Geocaching can be a great activity for those with Aspergers and other LD’s in the autism spectrum because it challenges them to use to exercise their sharp minds and encourages participation in group activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreation activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers called “geocaches” all over the world - like a real world treasure hunt. It’s one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks. Some parks are now even offering workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this relatively new activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual. You have to piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete interrelated challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you have to create a puzzle and leaving clues so people can follow your coordinates and find the treasure - or geocache. The acute problem solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers is precisely why they might love and be good at geocaching. It’s challenging, fulfilling, and it opens new opportunities to make new friends with the same interests and spend time outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers or other autism spectrum learning disabilities, you might gently recommend geocaching. There are places online where you can meet and make new friends who like these types of outdoor activities too. Try Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps someone. You can get all the geocaching stuff you need at Mountain Gear: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/zkeQYf\">http://goo.gl/zkeQYf</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGood luck!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOriginal Article: <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/breaking-through-&lt;strong&gt;aspergers&lt;/strong&gt;-with-&lt;strong&gt;geocaching&lt;/strong&gt;/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/breaking-through-aspergers-with-geocaching/</a>','Managing Aspergers With Geocaching','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 16:37:15','2015-02-25 16:37:15','',86,'http://localhost/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(185,1,'2015-02-25 16:41:06','2015-02-25 16:41:06','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFinding the right activity for someone with Aspergers can be a great way to manage the disorder. Geocaching allows those with autism to utilize their unique minds and improve their social skills at the same time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger\'s understands the complex challenges these men and women face in life. Those with Aspergers often have difficulties in social situations as well as repetitiv