g 15 degrees below the coldest temperatures you expect to face. Bundle up with beanies, socks, long johns, and light fabric gloves. Be sure to keep your boots in a pack and bring them inside your bag so they don’t ice overnight. And if you really feel like spoiling yourself with comfort, you can wrap rocks in aluminum foil and keep them near the fire (careful, not too close) to allow them to get warm over the course of the night, then place them by your feet inside the tent and they’ll stay warm all night.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlrighty then, hope this helps a bit. CampSaver always has some great deals on camping essentials - like the sleeping mat, mummy bag, and warm winter gear if you need stuff. Here’s a link: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz\">http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow get out there and live out - you’re burnin’ daylight!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRelated article:\r\n\r\nOriginal article:<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/\"> http://localhost/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/</a>','Winter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 17:22:04','2015-02-25 17:22:04','',133,'http://localhost/blog/133-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(203,1,'2015-02-25 17:26:22','2015-02-25 17:26:22','CampSaver deals on camping and hiking gear.','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Deal_Camping and Hiking_CampSaver','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal_camping-and-hiking_campsaver','','','2015-02-25 17:26:53','2015-02-25 17:26:53','',133,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal_Camping-and-Hiking_CampSaver.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(204,1,'2015-02-25 17:26:54','2015-02-25 17:26:54','&