utdoor Social Network','','inherit','open','open','','hiking-2','','','2015-02-25 18:13:26','2015-02-25 18:13:26','',102,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Hiking-Tips-How-to-Pack-a-Backpack-Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(211,1,'2015-02-25 18:13:52','2015-02-25 18:13:52','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPacking a backpack when planning a hiking or camping trip isn’t rocket science, but there are some important things to consider when loading up your outdoor gear. When you’re carrying upwards of fifty pounds on your back for days at a time, it pays to put some thought into what to bring and how to pack it! Things like weight distribution, conservation of space, and convenience are all important things to consider.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Convenience</strong>\r\nFirst, let’s talk about the logistics. Anything you don’t plan on using until night or later on in the trip can be stowed away in the bottom of the pack. Items that belong at the bottom are things like your sleeping bag, heavy clothing that you won’t use until sundown, dinner cooking utensils, and other things you’ll only need once you set up camp at the end of the day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou’ll find it is convenient to keep items that you might need at a moments notice at the top of your pack or in an easily accessible side pouch. You don’t want to have to go rooting around every time you stop just to grab that 5 Hour Energy or bag of sunflower seeds. Things like water, snacks, first aid supplies, a flashlight or headlamp, and a rain jacket, should all be kept somewhere when you can reach them easily.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDistribution\r\nDistributing weight is also key. It is important to spread out heavier items throughout your pack to avoid stress or injury. Too much weight at the bottom of your pack will take a toll on your lower back, while too much weight up top will put too much strain on your shoulders. It also helps to try to keep the heavier items closer to your back, that way they’re not constantly pulling the pack away from you. Adjust the straps to put more weight on your hips and less on your shoulders.\r\n\r\nNote: Clothing can be used to separate items and achieve a more balanced weight distribution.\r\n\r\nConservation\r\nConservation of space is also very important to consider, as just getting everything to fit can be a challenge. Some tips:\r\n\r\nShare gear. Try to share gear with your hiking partner to eliminate duplication. If you do this though, be sure to stick close! You don’t want them wandering off with the map, food and water.\r\n\r\nOnly take the essentials. You might not know exactly what you’ll need or use in advance until you’ve been on several hikes, but until then it’s probably best to play it safe. Better safe than sorry! Things NOT to skimp on: A good sleeping pad &amp; clean socks!\r\n\r\nAttach gear. Grab a couple carabiners before you go and attach some gear to the outside of your pack.\r\n\r\nCompress. Try to find compressible gear – there’s a lot of really light, warm, and compressible gear out there and lot of this stuff is becoming more and more affordable. If you haven’t updated your hiking arsenal in the past two decades, it might save your pack and your back to look into some new outdoor equipment.\r\n\r\nWater on the sides. Carry your water on the sides of your pack. You can even replace hard water bottles with collapsible reservoirs, which will help with the weight factor.\r\n\r\nRepackage food. Sometimes prepackaged backpacking meals can take up a huge amount of space with mostly empty air space inside the bag. Take the food out and repackage it yourself to minimize the space it takes up. Also, try to pack calorie dense food like nuts, dried fruit, and oatmeal to maximize the calories you’re getting per ounce of weight.\r\n\r\nRoll your clothes. When it comes to packing clothing, you can save space and fit more into your pack by rolling up your clothes. Rolling compresses clothes better than folding.\r\nTip: You can fit your socks in that extra pair of boots you’re carrying.\r\n\r\nOk guys, hope these tips on how to pack a backpack have helped. While it’s not overly complex, it does help to plan a little to avoid unnecessary discomfort that might take away from your backpacking experience. Here’s a link to some good deals on Mountain Gear hiking supplies if you need stuff: http://goo.gl/4JQRqo.\r\n\r\nCheers.\r\n\r\nArticle by Ryan Quinn\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\nhttp://www.liveout.org/','Hiking Tips: How to Pack a Backpack','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 18:13:52','2015-02-25 18:13:52','',102,'http://localhost/blog/102-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(212,1,'2015-02-25 18:15:51','2015-02-25 18:15:51','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPacking a backpack when planning a hiking or camping trip isn’t rocket science, but there are some important things to consider when loading up your outdoor gear. When you’re carrying upwards of fifty pounds on your back for days at a time, it pays to put some thought into what to bring and how to pack it! Things like weight distribution, conservation of space, and convenience are all important things to consider.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Convenience</strong>\r\nFirst, let’s talk about the logistics. Anything you don’t plan on using until night or later on in the trip can be stowed away in the bottom of the pack. Items that belong at the bottom are things like your sleeping bag, heavy clothing that you won’t use until sundown, dinner cooking utensils, and other things you’ll only need once you set up camp at the end of the day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou’ll find it is convenient to keep items that you might need at a moments notice at the top of your pack or in an easily accessible side pouch. You don’t want to have to go rooting around every time you stop just to grab that 5 Hour Energy or bag of sunflower seeds. Things like water, snacks, first aid supplies,