\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBringing your phone with you on a hike is probably a good idea just to be safe, even if you’re trying to unplug for a bit and just enjoy the outdoors. <strong>The Gaia GPS ($19.99)</strong> is cool because it allows you to download maps to your phone before you hit the trail so you can still find places to hike even if you lose reception - very helpful. It includes topo and street maps of the US and Canada and it allows you to document, track and geo-tag your photos. You can search for through points, modify units and coordinate types, and back everything up to the Cloud so you don’t have to worry about losing your data.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Columbia’s GPS Pal (Free)</strong> is clutch for serious hikers. The app is designed for recording details from your hiking experience. You can use photos, videos, or notes to tag your favorite locations. It even tracks your path via GPS, recording your elevation, distance and time so you can save your hikes and upload them to sites like Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you like to seek new heights, the <strong>Point de Vue ($3.99)</strong> might be the most practical hiking app for you. It provides a great deal of information about the mountains around you like their distance from you, their elevation, and peak (if you’ve ever had that weary “Are we there yet?” feeling, you can see how this might come in handy).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nA less expensive alternative but similar to the Gaia GPS is the <strong>EveryTrailPro ($3.99)</strong>. User friendly and packed with great hikes, it allows you to take video and picture of your trip to record your journey and is loaded with over 400,000 trails. You can even record audio notes for a more detailed account of your journey.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>AllTrails (Free)</strong> is especially helpful to find new trails to hike. It doesn’t provide the actual topo maps, but it will help you find some great trails in your area. It gives you tons of useful information like user ratings, difficulty, distances, elevations and path type. If you’re just looking to find new places to hike, this might be all you need.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you just want to log your hikes and aren’t concerned about topographical info or other technical data, try <strong>iMapMyHike (Free)</strong>. The app is simple, but sufficient for tracking your trips.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTrails (Free) is an ok alternative to the <strong>AllTrails</strong> app. It gives you the trail maps with a paid subscription, but some users have complained about it not being user-friendly and having too many ads.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>MotionX GPS ($1.99)</strong> is highly attractive for outdoor fans. It allows you to download road and terrain maps, and even marine charts for free. The app is fantastic, but some of the other apps are more comprehensive if you’re looking for something specifically for hiking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Live Out (Free)</strong> Live Out is a new social network / outdoors app that can help you find places to go hiking in your area and connect with other hikers nearby. Not only is it a good trail finder, it’s also social network for people who enjoy outdoor activities. It’s more about helping you to find fun things to do as well as other people near you based on your common outdoor interests. You can search for other hikers in your area and message them directly, which comes in handy when your usual hiking buddies are busy and you’re trying to make plans on short notice. The app has several other features that are worth exploring too, like the bucket list. The bucket list helps you find great places to travel to and the people to live out your ideas with. Live Out is free to join and can be found at <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWell, there you have it. Hope this hiking app review was helpful, you might start with the free ones and if they don’t have what you need then try the paid. <strong>CampSaver</strong> always has some good deals going on for hiking gear if you need stuff: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/nTOLvT\">http://goo.gl/nTOLvT</a>. Now stop staring at your screen, put on your hiking boots and get out there and hike the Appalachian Trail or something!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nOutdoor Enthusiast &amp; Writer\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Related articles</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFive National Parks Great For Outdoor Activities To Add To Your Bucket List\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/five-national-parks-great-for-outdoor-activities-to-add-to-your-bucket-list/\">http://localhost/blog/five-national-parks-great-for-outdoor-activities-to-add-to-your-bucket-list/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHiking Tips: How to Pack a Backpack\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/hiking-tips-how-to-pack-a-backpack/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/hiking-tips-how-to-pack-a-backpack/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Most Important Backpacking Traits\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/important-backpacking-traits/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/important-backpacking-traits/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWinter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/</a>','Best Hiking Apps to Find Local Hikes','','inherit','open','open','','73-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 21:45:34','2015-02-25 21:45:34','',73,'http://localhost/blog/73-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(285,1,'2015-02-25 21:53:43','2015-02-25 21:53:43','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for fun places to visit for outdoor activities this spring? With fifty-eight to choose from, it can be difficult to pick just which national park to explore next. Spread all over the country, these exquisitely preserved swaths of nature allow for the perfect break from the stress of everyday life. The greatest aspect of America’s National Parks is that there are parks to represent nearly every environment and climate imaginable. So to help you narrow down your options for your next trip, here are five National Parks to add to your bucket list.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-95\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\" alt=\"Yosemite National Park\" width=\"400\" height=\"267\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Yosemite National Park, California</strong>\r\n\r\nYosemite easily makes its way onto this list if for no other reason that it is an icon of a National Park and a go-to destination for outdoor activities. It was formally designated as a national park over 120 years ago and its beautiful scenery lead to its declaration as UNESECO World Heritage Sight in 1984. Few other places in the world can offer such views as those offered by the towering granite cliffs that drop off into the endless forests of Yosemite.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlso, about 95% of the park’s 1,880 square miles is designated as wilderness. So despite the high amount of visitors that come to Yosemite each year, if you’re looking to get completely lost (metaphorically speaking, of course) on a backpacking trek, you will have no problem doing so in such a vast expanse. It’s history, scenic landscapes, impressive size all come together to make this an absolute must see.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Zion-National-Park_-Utah_.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-96\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Zion-National-Park_-Utah_.jpg\" alt=\"Zion National Park\" width=\"400\" height=\"265\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Zion National Park, Utah</strong>\r\n\r\nZion should be high on any backpacker’s to-see list largely due to the gorgeous sights of emerald rivers that have carved out some impressively magnificent rock formations. Zion actually boasts a great deal of environmental diversity. Aside from the desert expanses and red rock caves that the park has become known for, the park also contains large sections of woodland and forested areas perfect for camping, hiking, and climbing. It’s variety in the ecosystems it offers is yet another reason to add Zion to your National Park bucketlist.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Acadia-National-Park_Maine.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-98\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Acadia-National-Park_Maine.jpg\" alt=\"Picturesque Acadia National Park Shoreline\" width=\"400\" height=\"256\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Acadia National Park, Maine</strong>\r\n\r\nArguably the natural gem of the East Coast, the iconic Acadia National Park is comprised of a series of heavily wooded islands off the coast of Maine. It’s considerably smaller than the other parks on the list, but it still offers great opportunities for camping nonetheless. Though it is small, the miles of coastline and the fact that it is located in one of the most beautiful scenic landscapes of the East Coast have given Acadia a reputation for providing some of the most memorable views imaginable.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Denali-National-Park_Alaska.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-99\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Denali-National-Park_Alaska.jpg\" alt=\"Lake on Alaska\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Denali National Park, Alaska</strong>\r\n\r\nAlaska just very well may be the most naturally beautiful state in America. Even if you only have the opportunity to travel in and around Anchorage, the most heavily populated area of the state, you will still be surrounded incredibly beautiful landscapes and fun things to do. There are endless opportunities for hiking, camping and fishing within short driving distance of the city. Though if you’re looking for a great area to go backpacking, Denali National Park is the place to go.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDenali is considerably larger than most other national parks. The park is actually bigger than the entire state of Massachusetts. It encompasses endless mountain ranges, valleys, rivers, woodlands and just one road. Also, it’s home to America’s largest mountain, Mt. McKinley. Even if you don’t make it to the summit of this 20,000-foot behemoth, it certainly provides for some spectacular scenery nonetheless.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Olympic-National-Park_-Washington.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-94\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Olympic-National-Park_-Washington.jpg\" alt=\"Olympik coast\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Olympic National Park, Washington</strong>\r\n\r\nLooking for things to do in Washington? If you’re trying to truly immerse yourself in the backcountry and make your escape from everyday life, Olympic National Park is the perfect place to do just that. Similar to Yosemite, 95% of this massive park is designated as wilderness. The few roads that are in the park barely penetrate this North American rainforest. And if you traverse to the west side of the park, 60 miles of isolated Pacific coastline await. Very few, if any other, parks offer rainforests, snowcapped mountains and pristine rocky shore beaches, which should make Olympic National Park a strong favorite for anyone who enjoys outdoor activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWell, there you have it. Some great places to visit to enjoy your favorite outdoor activities before you kick the bucket. You can make a bucket list and find people to live out your ideas with at Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network. For deals on outdoor gear, Patagonia is your best bet: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/0lSZvz\">http://goo.gl/0lSZvz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFeel free to share some of your best ideas for where to go in the comment section below!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Ryan Quinn\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Related articles</strong>\r\n\r\nHiking Tips: How to Pack a Backpack\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/hiking-tips-how-to-pack-a-backpack/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/hiking-tips-how-to-pack-a-backpack/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Most Important Backpacking Traits\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/important-backpacking-traits/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/important-backpacking-traits/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWinter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/winter-camping-tips-how-to-camp-in-cold-weather/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBest Hiking Apps to Find Local Hikes\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes\">http://www.liveout.org/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Five National Parks Great For Outdoor Activities To Add To Your Bucket List','','inherit','open','open','','93-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 21:53:43','2015-02-25 21:53:43','',93,'http://localhost/blog/93-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(286,1,'2015-02-25 22:14:57','2015-02-25 22:14:57','Are you looking for an exciting writing internship working with a team of creative, hard working entrepreneurs? Interested in working virtually, setting your own hours, and helping to promote a new social network &amp; app? If so, this could be the perfect opportunity for you to show off your creative writing skills.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out: The Outdoor Social Network is seeking people with strong writing skills to be contributors to the Live Out blog: <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog\">http://www.liveout.org/blog</a>. This position is unpaid, but offers exceptional resume-building experience, networking opportunities and exposure as a writer.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis opportunity is open to those seeking hands on experience. This is an unpaid internship for college credit if desired. We will work with your school / academic adviser to help you fulfill college credit if needed but please let us know prior to the beginning of your internship so that we can coordinate appropriately with your school.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Qualifications</strong>\r\nInterns applying for this internship should be marketing, business, journalism or new media and communications majors with experience with research, content writing, blogging and SEO. Must be a dedicated, responsible, creative, articulate, personable and an organized self-starter. The applicant should possess excellent writing and communications skills, be detail oriented and be able to contribute a minimum of one article per week. Other characteristics we\'re looking for include:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Passion &amp; knowledge for outdoor activities\r\n- Proactive go-getter with an entrepreneurial spirit, high energy, fun, positive can-do attitude and work-ethic\r\n- Reliable, detail-oriented and extremely motivated\r\n- Honesty, hard work (doing your best) and willingness to learn\r\n- Familiarity with Google’s Keyword Tool for SEO (preferred)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Advantages</strong>\r\n- Work remotely from comfort of your home\r\n- Set your own hours\r\n- No soul-crushing office maintenance work\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nInterested in a writing internship with Live Out? Tell us your story and why you would be a good fit.\r\n\r\nEmail us at blog@liveout.org\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Related articles</strong>\r\n\r\nMake new friends and discover the best places to go outdoors near you with Live Out 2.0\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/make-new-friends-discover-best-places-go-outdoors-live-out/\">http://localhost/blog/make-new-friends-discover-best-places-go-outdoors-live-out/</a>','Writing Internship With Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network','','inherit','open','open','','124-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 22:14:57','2015-02-25 22:14:57','',124,'http://localhost/blog/124-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(287,1,'2015-02-25 22:16:47','2015-02-25 22:16:47','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI recently read a story on daredevil Jeb Corliss’ Flying Dagger jump - pretty wild. After jumping from a helicopter in a flying squirrel suit he threaded his way through a narrow fissure between two mountain peaks rising 2,677 feet at speeds of nearly 200 miles per hour. The crevice runs 900 feet long and bends and turns between two giant rocks 15 to 60 feet apart. He emerged from the cracks, narrowly escaping death only to realize that he needed to deploy his parachute at full speed otherwise he would miss the only landing zone he had.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe described the experience on Facebook:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I covered 3 football fields in 5 seconds and at about half way the walls were about 25ft wide. I had to sideslip as I flew because the crack was crooked and there was turbulence. I had to pull as I exited the crack in full flight or I would not make it to the only landing area that was behind me. Once I committed to the landing area there were no outs.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis got me thinking: Why do we do stuff like this? What is it about risk taking that’s so appealing? Are we chasing a high? Are some of us just born with a risky appetite? Why has this urge evolved? Why do some of us feel the need to be flying daggers while others are content to ride the pine and watch from the sidelines?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI did a little Googling and found a few common factors.. Sorry the length.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo preface, you can’t just just lump people into two categories: risk takers vs risk avoiders. That would be an oversimplification. There are categories of risk taking behaviors and people’s tendencies can be different depending on the type. You might love scuba diving with sharks but you are scared shitless of public speaking. People are complex and lots of interrelated factors come into play.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are all kinds of risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>- Financial. </strong>The gamblers vs the penny-pinchers.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Health. </strong>The vegan vs Eric Cartman from South Park.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Recreational. </strong>The flying dagger vs the benchwarmer.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Ethical. </strong>Honest Abe vs the liar.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Social. </strong>The hermit vs the party animal.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne study at the University of Michigan categorized risk into evolutionary terms: competition with other individuals; competition with other groups; mating and allocating resources for mate attraction; environmental risks; and fertility risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we don’t live in Jurassic Park days and have to worry about becoming T-Rex’s next meal but we do continue to live in a world with complex challenges involving other people and material investments much like our ancestors. The basics of our social environment hasn’t changed much.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGender. The kinds of risk taking is influenced by the kinds of risks our ancestors experienced throughout many thousands of years of evolution. In a general sense, men are more inclined to be risk takers than women. Men compete for social status and resources to entice mates. Men have far more intra-sexual competition than women do for sex, so they have to sell their sexual fitness with overt and adventurous exploits. Even today the pressure is on men to win women over through acts of bravery and strength. Ever notice how your buddy all of the sudden acts different when a hot girls walk into the bar? Maybe he puffs his chest out or something. I call it peacocking. Men tend to take more recreational and financial risks, but when it comes to risks that threatened fertility women are not impressed. Sorry star of the show ‘Ow, my balls’ - girls don’t think it’s as funny as guys.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile women have a tendency to conduct themselves more responsibly and make restrained decisions, they also take risks. Women tend to take more social risks than men, for instance they may be more likely to switch careers late in life or voice unpopular viewpoints in business conferences. They also take recreational risks and risks related to social status in one’s group. The need to impress does go both ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Age</strong>\r\n\r\nYounger people take more risks, maybe because of hormone levels or just the fact that they have less life experience and less working knowledge of the consequences of their actions.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Relationships</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople tend to seek less risks as they age and enter into stable relationships. Relationship status can actually be a strong predictor in risk-taking behavior. Men’s testosterone level can shoot up again after a divorce and they become more risky.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Chemistry</strong>\r\n\r\nSome scientists point to neurotransmitters levels in the brain to explain risk taking. If you have an imbalance of dopamine, you are more likely to take risks that give you that ‘rush feeling’ because it restores your brain’s chemical balance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Perception</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you perceive a certain behavior as risky, you are less likely to do it. If you are optimistic, you are also more likely to do it. Some people don’t think the rules apply to them because they perceive a high level of control of situations.\r\nIs optimism good if it leads to risk taking?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Pride/ Gratification</strong>\r\n\r\nTaking risks and overcoming challenges can be very gratifying. This alone could be enough to tip the scales towards risky behavior.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I have been jumping for over 15 years and I have never done anything more committing and technical in my life. I am so happy” - Jeb Corliss, after his Flying Dagger jump.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Desperation</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople are more likely to engage in risky behavior when they are desperate. If your or someone you love’s life is on the line, there’s probably not much you wouldn’t do.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Conclusion</strong>\r\n\r\nDespite the many factors that come into play, there are definitely some patterns. An individual’s inclination to take risks correlates with their level of perceived benefit and the level of perceived danger. What’s funny is that as life becomes more cushy in the 21st century, we keep on pushing the limits just to keep this threshold in balance. They invent the airbag, we invented Nascar. They invent the parachute, we jump out of planes in squirrel suits for fun. It seems crazy sometimes, why we take risks. Maybe it’s essential, just a necessary part of life that keeps us moving forward and challenging ourselves to seek new heights, ensuring mankind’s progression as a whole and bringing about our most remarkable successes most devastating failures.. I don’t know, what do you think?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re someone who likes to take risks &amp; do fun stuff, check out our friends at Nectar Shades:<a href=\"%20http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/\"> http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/</a>. They’re all about doin’ epic shit &amp; lookin’ good while you’re at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFeel free to leave some comments below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Scott McGuire\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Risk Taking: Why do we take risks?','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2015-02-25 22:16:47','2015-02-25 22:16:47','',126,'http://localhost/blog/126-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(288,1,'2015-02-26 02:36:19','2015-02-26 02:36:19','','Deal of the Day','','publish','closed','closed','','acf_deal-of-the-day','','','2015-02-26 02:37:06','2015-02-26 02:37:06','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?post_type=acf&#038;p=288',0,'acf','',0),(289,1,'2015-02-26 03:16:15','2015-02-26 03:16:15','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for fun places to visit for outdoor activities this spring? With fifty-eight to choose from, it can be difficult to pick just which national park to explore next. Spread all over the country, these exquisitely preserved swaths of nature allow for the perfect break from the stress of everyday life. The greatest aspect of America’s National Parks is that there are parks to represent nearly every environment and climate imaginable. So to help you narrow down your options for your next trip, here are five National Parks to add to your bucket list.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-95\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network-_Bucket-List-Ideas_Yosemite-National-Park_California.jpg\" alt=\"Yosemite National Park\" width=\"400\" height=\"267\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Yosemite National Park, California</strong>\r\n\r\nYosemit