:56:02','2015-02-26 19:56:02','Get the gear to get your there.','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Deal_Camping and Hiking_CampSaver','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal_camping-and-hiking_campsaver-2','','','2015-02-26 19:56:19','2015-02-26 19:56:19','',133,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal_Camping-and-Hiking_CampSaver1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(324,1,'2015-02-26 19:57:05','2015-02-26 19:57:05','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for things to do this winter? Why not go camping? Camping in cold weather is not as hard as you may think. The key is creating a comfortable environment so everyone is a happy camper. Yup, that was a pun. This includes getting there safely, staying hydrated, eating well and frequently (s’mores count), staying warm at night, and sleeping comfortably.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTRAVEL\r\nYou’ll need a solid ride to get in and out of the backcountry in good shape - ideally, something with 4 wheel drive and a winch in case you get stuck. Before you set out on your adventure, you’ll want to make sure your car battery is in good condition. Nothing worse than getting stranded out in the cold. If it’s questionable, it might be a good time go ahead and replace it. Same goes for your oil - make sure you’re not over your miles and you might want to bring an extra quart just in case. Thinner oil in the winter - 5w30 should do just fine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHYDRATE\r\nYour body’s metabolism has to work harder in the winter just to stay warm, so be sure to drink plenty of water to stay hydrated. Keep a bottle inside your jacket so it doesn’t freeze. Clean snow (not the yellow stuff) is another good water source. If you’re uncertain about its purity, throw some in a large pot and boil it up. 10 quarts of snow makes about 1 quart of water.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEAT\r\nYour body expends more energy in cold temperatures. Food helps keep your inner furnace burning and can have a huge impact on your psychological well-being, so it’s crucial to eat plenty of carbs to maintain your core temperature and keep your spirits high. Oatmeal makes for an easy meal packed with carbs and is especially tasty with hot milk. Brew something warm like coffee or a powdered juice mix to go with it, and if you’re still hungry toast some bread by the fire. If you’re hiking, keep in mind that stopping for too long will cool you down and if you’ve been sweating you could get sick, so maybe bring a lunch that you can eat on the go. Carbs are energy dense and best for a quick boost. Peanut butter crackers, cheese, granola bars, beef jerky, and trail mix make excellent solid trail foods high in calories and protein. Keep an eye on your sodium intake with these items though, as too much will dehydrate you. Chicken noodle soup is great for dinner. It provides instant warmth and will keep your metabolism going for hours as protein energy is released throughout the night. You can buy it in dehydrated form which is super lightweight and all you have to do is add hot water. If you get the dehydrated stuff, open the package to let the excess air out and seal it back up - these can take up a ton of empty space in your pack if you don’t.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSLEEP\r\nCots are good for keeping off the hard ground in the summertime but in the winter the cold air that flows beneath will keep you chilly and uncomfortable all night. Try stacking a few sleeping mats. I prefer Therm-A-Rest, but you can also stack egg-crate foam or mix and match other mats to your comfort. Definitely sleep in insulation – mummy bags are great because they trap your body heat inside. To be safe, choose a sleeping bag with a rating 15 degrees below the coldest temperatures you expect to face. Bundle up with beanies, socks, long johns, and light fabric gloves. Be sure to keep your boots in a pack and bring them inside your bag so they don’t ice overnight. And if you really feel like spoiling yourself with comfort, you can wrap rocks in aluminum foil and keep them near the fire (careful, not too close) to allow them to get warm over the course of the night, then place them by your feet inside the tent and they’ll stay warm all night.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlrighty then, hope this helps a bit. CampSaver always has some great deals on camping essentials - like the sleeping mat, mummy bag, and warm winter gear if you need stuff. Here’s a link: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz\">http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow get out there and live out - you’re burnin’ daylight!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Related articles</strong>\r\n\r\n<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;Best Hiking Apps to Find Local Hikes&quot;]\" data-sheets-userformat=\"[null,null,771,[null,0],[null,2,13624051],null,null,null,null,null,null,1,0]\">Best Hiking Apps to Find Local Hikes</span>\r\n\r\n<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;liveout.org/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes/&quot;]\" data-sheets-userformat=\"[null,null,10755,[null,0],[null,2,16645629],null,null,null,null,null,null,null,0,null,[null,2,26145],null,10]\"><a class=\"in-cell-link\" href=\"http://localhost/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes/\" target=\"_blank\">liveout.org/blog/best-hiking-apps-to-find-local-hikes/</a></span>\r\n\r\n<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;Five National Parks Great For Outdoor Activities To Add To Your Bucket List&quot;]\" data-sheets-userformat=\"[null,null,771,[null,0],[null,2,13624051],null,null,null,null,null,null,1,0]\">Five National Parks Great For Outdoor Activities To Add To Your Bucket List</span>\r\n\r\n<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;liveout.org/blog/five-national-parks-great-for-outdoor-activities-to-add-to-your-bucket-list/&quot;]\" data-sheets-userformat=\"[null,null,10755,[null,0],[n