chool.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Qualifications</strong>\r\nInterns applying for this internship should be marketing, business, journalism or new media and communications majors with experience with research, content writing, blogging and SEO. Must be a dedicated, responsible, creative, articulate, personable and an organized self-starter. The applicant should possess excellent writing and communications skills, be detail oriented and be able to contribute a minimum of one article per week. Other characteristics we\'re looking for include:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Passion &amp; knowledge for outdoor activities\r\n- Proactive go-getter with an entrepreneurial spirit, high energy, fun, positive can-do attitude and work-ethic\r\n- Reliable, detail-oriented and extremely motivated\r\n- Honesty, hard work (doing your best) and willingness to learn\r\n- Familiarity with Google’s Keyword Tool for SEO (preferred)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Advantages</strong>\r\n- Work remotely from comfort of your home\r\n- Set your own hours\r\n- No soul-crushing office maintenance work\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nInterested in a writing internship with Live Out? Tell us your story and why you would be a good fit.\r\n\r\nEmail us at blog@liveout.org\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Related articles</strong>\r\n\r\nMake new friends and discover the best places to go outdoors near you with Live Out 2.0\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/make-new-friends-discover-best-places-go-outdoors-live-out/\">http://localhost/blog/make-new-friends-discover-best-places-go-outdoors-live-out/</a>','Writing Internship With Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network','','inherit','open','open','','124-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 21:41:43','2015-03-06 21:41:43','',124,'http://localhost/blog/124-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(402,1,'2015-03-06 21:45:17','2015-03-06 21:45:17','Save on gear that gets you outside.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_REI_Save on gear that gets you outside','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_rei_save-on-gear-that-gets-you-outside','','','2015-03-06 21:45:29','2015-03-06 21:45:29','',126,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_REI_Save-on-gear-that-gets-you-outside.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(403,1,'2015-03-06 21:47:45','2015-03-06 21:47:45','Free shipping on all orders.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Patagonia_2','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_patagonia_2','','','2015-03-06 21:51:03','2015-03-06 21:51:03','',126,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Patagonia_2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(404,1,'2015-03-06 21:48:08','2015-03-06 21:48:08','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI recently read a story on daredevil Jeb Corliss’ Flying Dagger jump - pretty wild. After jumping from a helicopter in a flying squirrel suit he threaded his way through a narrow fissure between two mountain peaks rising 2,677 feet at speeds of nearly 200 miles per hour. The crevice runs 900 feet long and bends and turns between two giant rocks 15 to 60 feet apart. He emerged from the cracks, narrowly escaping death only to realize that he needed to deploy his parachute at full speed otherwise he would miss the only landing zone he had.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe described the experience on Facebook:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I covered 3 football fields in 5 seconds and at about half way the walls were about 25ft wide. I had to sideslip as I flew because the crack was crooked and there was turbulence. I had to pull as I exited the crack in full flight or I would not make it to the only landing area that was behind me. Once I committed to the landing area there were no outs.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis got me thinking: Why do we do stuff like this? What is it about risk taking that’s so appealing? Are we chasing a high? Are some of us just born with a risky appetite? Why has this urge evolved? Why do some of us feel the need to be flying daggers while others are content to ride the pine and watch from the sidelines?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI did a little Googling and found a few common factors.. Sorry the length.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo preface, you can’t just just lump people into two categories: risk takers vs risk avoiders. That would be an oversimplification. There are categories of risk taking behaviors and people’s tendencies can be different depending on the type. You might love scuba diving with sharks but you are scared shitless of public speaking. People are complex and lots of interrelated factors come into play.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are all kinds of risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>- Financial. </strong>The gamblers vs the penny-pinchers.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Health. </strong>The vegan vs Eric Cartman from South Park.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Recreational. </strong>The flying dagger vs the benchwarmer.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Ethical. </strong>Honest Abe vs the liar.\r\n\r\n<strong>- Social. </strong>The hermit vs the party animal.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne study at the University of Michigan categorized risk into evolutionary terms: competition with other individuals; competition with other groups; mating and allocating resources for mate attraction; environmental risks; and fertility risks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we don’t live in Jurassic Park days and have to worry about becoming T-Rex’s next meal but we do continue to live in a world with complex challenges involving other people and material investments much like our ancestors. The basics of our social environment hasn’t changed much.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGender. The kinds of risk taking is influenced by the kinds of risks our ancestors experienced throughout many thousands of years of evolution. In a general sense, men are more inclined to be risk takers than women. Men compete for social status and resources to entice mates. Men have far more intra-sexual competition than women do for sex, so they have to sell their sexual fitness with overt and adventurous exploits. Even today the pressure is on men to win women over through acts of bravery and strength. Ever notice how your buddy all of the sudden acts different when a hot girls walk into the bar? Maybe he puffs his chest out or something. I call it peacocking. Men tend to take more recreational and financial risks, but when it comes to risks that threatened fertility women are not impressed. Sorry star of the show ‘Ow, my balls’ - girls don’t think it’s as funny as guys.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile women have a tendency to conduct themselves more responsibly and make restrained decisions, they also take risks. Women tend to take more social risks than men, for instance they may be more likely to switch careers late in life or voice unpopular viewpoints in business conferences. They also take recreational risks and risks related to social status in one’s group. The need to impress does go both ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Age</strong>\r\n\r\nYounger people take more risks, maybe because of hormone levels or just the fact that they have less life experience and less working knowledge of the consequences of their actions.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Relationships</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople tend to seek less risks as they age and enter into stable relationships. Relationship status can actually be a strong predictor in risk-taking behavior. Men’s testosterone level can shoot up again after a divorce and they become more risky.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Chemistry</strong>\r\n\r\nSome scientists point to neurotransmitters levels in the brain to explain risk taking. If you have an imbalance of dopamine, you are more likely to take risks that give you that ‘rush feeling’ because it restores your brain’s chemical balance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Perception</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you perceive a certain behavior as risky, you are less likely to do it. If you are optimistic, you are also more likely to do it. Some people don’t think the rules apply to them because they perceive a high level of control of situations.\r\nIs optimism good if it leads to risk taking?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Pride/ Gratification</strong>\r\n\r\nTaking risks and overcoming challenges can be very gratifying. This alone could be enough to tip the scales towards risky behavior.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>“I have been jumping for over 15 years and I have never done anything more committing and technical in my life. I am so happy” - Jeb Corliss, after his Flying Dagger jump.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Desperation</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople are more likely to engage in risky behavior when they are desperate. If your or someone you love’s life is on the line, there’s probably not much you wouldn’t do.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Conclusion</strong>\r\n\r\nDespite the many factors that come into play, there are definitely some patterns. An individual’s inclination to take risks correlates with their level of perceived benefit and the level of perceived danger. What’s funny is that as life becomes more cushy in the 21st century, we keep on pushing the limits just to keep this threshold in balance. They invent the airbag, we invented Nascar. They invent the parachute, we jump out of planes in squirrel suits for fun. It seems crazy sometimes, why we take risks. Maybe it’s essential, just a necessary part of life that keeps us moving forward and challenging ourselves to seek new heights, ensuring mankind’s progression as a whole and bringing about our most remarkable successes most devastating failures.. I don’t know, what do you think?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re someone who likes to take risks &amp; do fun stuff, check out our friends at Nectar Shades:<a href=\"%20http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/\"> http://www.nectarsunglasses.com/</a>. They’re all about doin’ epic shit &amp; lookin’ good while you’re at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFeel free to leave some comments below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Scott McGuire\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Risk Taking: Why do we take risks?','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 21:48:08','2015-03-06 21:48:08','',126,'http://localhost/blog/126-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(405,1,'2015-03-06 21:51:12','2015-03-06 21:51:12','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRECON Instruments has recently developed the world’s first Micro Optics Displays for ski goggles. The device uses built-in GPS &amp; sensors to display stats like speed, vertical descent, air time, altitude, navigation and distance, providing you with real-time stats as you blast down the mountain - and it fits conveniently into goggles made by just about every leading brand including Burton, K2 and Ride.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRecon’s sensors can be embedded in the sides of your goggles out of your line of vision so as not to be distracting or dangerous. It allows you to retain visibility while the information is displayed in your peripheral area, like having a mini LCD screen in the side of your mask that’s there when you need it and out of sight when you don’t.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUsing inbuilt GPS, the MOD Live can determine your location to within a meter. The on-board altimeter tracks your elevation while the gyroscope and accelerometer track your orientation and speed allowing you to trace your every shred on the slopes.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlthough initially created for alpine skiers, the many advantages of this type of technology are quickly being recognized in other extreme sports – like sky sports. In the past, professional hang gliding and paragliding pilots use flight computers to provide them with detailed, real-time information about the skies they’re flying and have yet to utilize this new technology until recently. Considering the many preparations, safety measures, and calculations to consider when planning a jump, The MOD Live heads-up display provides an additional level of calculation and safety to the equation for wingsuit pilots as it delivers important flight information like speed, glide rate, and altitude in real time at a simple glance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nRecon Live can also be linked to a wireless video camera through Bluetooth, allowing you to film your experiences while simultaneously tracking your analytic data. The Micro Optic Display will even connect to your smartphone so you cou can access your music playlist without removing your phone from your pocket - super gnarly.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe MOD Live runs off of Android OS so you can upload your apps to it and it even comes with several relevant ones – like navigation and buddy tracking. A wireless remote control allows you to navigate between apps and interact with the Micro Optics Display and when the day is done you can upload all your stats online to sites like Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlrighty then, the RECON MOD Live Display - add it to your snowboarding gear wishlist. Cole Sports is your go-to for ski &amp; snowboarding deals if you need some fresh gear: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/Ab1A9E\">http://goo.gl/Ab1A9E</a>. Now get off your butt, throw on your Burton goggles, and get out there and get shredding!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>','Ski & Snowboarding Gear Review: MOD Live Micro Optic Display by RECON','','inherit','open','open','','109-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 21:51:12','2015-03-06 21:51:12','',109,'http://localhost/blog/109-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(406,1,'2015-03-06 21:55:02','2015-03-06 21:55:02','Get premium quality natural supplements.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Institute for Vibrant Living','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_institute-for-vibrant-living','','','2015-03-06 21:55:49','2015-03-06 21:55:49','',79,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Institute-for-Vibrant-Living.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(407,1,'2015-03-06 21:55:56','2015-03-06 21:55:56','For those who enjoy outdoor activities, here’s 3 nutrient-dense superfoods to supercharge your active lifestyle and improve your overall health and wellness.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Spirulina</strong>\r\nSpirulina is a form of algae loaded with nutrients. It’s made up of high quality, healthy proteins, B vitamins, and numerous other minerals with various health benefits. It boosts your immune system by kick starting antibody production and raising the number of cells in your body that help you fight disease. It also helps regulate fat and carbohydrate metabolism.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome studies indicate that spirulina may also help:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Regulate blood sugar levels and fat levels in diabetes\r\n- Slow the growth of cancer\r\n- Prevent and suppress viral infections\r\n- Detoxify the liver and kidneys\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis superfood is commonly sold as a powder, so it’s easy to stir into a glass of juice or water, but be warned, it does have a distinct flavor, so first-time users may want to start by blending a spoonful into a green smoothie for a healthy breakfast.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Broccoli</strong>\r\nIt’s cliche’, but it’s true. Broccoli will turn you into a badass. Loaded with nutrients, this vegetable helps you fight stress, fatigue, maintain weight, keep your blood sugar in check and boost your immune system - all at the same time. Here’s some of the nerd stuff to back it up:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBroccoli is packed with Vitamin C, which helps you recover from physical and emotional stress by balancing cortisol. Too much cortisol production leads to exhaustion and a fat belly, and you don’t want that. Broccoli’s stem’s have a lot of fiber and chromium to help you maintain weight and stabilize blood sugar. Stable blood sugar = balanced energy and less stress. The florets are packed with Beta-carotene - a powerful antioxidant that supercharges your immune system.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf a steamy side dish of roasted broccoli isn’t your thing, try blending some into a pesto sauce, finely chop to add to scrambled eggs, or add a bunch of small florets to your favorite soup, pasta sauce, or salad.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Green Tea</strong>\r\nGreen tea will turn you into Bruce Li. Chock full of nutrients, antioxidants, and caffeine, the list of things green tea has been claimed to fix include helping you burn fat, lowering your risk of cancer, improving brain function, killing bacteria and helping you fight infection, lowering your risk of diabetes and heart disease, and helping you live longer. Phew... As you can see, it’s worth looking into.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re bored by the thought of another hot beverage, think beyond the mug - use green tea in oatmeal, smoothies, salad dressings, marinades, juice blends, or even mixers!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese three foods pack a Mighty Man punch when you take them together. Not only do you get the individual benefits of each, but the combination helps you break down food easier and absorb more from what you put in. Better nutrient absorption = more energy, strength, and immunity and BOOM. You’re a badass. Now go be America’s next Ninja Warrior.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBy the way, Under Armour has some good deals going on on fresh swag right now  if you want to stay ahead of the curve &amp; lose weight in style: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/Y305lE\">http://goo.gl/Y305lE</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDisclaimer: I’m not a doctor; consult your doctor before starting a new diet. Yada yada yada...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Fuel For The Fire: 3 Nutritious Superfoods for Active People','','inherit','open','open','','79-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 21:55:56','2015-03-06 21:55:56','',79,'http://localhost/blog/79-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(408,1,'2015-03-06 22:03:52','2015-03-06 22:03:52','Healthy products at a healthy savings.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_WebVitamins','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_webvitamins','','','2015-03-06 22:04:08','2015-03-06 22:04:08','',54,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_WebVitamins.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(409,1,'2015-03-06 22:04:11','2015-03-06 22:04:11','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLearning how to set goals is crucial for personal development. Since 90% of new years resolutions are self-improvement related or to lose weight, these are what we\'ll focus on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPeople are becoming overly dependent resolutions to start making healthy lifestyle choices. We put things off in order to start on a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. Old habits are hard to break and people don’t change overnight so when we expect ourselves to we are putting a lot of pressure on ourselves. This makes it discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways. Let’s try to break this train of thought. Think goals, not resolutions. The word resolution plays too many mind games.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFirst you have to ask yourself: <strong>What do I want?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are a lot of different types of goals. Once you’ve nailed that down, write it down and put it somewhere you’ll see it every day. A bathroom mirror.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHaving the knowledge is only part of the equation though. You’ll need plan of execution if you want to see results.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo you ask yourself: <strong>How can I get there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAchieving your diet and setting fitness goals is about cultivating healthy habits. A funny thing happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your behavior becomes like clockwork. Once you start seeing and feeling the benefits and you won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you want lasting results, sit down and look at the daily choices you make with regard to food, exercise, sleep, and stress. You might only have to make this resolution once if you do it right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Set attainable goals.</strong>\r\nThere’s no single step from A to Z. Write down a full list of goals and break them up into short-term attainable ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCommon examples of goals:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose weight”\r\n“I’m going to quit smoking.”\r\n“I’m going to make more sales and start saving more money this year.”\r\n“I’m going to work on my personal relationships this year.”\r\netc..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese are great goal ideas but they lack a step-by-step plan on how to achieve them. The language is too distant. One year is a long time and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It can be discouraging if you keep your sights set on 20 pounds. Think 1 pound. How am I going to lose 1 pound?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a plan of action, and set milestones.</strong>\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by eating healthy and going on a walk each evening after work. If I can keep this up for 1 month I will have lost almost 5 pounds.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n1. There is a clear plan\r\n2. There are short-term milestones\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that it’s not the end of the world if you mess up or miss a day!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nShit happens, it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and nobody’s perfect. Things come up from time to time but it’s important that you stick with it. So you skip a day. Maybe add 15 minutes to your routine the next day or whatever - just get back at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI had a friend who quit smoking for 6 months and one night he decided to have a smoke. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day. This is nuts. I understand substance addictions are difficult and complicated, but it’s the thought pattern that lead to the behaviors. So you had one cigarette, big deal. Resist the urge to have that next one and the urge will go away in time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnother buddy all psyched up one year about losing weight and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. These programs can be great but if you haven’t exercised in years, they can be tough. He worked his ass off for about two days and on the third he couldn’t get off the couch because he was so sore. He didn’t ever get back into because it was just too strenuous for him and he associated exercise with bad feelings. He would have been better off going for a few walks and easing his way into a program like that. You can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and your workout becomes counter-productive.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out. Plus, achieving short-term goals achieving them can be really encouraging! When you see and feel the progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Plan your trips to the gym.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more you’ll start to rationalize about not going. It’s easy to allow things to get in the way when you don’t plan for them in your schedule. Write it down &amp; plan on it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind you don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health. Every minutes counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThink you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this, 30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDon’t believe me? Try it sometime.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf your goal is to lose weight, keep in mind that exercise is only a part of the equation. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting junk in you’re going to look and feel like junk. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone. If you hate the taste of most vegetables, throw some into a blender with sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, bananas and some apple juice and to mask the taste. You’ll get them in without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Do what you enjoy.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy exercise. Habits will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get creative!</strong>\r\n\r\nIf running on the treadmill bores the hell out of you, try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. Crank up some crunchy tunes or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make it more enjoyable. The more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep it fresh!</strong>\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again you get bored and your body gets used to it. Diversifying your workouts is not only less boring, but it also helps you burn more calories because your body is not as used to it. It’s called muscle confusion.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get sleep.</strong>\r\n\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Anticipate obstacles.</strong>\r\n\r\nLife is unpredictable. There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps you achieve your goals. Under Armour has some fresh new swag if you wanna look good while you’re at it: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/iXABx7\">http://goo.gl/iXABx7</a>. Feel free to leave a reply and tips of your own in the comments section below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Additional resources:</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://appadvice.com/appguides/show/habit-building-apps\">Goal setting apps</a>\r\nNot sure how to choose the right foods? <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/\">ChooseMyPlate.gov</a> can help.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Goal Setting For Personal Development','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:04:11','2015-03-06 22:04:11','',54,'http://localhost/blog/54-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(410,1,'2015-03-06 22:06:06','2015-03-06 22:06:06','Premium quality supplements','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Institute for Vibrant Living_Banner','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_institute-for-vibrant-living_banner','','','2015-03-06 22:06:28','2015-03-06 22:06:28','',54,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Institute-for-Vibrant-Living_Banner.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(411,1,'2015-03-06 22:06:35','2015-03-06 22:06:35','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLearning how to set goals is crucial for personal development. Since 90% of new years resolutions are self-improvement related or to lose weight, these are what we\'ll focus on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPeople are becoming overly dependent resolutions to start making healthy lifestyle choices. We put things off in order to start on a specific date and then expect ourselves to suddenly change our ways overnight. Old habits are hard to break and people don’t change overnight so when we expect ourselves to we are putting a lot of pressure on ourselves. This makes it discouraging when we slip up and so the minute we feel like we’re too far off track we allow ourselves to slip back into our old ways. Let’s try to break this train of thought. Think goals, not resolutions. The word resolution plays too many mind games.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFirst you have to ask yourself: <strong>What do I want?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are a lot of different types of goals. Once you’ve nailed that down, write it down and put it somewhere you’ll see it every day. A bathroom mirror.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHaving the knowledge is only part of the equation though. You’ll need plan of execution if you want to see results.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo you ask yourself: <strong>How can I get there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAchieving your diet and setting fitness goals is about cultivating healthy habits. A funny thing happens when you develop a new habit. Over time, your behavior becomes like clockwork. Once you start seeing and feeling the benefits and you won’t ever want to go back to your old ways.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you want lasting results, sit down and look at the daily choices you make with regard to food, exercise, sleep, and stress. You might only have to make this resolution once if you do it right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Set attainable goals.</strong>\r\nThere’s no single step from A to Z. Write down a full list of goals and break them up into short-term attainable ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCommon examples of goals:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose weight”\r\n“I’m going to quit smoking.”\r\n“I’m going to make more sales and start saving more money this year.”\r\n“I’m going to work on my personal relationships this year.”\r\netc..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThese are great goal ideas but they lack a step-by-step plan on how to achieve them. The language is too distant. One year is a long time and 20 lbs is a lot of weight. It can be discouraging if you keep your sights set on 20 pounds. Think 1 pound. How am I going to lose 1 pound?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a plan of action, and set milestones.</strong>\r\n\r\n“I’m going to lose 1 lb this week by eating healthy and going on a walk each evening after work. If I can keep this up for 1 month I will have lost almost 5 pounds.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhy is this better?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n1. There is a clear plan\r\n2. There are short-term milestones\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind that it’s not the end of the world if you mess up or miss a day!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nShit happens, it doesn’t mean you should just quit. Life is unpredictable and nobody’s perfect. Things come up from time to time but it’s important that you stick with it. So you skip a day. Maybe add 15 minutes to your routine the next day or whatever - just get back at it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI had a friend who quit smoking for 6 months and one night he decided to have a smoke. In his mind, he’d slipped up and completely fallen off the wagon, so the next day he went out and bought a pack and resumed his habit of smoking a pack a day. This is nuts. I understand substance addictions are difficult and complicated, but it’s the thought pattern that lead to the behaviors. So you had one cigarette, big deal. Resist the urge to have that next one and the urge will go away in time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnother buddy all psyched up one year about losing weight and went out and bought the full Insanity DVD set. These programs can be great but if you haven’t exercised in years, they can be tough. He worked his ass off for about two days and on the third he couldn’t get off the couch because he was so sore. He didn’t ever get back into because it was just too strenuous for him and he associated exercise with bad feelings. He would have been better off going for a few walks and easing his way into a program like that. You can actually do more harm than good when you over-exercise. Your muscles break down faster than they can repair and your workout becomes counter-productive.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen you allow your body to adapt to the transition, you’re less likely to burn out. Plus, achieving short-term goals achieving them can be really encouraging! When you see and feel the progress being made, you’ll be more likely to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Plan your trips to the gym.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to plan your day around going to the gym. The more you make it optional i.e. “I’ll go if I have time,” the more you’ll start to rationalize about not going. It’s easy to allow things to get in the way when you don’t plan for them in your schedule. Write it down &amp; plan on it like you would a dentists appointment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKeep in mind you don’t have to go to the gym to get exercise in! Sometimes just taking a 20 minute walk or even a few short walks throughout the day can be enough to get the blood flowing and maintain good health. Every minutes counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThink you’re too busy to find time to exercise? Consider this, 30 minutes of exercise can add 4 hours of productivity to your day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDon’t believe me? Try it sometime.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf your goal is to lose weight, keep in mind that exercise is only a part of the equation. Remember the old adage “You are what you eat.” It’s true! If you’re putting junk in you’re going to look and feel like junk. Find healthy foods that you enjoy eating and include them in your diet more often. Include them into your family dinners so you don’t feel alone. If you hate the taste of most vegetables, throw some into a blender with sweet fruit like strawberries, blueberries, bananas and some apple juice and to mask the taste. You’ll get them in without having to force them down.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Do what you enjoy.</strong>\r\n\r\nTry to find a way to enjoy exercise. Habits will last longer if you actually enjoy what you’re doing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get creative!</strong>\r\n\r\nIf running on the treadmill bores the hell out of you, try biking, swimming, or even kick-boxing. Crank up some crunchy tunes or invite a friend to chat with while you work out – anything to make it more enjoyable. The more positive associations you make with exercise, the more likely you are to stick with it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep it fresh!</strong>\r\n\r\nChange up your routine from time to time. When you do the same things over and over again you get bored and your body gets used to it. Diversifying your workouts is not only less boring, but it also helps you burn more calories because your body is not as used to it. It’s called muscle confusion.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Get sleep.</strong>\r\n\r\nYour body (and your mind) repairs itself during sleep – make time for it!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Anticipate obstacles.</strong>\r\n\r\nLife is unpredictable. There are always unforeseen challenges that threaten to get in between you and your goals – learn to expect and anticipate them and try to develop strategies ahead of time to deal with them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps you achieve your goals. Under Armour has some fresh new swag if you wanna look good while you’re at it: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/iXABx7\">http://goo.gl/iXABx7</a>. Feel free to leave a reply and tips of your own in the comments section below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Additional resources:</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://appadvice.com/appguides/show/habit-building-apps\">Goal setting apps</a>\r\nNot sure how to choose the right foods? <a href=\"http://www.choosemyplate.gov/\">ChooseMyPlate.gov</a> can help.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Goal Setting For Personal Development','','inherit','open','open','','54-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:06:35','2015-03-06 22:06:35','',54,'http://localhost/blog/54-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(412,1,'2015-03-06 22:08:27','2015-03-06 22:08:27','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPacking a backpack when planning a hiking or camping trip isn’t rocket science, but there are some important things to consider when loading up your outdoor gear. When you’re carrying upwards of fifty pounds on your back for days at a time, it pays to put some thought into what to bring and how to pack it! Things like weight distribution, conservation of space, and convenience are all important things to consider.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Convenience</strong>\r\nFirst, let’s talk about the logistics. Anything you don’t plan on using until night or later on in the trip can be stowed away in the bottom of the pack. Items that belong at the bottom are things like your sleeping bag, heavy clothing that you won’t use until sundown, dinner cooking utensils, and other things you’ll only need once you set up camp at the end of the day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou’ll find it is convenient to keep items that you might need at a moments notice at the top of your pack or in an easily accessible side pouch. You don’t want to have to go rooting around every time you stop just to grab that 5 Hour Energy or bag of sunflower seeds. Things like water, snacks, first aid supplies, a flashlight or headlamp, and a rain jacket, should all be kept somewhere when you can reach them easily.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Distribution</strong>\r\nDistributing weight is also key. It is important to spread out heavier items throughout your pack to avoid stress or injury. Too much weight at the bottom of your pack will take a toll on your lower back, while too much weight up top will put too much strain on your shoulders. It also helps to try to keep the heavier items closer to your back, that way they’re not constantly pulling the pack away from you. Adjust the straps to put more weight on your hips and less on your shoulders.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Note:</strong> Clothing can be used to separate items and achieve a more balanced weight distribution.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Conservation</strong>\r\nConservation of space is also very important to consider, as just getting everything to fit can be a challenge. Some tips:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Share gear.</strong> Try to share gear with your hiking partner to eliminate duplication. If you do this though, be sure to stick close! You don’t want them wandering off with the map, food and water.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Only take the essentials.</strong> You might not know exactly what you’ll need or use in advance until you’ve been on several hikes, but until then it’s probably best to play it safe. Better safe than sorry! Things NOT to skimp on: A good sleeping pad &amp; clean socks!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Attach gear.</strong> Grab a couple carabiners before you go and attach some gear to the outside of your pack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Compress.</strong> Try to find compressible gear – there’s a lot of really light, warm, and compressible gear out there and lot of this stuff is becoming more and more affordable. If you haven’t updated your hiking arsenal in the past two decades, it might save your pack and your back to look into some new outdoor equipment.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Water on the sides.</strong> Carry your water on the sides of your pack. You can even replace hard water bottles with collapsible reservoirs, which will help with the weight factor.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Repackage food.</strong> Sometimes prepackaged backpacking meals can take up a huge amount of space with mostly empty air space inside the bag. Take the food out and repackage it yourself to minimize the space it takes up. Also, try to pack calorie dense food like nuts, dried fruit, and oatmeal to maximize the calories you’re getting per ounce of weight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Roll your clothes.</strong> When it comes to packing clothing, you can save space and fit more into your pack by rolling up your clothes. Rolling compresses clothes better than folding.\r\nTip: You can fit your socks in that extra pair of boots you’re carrying.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOk guys, hope these tips on how to pack a backpack have helped. While it’s not overly complex, it does help to plan a little to avoid unnecessary discomfort that might take away from your backpacking experience. Here’s a link to some good deals on Mountain Gear hiking supplies if you need stuff: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/4JQRqo\">http://goo.gl/4JQRqo</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCheers.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Ryan Quinn\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Hiking Tips: How to Pack a Backpack','','inherit','open','open','','102-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:08:27','2015-03-06 22:08:27','',102,'http://localhost/blog/102-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(413,1,'2015-03-06 22:11:56','2015-03-06 22:11:56','Shop women\'s run.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Under Armour','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_under-armour-2','','','2015-03-06 22:12:14','2015-03-06 22:12:14','',67,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Under-Armour.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(414,1,'2015-03-06 22:12:20','2015-03-06 22:12:20','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDon’t have time for the gym? Welcome to the reality of daily life for a lot of people. No worries, recent studies suggest that each minute of physical activity counts as a workout.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nExperts recommend getting at least 150 minutes of moderate physical activity each week, performed in increments of at least 10 minutes. &lt;&lt;&lt; The time requirement here can be misleading. It almost implies that anything less than 10 minutes is pointless for health and fitness, which just isn’t the case. Over time, even mild exercise in small increments can help you lose weight and improve overall well-being, both physically and mentally.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDon’t believe me? Take a hike. Literally. Get up and take a walk around your office building and take the stairs on your way back up. You might be be surprised at how easily you can squeeze in that 2.5 hours of aerobic exercise per week with a few minutes here and there.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne study at the University of Utah showed that every minute invested in mild to strenuous exercise was associated with a .07 decrease in BMI in women and a .04 drop in men. This may not seem like a lot, but these minutes add up after a while and manifests into real muscle and fitness results.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMost people think if they can’t make it to the gym, then why bother at all? Don’t think like that. You don’t need to go out and buy a workout plan like Insanity or P90x. If you haven’t exercised in a while, these programs can be discouraging and lead to burnout. Just do things to get your heart rate up a few times throughout the day. Start with a walk, then try to add some new exercises each week. One week you take a walk, the next week you get off the bus one stop early and walk home those extra 5 minutes. Every minute of physical activity counts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHere are a few home workout ideas to get you thinking..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n- Crank up your iPod and clean the house once a week\r\n- Wash your car by hand instead of driving through a carwash\r\n- Have access to a pool? Swim a few laps occasionally\r\n- While cooking, chop the veggies by hand or stir the batter manually instead of using an electric mixer\r\n- Park further from the building at the grocery store or at your office so you can get in an extra 2-3 minutes in before and after\r\n- Get off the bus a stop early on your way home and walk the rest of the way\r\n- Take a 5 minute walk when you get home from work, before sitting on the couch or cooking dinner. Going outside for a while can literally melt away both fat and stress\r\n- Have a dog? Take them on an extra walk each day\r\n- Get a friend or family member involved with you and challenge them to join you\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou get the point. Don’t give up on a workout if you can’t make it to the gym, each minute of physical activity counts as exercise. If you don’t want to pay for a gym membership, Horizon Fitness equipment to help you lose weight: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/ovv4FG\">http://goo.gl/ovv4FG</a>. Bottom line, get creative &amp; do things you enjoy. If you’re moving, you’re burnin’ calories, and if you’re not.. well, you’re burnin’ daylight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Exercise Tips: Every Minute Counts','','inherit','open','open','','67-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:12:20','2015-03-06 22:12:20','',67,'http://localhost/blog/67-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2015-03-06 22:24:39','2015-03-06 22:24:39','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFinding the right activity for someone with Aspergers can be a great way to manage the disorder. Geocaching allows those with autism to utilize their unique minds and improve their social skills at the same time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnyone with a loved one affected by Asperger\'s understands the complex challenges these men and women face in life. Those with Aspergers often have difficulties in social situations as well as repetitive behavior patterns and interests. They also tend to have extremely high IQ’s as a result of their dedication to their intense interests.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nCertain careers and hobbies are more common among those with autism - those that involve technology, small environments, and few people. This is why Geocaching can be a great activity for those with Aspergers and other LD’s in the autism spectrum because it challenges them to use to exercise their sharp minds and encourages participation in group activities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGeocaching is an outdoor recreation activity where participants use a GPS, cell phone or other navigational technique to hide and seek objects and containers called “geocaches” all over the world - like a real world treasure hunt. It’s one of the fastest growing activities in State Parks. Some parks are now even offering workshops for beginners to learn the ins and the out’s of this relatively new activity.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo be good at geocaching, it takes a pretty tech-savvy and perceptive individual. You have to piece together clues, follow navigational coordinates and complete interrelated challenges. When you’re hiding the “cache”, you have to create a puzzle and leaving clues so people can follow your coordinates and find the treasure - or geocache. The acute problem solving mindset and attention to detail commonly seen in individuals with Aspergers is precisely why they might love and be good at geocaching. It’s challenging, fulfilling, and it opens new opportunities to make new friends with the same interests and spend time outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you know someone with Aspergers or other autism spectrum learning disabilities, you might gently recommend geocaching. There are places online where you can meet and make new friends who like these types of outdoor activities too. Try Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlright hope this helps someone. You can get all the geocaching stuff you need at Mountain Gear: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/zkeQYf\">http://goo.gl/zkeQYf</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nGood luck!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Managing Aspergers With Geocaching','','inherit','open','open','','86-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:24:39','2015-03-06 22:24:39','',86,'http://localhost/blog/86-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(416,1,'2015-03-06 22:46:51','2015-03-06 22:46:51','Sara Fry, the accomplished author, motivational speaker, thru-hiker, and explorer shares her inspirational story with us about how she’s overcome unbelievable challenges and forged her own path in pursuit of her passion for hiking. She offers words of encouragement, advice on how to cultivate a positive mindset, and shares quotes about life, reminding us to stay young at heart, be strong and determined, and to never, ever give up.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn 22 days I’ll take my first steps on one of the most ruggedly beautiful and enticing backcountry trails in the United States: The Continental Divide Trail – a 3,100 mile backpacking trek. I’ve spent the past 2 years exploring and expanding my backcountry resume. In less than 24 months, I’ve logged over 3,500 miles exclusively on our nation’s extensive network of trails. Needless to say, I’m helplessly in love with nature and all things outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_7.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-116\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_7.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_7\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMany people think that to be able to backpack you must be young, strong, and healthy. This may be true, but not in the sense of the definitions you’ve been taught. A backpacker must possess these qualities, but on a different platform.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe ideal backpacker should be young… at heart. They should know how to let loose and gaze at nature with the wide-eyed wonder of a child. They should welcome the unknown and recapture the freedom that they once felt in their youth.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe ideal backpacker should be strong… with determination. They should know that self-encouragement and positivity are quintessential friends to have along on any journey. They must believe in themselves and have the strength to continue achieving progress.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe ideal backpacker should be healthy… mentally healthy. They should recognize the power that not only their words hold, but also their thoughts. Over 90% of hiking is entirely mental. The other 10% is physical. The mind is a beautiful thing; we have the power to achieve anything we set our sights on. Perhaps J.R.R. Tolkien said it best, “It is not the strength of the body that counts, but the strength of the spirit.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_5.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-117\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_5.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_5\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI found my passion for backpacking after I had gotten diagnosed with cancer at the young age of 19. During that time, I had been through 11 surgeries in 13 months. It was sheer torture – in all sense of the word.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBut my health issues go back further. Five years prior to my cancer diagnosis, I sustained a Traumatic Brain Injury. I was in a coma, I had to re-learn how to properly read, I was bedridden for years and was unable to attend my Sophomore, Junior, and Senior years of high school. To this day I have a grocery list of persistent symptoms long enough to make even a personal assistant do a double take. My physical health has never been my “strong suit.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAt 20 years of age, I was tired of having my life being dictated around what I should and shouldn’t do. I was tired of family constantly checking in on me. I was tired of being perpetually sick. I was tired of listening to doctors tell me how to live. This was, after all, MY life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI decided to set out on my own path. For years I had wanted to thru-hike the Pacific Crest Trail. So I strapped on my backpack and tramped down the winding trail of exploration, imagination, and overall sheer happiness… and I haven’t looked back since.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-115\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBecause of my ever prominent health symptoms, hiking does not come easy for me. On any given day I could have one or all of the following: blurry vision, vertigo, extreme fatigue, complete loss of hearing, numb mouth, and severe muscle spasms… just to name a few. But I’ve made a conscious decision not to let any of these things hold me back from doing what I truly love.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_3.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-118\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_3.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_3\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBackpacking is my passion. I refuse to fall back on the many legitimate reasons as to why some people say I “can’t.” I refuse to be defined by the suffocating constraints that people so readily want to place on me. I was given life so that I could LIVE – genuinely and wholeheartedly. Stephen Covey said, “Live life out of your imagination, not your history.” And as long as I’m living I intend to indefatigably follow his wisdom.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-119\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_2.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_2\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo me, nature is more than a wild, opulent wonderland. It is more than the dazzling alpine lakes and the rigidly enchanting peaks. To me, nature is my home. It’s a place where I can be myself without hiding my ailments. It’s a place where I can test my strength and endurance. It’s a place where despite the war sometimes raging inside me, I’m able to stand amidst such grand majesty and everything else simply fades away into the wind.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo me, nature isn’t strictly a place or location, but it exists inside each and everyone of us. Everybody possess the three backpacking traits: youth, strength, and health. But it is up to the individual to cultivate these valuable qualities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_6.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-120\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_6.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_6\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI challenge you to dream big, despite what others may say. I encourage you to follow your passion, it’ll take you further than you’ve imagined. I urge you stop making excuses. We have the ability to not only overcome, but also thrive in our environment when we put our mind to it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhen situations seem daunting and you begin doubting yourself, remember the girl who’s walking across the length of the United States despite everything she’s been told she “can’t” do. Remember the girl who looks for the positive things in life, when often times it’s the harder route to take. But most importantly, remember that YOU are capable of anything you set your mind to… because just like hiking, life is also 90% mental and 10% physical. Now take my hand and we’ll roam with a freedom rarely seen.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_4.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-121\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Backpacking-Traits_Sara-Fry_4.jpg\" alt=\"Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Backpacking Traits_Sara Fry_4\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFollow her journey of Continental Divide Trail at <a href=\"http://sarafry.wordpress.com/\">http://sarafry.wordpress.com/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Sara Fry\r\n\r\nAuthor. Motivational Speaker. Thru-hiker. Explorer.\r\n\r\nGuest Post, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Related articles</b>\r\n\r\nGoal Setting For Personal Development\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/goal-setting-for-personal-development/\">liveout.org/blog/goal-setting-for-personal-development/</a></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Original article</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/important-backpacking-traits/\">http://localhost/blog/important-backpacking-traits/</a>','The Most Important Backpacking Traits','','inherit','open','open','','114-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:46:51','2015-03-06 22:46:51','',114,'http://localhost/blog/114-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(417,1,'2015-03-06 22:49:59','2015-03-06 22:49:59','','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Mountain Gear','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_mountain-gear','','','2015-03-06 22:50:05','2015-03-06 22:50:05','',133,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Mountain-Gear.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(418,1,'2015-03-06 22:50:09','2015-03-06 22:50:09','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLooking for things to do this winter? Why not go camping? Camping in cold weather is not as hard as you may think. The key is creating a comfortable environment so everyone is a happy camper. Yup, that was a pun. This includes getting there safely, staying hydrated, eating well and frequently (s’mores count), staying warm at night, and sleeping comfortably.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTRAVEL\r\nYou’ll need a solid ride to get in and out of the backcountry in good shape - ideally, something with 4 wheel drive and a winch in case you get stuck. Before you set out on your adventure, you’ll want to make sure your car battery is in good condition. Nothing worse than getting stranded out in the cold. If it’s questionable, it might be a good time go ahead and replace it. Same goes for your oil - make sure you’re not over your miles and you might want to bring an extra quart just in case. Thinner oil in the winter - 5w30 should do just fine.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHYDRATE\r\nYour body’s metabolism has to work harder in the winter just to stay warm, so be sure to drink plenty of water to stay hydrated. Keep a bottle inside your jacket so it doesn’t freeze. Clean snow (not the yellow stuff) is another good water source. If you’re uncertain about its purity, throw some in a large pot and boil it up. 10 quarts of snow makes about 1 quart of water.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEAT\r\nYour body expends more energy in cold temperatures. Food helps keep your inner furnace burning and can have a huge impact on your psychological well-being, so it’s crucial to eat plenty of carbs to maintain your core temperature and keep your spirits high. Oatmeal makes for an easy meal packed with carbs and is especially tasty with hot milk. Brew something warm like coffee or a powdered juice mix to go with it, and if you’re still hungry toast some bread by the fire. If you’re hiking, keep in mind that stopping for too long will cool you down and if you’ve been sweating you could get sick, so maybe bring a lunch that you can eat on the go. Carbs are energy dense and best for a quick boost. Peanut butter crackers, cheese, granola bars, beef jerky, and trail mix make excellent solid trail foods high in calories and protein. Keep an eye on your sodium intake with these items though, as too much will dehydrate you. Chicken noodle soup is great for dinner. It provides instant warmth and will keep your metabolism going for hours as protein energy is released throughout the night. You can buy it in dehydrated form which is super lightweight and all you have to do is add hot water. If you get the dehydrated stuff, open the package to let the excess air out and seal it back up - these can take up a ton of empty space in your pack if you don’t.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSLEEP\r\nCots are good for keeping off the hard ground in the summertime but in the winter the cold air that flows beneath will keep you chilly and uncomfortable all night. Try stacking a few sleeping mats. I prefer Therm-A-Rest, but you can also stack egg-crate foam or mix and match other mats to your comfort. Definitely sleep in insulation – mummy bags are great because they trap your body heat inside. To be safe, choose a sleeping bag with a rating 15 degrees below the coldest temperatures you expect to face. Bundle up with beanies, socks, long johns, and light fabric gloves. Be sure to keep your boots in a pack and bring them inside your bag so they don’t ice overnight. And if you really feel like spoiling yourself with comfort, you can wrap rocks in aluminum foil and keep them near the fire (careful, not too close) to allow them to get warm over the course of the night, then place them by your feet inside the tent and they’ll stay warm all night.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlrighty then, hope this helps a bit. CampSaver always has some great deals on camping essentials - like the sleeping mat, mummy bag, and warm winter gear if you need stuff. Here’s a link: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz\">http://goo.gl/dYC3Uz</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow get out there and live out - you’re burnin’ daylight!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','Winter Camping Tips: How to Camp in Cold Weather','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:50:09','2015-03-06 22:50:09','',133,'http://localhost/blog/133-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(419,1,'2015-03-06 22:53:01','2015-03-06 22:53:01','Deals on hunting & outdoors gear.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deals_Sportsmans Warehouse','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deals_sportsmans-warehouse','','','2015-03-06 22:53:37','2015-03-06 22:53:37','',105,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deals_Sportsmans-Warehouse.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(420,1,'2015-03-06 22:53:44','2015-03-06 22:53:44','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome areas out west are moving to ban hunters from using drones to find game. While most sportsmen consider it cheating, lawmakers are deliberating over how to deal with these new gadgets.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Who would regulate it?</strong>\r\nHunting game from the air was outlawed in federal law in 1959. The use of commercial drones for private purposes has become hugely popular in recent years, which is why wildlife rangers are addressing the issue now to clarify the guidelines before it gets out of control, and everyone adds drones to their hunting gear list. Banning the use of these unmanned aircrafts would be a decision left to government authorities.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What is the issue at stake?</strong>\r\nThe current law states that is against the law to hunt until 2 days after conducting a scout by air - a “fair game” ethics honored by most game sportsmen.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n$$$. The state reports that hunting yields virtually four hundred mil each year via permit costs, attire, product revenue, accommodations and other associated activities. A ban on drone hunting accessories would cost outfitters and sporting good stores a lot of money. The animals, however are largely in favor of the ban.\r\n<strong>When are they looking to implement these laws?</strong>\r\nPreliminary votes are underway. If passed, the ban would be included as a modification of current hunting regulations.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Why do people care?</strong>\r\nMost people think of the US army using drones for counter terrorism during wartime, but they’re becoming increasingly popular among law enforcement and other gov departments. The issue of privacy has prompted some states to limit their use, even by these agencies. Specifically with regard to hunting, some people just think it’s plain unfair and takes the sportsmanship out of the game.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>How do we regulate the use of drones?</strong>\r\nSome folks are already holding protests about the issue, asking for legislation mandating an additional tax on special drone hunting permits. Not long after introducing the idea to a small town outside of Denver, checks came pouring in from people trying to acquire one of these licenses – an unexpected and unfortunate backfire for those protesting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe deliberations to permit these licenses are ongoing, however the issue has already been disputed in the courtroom – opposing hunters arguing that denying their privilege to use drones would be a criminal offense.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThat just leaves the question of where..\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Where does one draw the line between cheating and “fair game”?</strong>\r\n\r\nWhat’s your opinion?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor deals on solid hunting gear from the best brands, check out BlackOvis: <a href=\"http://goo.gl/uzmc57\">http://goo.gl/uzmc57</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/\">http://www.liveout.org/</a>','On the Hunt: Is it fair to use hunting drones to track prey?','','inherit','open','open','','105-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:53:44','2015-03-06 22:53:44','',105,'http://localhost/blog/105-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(421,1,'2015-03-06 22:56:11','2015-03-06 22:56:11','Stay warmer, shred longer.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deals_Under Armour','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deals_under-armour-3','','','2015-03-06 22:56:29','2015-03-06 22:56:29','',30,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deals_Under-Armour2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(422,1,'2015-03-06 22:58:01','2015-03-06 22:58:01','Save on gear that gets you outside.','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_REI_Save on gear that gets you outside','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_rei_save-on-gear-that-gets-you-outside-2','','','2015-03-06 22:58:18','2015-03-06 22:58:18','',30,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_REI_Save-on-gear-that-gets-you-outside1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(423,1,'2015-03-06 22:58:22','2015-03-06 22:58:22','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe recently had the chance to catch up with professional mountain biker &amp; GoPro athlete Kelly McGarry. You may remember Kelly from last year\'s Red Bull Rampage as the guy who busted out a back-flip over the 72-ft canyon during the middle of his silver medal run. In case you missed it, check out this rad video:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x76VEPXYaI0\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo we sat down Kelly to hear about his plans, goals, and passion for mountain biking...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What motivates you to ride &amp; what do you enjoy most about it?</strong>\r\n\r\nI guess one of the main things I enjoy about riding is sessioning with my mates, its always fun and motivates me to get my bike out and go shred.. We have plenty of laughs when we are riding and that\'s what its all about!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>How do you normally find new places to ride?</strong>\r\n\r\nI normally find new places to ride by talking to friends who tell me about new areas they have ridden recently, but if I\'m scoping out new free ride zones I check out Google maps and satellite photos to search for awesome terrain and scree slopes etc.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What\'s your all-time favorite trail &amp; why?</strong>\r\n\r\nMy fav trail is called \"Rude Rock\" its here in Queenstown its flowwy and has great views!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>What\'s your favorite trick &amp; the trick you find most challenging?</strong>\r\n\r\nMy fav trick is probably a big ol floaty Back flip on a BIG jump! and the trick I find the most challenging is Tailwhips, they annoy me a lot!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>How has the sport evolved since you started riding? Do you hope it will continue to evolve &amp; if so, in what new directions can you see it going?</strong>\r\n\r\nYeah our sport is so young really, equipment, riding style, riding amplitude and tricks have progressed hugely over the last few years. As the sport evolves more we are only going to see things getting wilder!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>What career achievement you are most proud of?</strong>\r\n\r\nI am pretty stoked on my 2nd place at Red Bull Rampage last year, it the gnarliest comp of the year and it was a pretty big honor to stand on the podium!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>What is your ultimate goal as a rider?</strong>\r\n\r\nI think my ultimate goal is to have fun!, if its not fun there is no point in doing it if you are not stoked. I also love to ride my bike on terrain that has never been ridden before.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>What\'s the #1 thing to do / place to visit on your Bucket List?</strong>\r\n\r\nI want to travel to Africa at some point, I would love to check out the culture, go for a surf ( hopefully avoiding donating my leg to a shark!) ride my bike and most of all check out the wildlife.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>What are some of your other outdoor hobbies besides riding?</strong>\r\n\r\nI like to surf, we live 2 hours away from the waves but when the forecast is good we head out there. I love being on the coast and its good to have a chill off the bike every now and then.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Gotta ask, What was going through your head just before you did the back flip over the canyon at the 2013 Red Bull Rampage? Did you plan it, or did it it just sort of happen in the moment?</strong>\r\n\r\nHahah I have had that question a few times... Yeah I did plan it, I thought about it for a while... I was mostly reminding myself to \"spin slow,spin slow\" it was such a big jump I knew I didn\'t need to pull back much at all, it was awesome feeling I want to do it again!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>What does the expression Live Out mean to you?</strong>\r\n\r\nGet outside and live your dream!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Would you consider using Live Out to find new trails when you come to the U.S.?</strong>\r\n\r\nYeah for sure, it\'s sometimes hard when you are traveling to find places to shred and people to shred them with, Live Out is a good way to get in touch with people that want to do the same stuff as you do.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nConnect with Kelly!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/kellymcgarrymtb?fref=nf\">https://www.facebook.com/kellymcgarrymtb?fref=nf</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://twitter.com/kellymcgazza\">https://twitter.com/kellymcgazza</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://instagram.com/kellymcgazza/\">https://instagram.com/kellymcgazza/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nInterview by Scott McGuire\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About Live Out</strong>\r\n\r\nLive Out is a new web-app &amp; social network where you can find people with outdoor interests, discover the best places to go &amp; find fun things to do outdoors near you.','Catching Up With Pro Mountain Biker Kelly McGarry','','inherit','open','open','','30-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 22:58:22','2015-03-06 22:58:22','',30,'http://localhost/blog/30-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(424,1,'2015-03-06 23:03:53','2015-03-06 23:03:53','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Athens, GA </b>February, 2015\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis winter, Live Out Enterprise LLC will launch Live Out 2.0 - an online app and social network to connect and inspire outdoor enthusiasts.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out was first introduced in January 2014, ringing in the new year with a bang. Developed by a group of outdoor enthusiasts on a mission to utilize technology to enhance the experience of outdoor activities, Live Out helps you meet people online with common interests and find fun things to do and places to go for all kinds of recreation activities - from camping, hiking, and fishing, to bicycling, skateboarding, and long distance triathlons. The main features of Live Out are its member directory, custom map, digital media and event marketing tools, and the bucket list - all integrated into one seamless and user-friendly app designed to connect the outdoor community with each other and to the outdoors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out’s comprehensive map is powered by Google Maps and aggregates over 200,000 locations for outdoor recreation and adventure sports in the US to help members discover new places to visit and find fun stuff to do in their area for the outdoor activities they like. Members can search where to go for a specific activity or conduct a localized search to find out what to do nearby.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out’s social networking platform lists members based on the outdoor activities they like, making it easy to meet new people with common interests and experience levels. Members can upload photos and videos, post status updates, and send / receive friend requests, invites, and messages to one another directly through the app.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out’s digital media and event marketing tools allow members to check out local events, create new ones, and make plans on short notice with group alerts and instant messaging. Those with big plans can venture over to the bucket list to get new outdoor activity ideas and check out what other people are up to and wanting to do. Members can share their own bucket list ideas and find others with similar ambitions to explore the outdoor world and live out their dreams with.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhether you’re looking to make new friends, or traveling to an unfamiliar area and want to find out where to go, an outdoor aficionado or just someone who likes to get out on the weekends, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network is something to check out.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn celebration of their anticipated re-launch, Live Out is hosting the Live Out 2.0 Giveaway and awarding outdoor gear to their fans on Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, and Instagram.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLive Out is free to join and can be found at <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Charlie West\r\n\r\nOutdoor Enthusiast &amp; Writer\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Make new friends and discover the best places to go outdoors near you with Live Out 2.0','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2015-03-06 23:03:53','2015-03-06 23:03:53','',16,'http://localhost/blog/16-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(426,1,'2015-03-07 00:31:42','2015-03-07 00:31:42','Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network Refer a Friend Program','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Refer a Friend Program','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_refer-a-friend-program','','','2015-03-07 00:32:08','2015-03-07 00:32:08','',327,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Refer-a-Friend-Program.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(427,1,'2015-03-07 00:41:29','2015-03-07 00:41:29','','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Refer a Friend Program_2','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_refer-a-friend-program_2','','','2015-03-07 00:41:29','2015-03-07 00:41:29','',327,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Refer-a-Friend-Program_2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(428,1,'2015-03-07 00:59:34','2015-03-07 00:59:34','','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Refer a Friend Program_3','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_refer-a-friend-program_3','','','2015-03-07 00:59:34','2015-03-07 00:59:34','',327,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Refer-a-Friend-Program_3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(429,1,'2015-03-07 01:01:11','2015-03-07 01:01:11','','Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Under-Armour','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_deal-of-the-day_under-armour-3','','','2015-03-07 01:01:11','2015-03-07 01:01:11','',327,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Deal-of-the-Day_Under-Armour1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(430,1,'2015-03-07 01:01:20','2015-03-07 01:01:20','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe recently had a chance to catch up with professional mountain biker and two-time Red Bull Rampage Champion Kyle Strait to learn more about his plans, goals, and passion for mountain biking...\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>When did you first get into the sport?</b>\r\n\r\nI grew up racing downhill and slalom at the age of 10 all around the US and when I wasn\'t racing I liked to dirt jump and hone my skills on jumps and drops. When the first Rampage event came up I was excited to see what I could do. Being only 14 I wasn\'t really sure how it would go but I ended up making it to the finals placing 8th. And so the Rampage began and I happened to be at the start of all of it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What motivates you to ride? What do you enjoy most about it?</b>\r\n\r\nI love being able to create/build just about anything I can think of and ride it. This keeps me going to push the limits of myself.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How do you normally find new places to ride?</b>\r\n\r\nNew places to ride are very hard to come by. Mostly on film trips we sometimes get lucky in finding new spots to ride and build.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How would you describe your mind-set before entering a competition?</b>\r\n\r\nI basically try and calm myself down as much as I can before dropping in on a run. I had already thought about what I was planning on doing and just have to keep calm.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Which trick do you enjoy the most and which do you find the most challenging?</b>\r\n\r\nI really enjoy doing whips. They are the most fun and aren\'t always easy to look good on new jumps. Would say for me the most challenging would be flip tricks. I am not too good at them but have been working on them to get better at them. Flip-whips I suck at. haha\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How has the sport progressed since you started? In what new directions do you see it going?</b>\r\n\r\nAfter a lot of the riders started learning to flip and 360 drops the sport progressed like crazy, all of a sudden there were now 10 riders that were able to win an event. I see it staying in the same direction it has been going, up and coming riders see what we are doing as of now and see it as thats what you have to do to be a pro and in-turn makes them become amazing riders.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>We\'ve noticed you prefer not to wear much upper body protection during competitionâEUR¦ Is that just to impress the ladies or do you find that it interferes with your riding?</b>\r\n\r\nGrowing up I wore every piece of protection you could find at the time and once I grew to the size I am now body armor stopped fitting me. It became really restrictive while I rode and ended up making me crash more. So since then I choose not to wear it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How many bones have you broke in your lifetime?</b>\r\n\r\nTo be honest I don\'t think that many. 5 is the number and plan on keeping it that way.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Worst injury ever?</b>\r\n\r\nI broke my back a few years ago and that was by far the worst. It took me quite a few months to recover and even longer getting my confidence back up.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>We\'re big fans of the moto that \"It\'s not how many times you fall down; it\'s how many times you get back up.\" Any good wipeout stories/videos you\'d like to share with us?</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nHere are my two favorite…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n\'\'Lose it fast, and when you\'re on the edge you\'re out of control.\'\' - Days of Thunder (movie)\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n\"You can do anything you put your mind to\" - Shaun Palmer\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What achievement you are most proud of?</b>\r\n\r\nBeing the first rider to ever win Rampage twice.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Who is your role model?</b>\r\n\r\nIt comes down to a few, Shaun Palmer, Kirt Voreis, Colin Bailey.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What is your ultimate goal?</b>\r\n\r\nEndless Saturdays?? Ha well to be able to keep riding my bike for a living and teach others to become a better rider.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Advice for someone just starting out?</b>\r\n\r\nStay within your skill level but to be ready for the time to push yourself.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What\'s the #1 thing to do / place to visit on your Bucket List?</b>\r\n\r\nJapan! I have always wanted to go there for the riding and to see that place.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What are some of your other outdoor hobbies besides mountain biking?</b>\r\n\r\nI fish a lot. Salt water and Bass fishing. Pretty much everywhere I go I try to bring a rod with me.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What have you been up to lately?</b>\r\n\r\nAfter Rampage I took some time off the bike and enjoyed the sun. Living in southern California allows me to be able to have somewhat of a second summer. The season is starting to kick into gear, starting off great with a second place at the Sea Otter Dual Slalom and have been doing quite a few film projects.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How are you getting ready for this year\'s Red Bull Rampage?</b>\r\n\r\nFirst by making sure my bike is dialed along with hitting a lot of big jumps and feeling really comfortable on my bike.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>For those less familiar with free-riding, how would you best describe it?</b>\r\n\r\nNo rules, if you can build it you can ride it. Its not against a clock only against yourself.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>When you bust out a trick - like the no-hander, for instance - does earn you points? or is it just for show?</b>\r\n\r\nOh yeah big time on the points. Contest like Rampage judge you on everything while adding points like that.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What kind of planning and preparation goes into scouting out and building your own line before a freeride competition like the Red Bull Rampage?</b>\r\n\r\nIt take a ton of time finding and planning out where you want to go on your line. Once you have your line figured out you only get 4 days to build that line and ride it before the comp starts. It makes it really hard on the riders but its what you\'ve got to do. It would be nice to have a few weeks to ride and build but its not in that cards.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How big a factor is wind/weather in these competitions? What kind of last-minute changes are required if this becomes an issue?</b>\r\n\r\nIts a major factor. If you get wind blow there is nothing you can really do while in the air. It can take out the best of riders and end your day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Are you a fan of the wooden structures in free-ride events, or would you prefer natural terrain only?</b>\r\n\r\nI am really only a fan if it makes sense on the course. Sometimes things are built that should be out there.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>3-peat?</b>\r\n\r\nDUH. Ha yeah you sure bet I am going to put everything into this years rampage as I have done in the past.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Would you consider using Live Out to find new places to shred and the people to go with?</strong>\r\n\r\nYeah sounds great.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What\'s next for you?</b>\r\n\r\nI have quite a few comps and races coming up. National Champs, RedBull Wide Open, teaching camps at Highland Mountain bike park, Crankworx and Rampage. Just to name a few.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWell there you have it. Connect with Kyle on Facebook to keep up with what\'s new!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Kyle-Strait/159652520741448\">https://www.facebook.com/pages/Kyle-Strait/159652520741448</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nGood luck to Kyle and the rest of the competitors this year! - The Live Out Team\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nInterview by Scott McGuire\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About Live Out</b>\r\n\r\nLive Out is a web-based app and social network that encourages and enables participation in outdoor activities by helping people to meet others with common outdoor interests and find the best local places to go for their favorite activities. We facilitate event planning and advocate outdoor recreation programs to connect outdoor enthusiasts and create new ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Interview With Two-Time Red Bull Rampage Champion Kyle Strait','','inherit','open','open','','327-revision-v1','','','2015-03-07 01:01:20','2015-03-07 01:01:20','',327,'http://localhost/blog/327-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(431,1,'2015-03-07 02:22:57','2015-03-07 02:22:57','a:6:{s:8:\"location\";a:1:{i:0;a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:\"param\";s:12:\"options_page\";s:8:\"operator\";s:2:\"==\";s:5:\"va