alt)','top_ad_-_title','publish','open','open','','field_54fa61218a3f1','','','2015-03-07 02:23:43','2015-03-07 02:23:43','',431,'http://localhost/blog/?post_type=acf-field&p=434',2,'acf-field','',0),(435,1,'2015-03-07 02:24:49','2015-03-07 02:24:49','','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Refer a Friend Program_3','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_refer-a-friend-program_3-2','','','2015-03-07 02:24:49','2015-03-07 02:24:49','',0,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Refer-a-Friend-Program_31.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(436,1,'2015-03-07 02:31:31','2015-03-07 02:31:31','','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Refer a Friend Program_3','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_refer-a-friend-program_3-3','','','2015-03-07 02:31:31','2015-03-07 02:31:31','',0,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Refer-a-Friend-Program_32.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(437,1,'2015-03-10 23:57:39','2015-03-10 23:57:39','It can be overwhelming to plan and budget travel in Europe. Any place imaginable is only a few hours away by train or plane, and there’s no shortage of exciting things to do in any destination. Sometimes there’s a place you just can’t leave Europe without visiting, and others it simply comes down to cost.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those who have a desire to travel but no specific destination in mind, Google flights is an amazing tool (<a href=\"http://www.google.com/flights\">www.google.com/flights</a>). You can type in your starting point and the dates you’d like to travel, and google will generate the lowest plane fares for multiple cities to give you the cheap travel destinations for that time. The tool starts with a nice map with the price of major cities easy to find and read, plus the option to zoom in on a specific areas to get information on smaller cities. Then it leads you right up to actually booking your flight, showing options for each direction of the trip and adjusting overall prices based on airlines and times you choose. It’s almost a better recipe for adventure than throwing a dart at a map...instead, decide when to travel, sit back, let Google tell you what your cheapest destination is, and just go. The tool is useful for comparing airlines if you’ve already got a place in mind, too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTo plan cheap travel with a set destination, or more than one destination, Rome2Rio (<a href=\"http://www.rome2rio.com\">www.rome2rio.com</a>) is a helpful resource to compile every option for getting from point A to point B. The biggest perk of this one is the inclusiveness of the cheap travel options it provides. Instead of searching airlines and trains and buses and rideshare websites all separately, Rome2Rio compares them all in one place. It displays all of these modes of travel, and every possible combination of them: a bus to one city then a train the the final destination, two different trains, etc. It’s also great for planning journeys with multiple stops since it’s geared toward one-way travel; I’ve planned a trip with a train to Paris, a flight to Budapest, and a bus to Prague. One downfall of the site is that with things like bus schedules that might operate on a weekly or even monthly basis, it can be difficult to get accurate options for the day you actually intend to travel. Their accuracy depends on how much information you give them; dates, for example, aren’t required in a search but will drastically impact the prices of flights and even train travel. Some things, like trains, are simple to book directly through Rome2Rio, but booking does get messy when it comes to buses and flights as information gets lost from one website to another. The format of the site as a whole is a bit more glitchy than good ol’ Google, but it’s a great place to start looking over options.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAside from those couple of search engines, it’s always a good idea to look for any sort of discount card you can purchase at the beginning of your travels. For example, in France there’s a “Carte Jeune” available for anyone age 12-27. It costs 50 euros but even after just a few trips with the TGV or TER in France, the savings quickly trump the price to make the cheap option of train travel even cheaper. The earlier in your travels you get one, the more savings you can take advantage of.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRyanair has a wide range of destinations and some good search options on <a href=\"http://www.ryanair.com\">www.ryanair.com</a>, and their tickets are often the cheapest option. It’s important to remember that you get the flight experience you pay for: Ryanair often flies out of more remote airports and runs a bit behind schedule with little communication with its customers. It’s a good idea to research the exact locations of the airport you’re considering flying through, and to check on the costs of transport into the city itself from the airport. There’s also something to be said for reading the fine print with Ryanair. Their “printing fees” and baggage policies can end up costing more than the ticket itself. Still, with the right research and preparation and a bit of patience at the airport, Ryanair is still a great option for traveling on a budget.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>The internet is a wonderful resource for travelers! I know I would be lost without it (and not in the good way), and these methods in particular have led me to some amazing, cheap travel experiences. The options are overwhelming and the destinations are endless - but that’s certainly not a bad thing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Elizabeth Thompson\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>','Finding Cheap Travel Options in Europe','','