e worst. It took me quite a few months to recover and even longer getting my confidence back up.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>We\'re big fans of the motto that \"It\'s not how many times you fall down; it\'s how many times you get back up.\" Any good wipeout stories/videos you\'d like to share with us?</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nHere are my two favorite…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n\'\'Lose it fast, and when you\'re on the edge you\'re out of control.\'\' - Days of Thunder (movie)\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n\"You can do anything you put your mind to\" - Shaun Palmer\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What achievement you are most proud of?</b>\r\n\r\nBeing the first rider to ever win Rampage twice.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Who is your role model?</b>\r\n\r\nIt comes down to a few, Shaun Palmer, Kirt Voreis, Colin Bailey.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What is your ultimate goal?</b>\r\n\r\nEndless Saturdays?? Ha well to be able to keep riding my bike for a living and teach others to become a better rider.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Advice for someone just starting out?</b>\r\n\r\nStay within your skill level but to be ready for the time to push yourself.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What\'s the #1 thing to do / place to visit on your Bucket List?</b>\r\n\r\nJapan! I have always wanted to go there for the riding and to see that place.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What are some of your other outdoor hobbies besides mountain biking?</b>\r\n\r\nI fish a lot. Salt water and Bass fishing. Pretty much everywhere I go I try to bring a rod with me.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What have you been up to lately?</b>\r\n\r\nAfter Rampage I took some time off the bike and enjoyed the sun. Living in southern California allows me to be able to have somewhat of a second summer. The season is starting to kick into gear, starting off great with a second place at the Sea Otter Dual Slalom and have been doing quite a few film projects.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How are you getting ready for this year\'s Red Bull Rampage?</b>\r\n\r\nFirst by making sure my bike is dialed along with hitting a lot of big jumps and feeling really comfortable on my bike.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>For those less familiar with free-riding, how would you best describe it?</b>\r\n\r\nNo rules, if you can build it you can ride it. Its not against a clock only against yourself.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>When you bust out a trick - like the no-hander, for instance - does earn you points? or is it just for show?</b>\r\n\r\nOh yeah big time on the points. Contest like Rampage judge you on everything while adding points like that.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What kind of planning and preparation goes into scouting out and building your own line before a freeride competition like the Red Bull Rampage?</b>\r\n\r\nIt take a ton of time finding and planning out where you want to go on your line. Once you have your line figured out you only get 4 days to build that line and ride it before the comp starts. It makes it really hard on the riders but its what you\'ve got to do. It would be nice to have a few weeks to ride and build but its not in that cards.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>How big a factor is wind/weather in these competitions? What kind of last-minute changes are required if this becomes an issue?</b>\r\n\r\nIts a major factor. If you get wind blow there is nothing you can really do while in the air. It can take out the best of riders and end your day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Are you a fan of the wooden structures in free-ride events, or would you prefer natural terrain only?</b>\r\n\r\nI am really only a fan if it makes sense on the course. Sometimes things are built that should be out there.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>3-peat?</b>\r\n\r\nDUH. Ha yeah you sure bet I am going to put everything into this years rampage as I have done in the past.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Would you consider using Live Out to find new places to shred and the people to go with?</strong>\r\n\r\nYeah sounds great.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>What\'s next for you?</b>\r\n\r\nI have quite a few comps and races coming up. National Champs, RedBull Wide Open, teaching camps at Highland Mountain bike park, Crankworx and Rampage. Just to name a few.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nConnect with Kyle on Facebook to keep up with what\'s new!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Kyle-Strait/159652520741448\">https://www.facebook.com/pages/Kyle-Strait/159652520741448</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nGood luck to Kyle and the rest of the competitors this year! - The Live Out Team\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nInterview by Scott McGuire\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Scott-McGuire_Founder_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-447\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Scott-McGuire_Founder_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Scott McGuire\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About Live Out</b>\r\n\r\nLive Out is a web-based app and social network that encourages and enables participation in outdoor activities by helping people to meet others with common outdoor interests and find the best local places to go for their favorite activities. We facilitate event planning and advocate outdoor recreation programs to connect outdoor enthusiasts and create new ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Interview With Two-Time Red Bull Rampage Champion Kyle Strait','','inherit','open','open','','327-revision-v1','','','2015-03-11 00:37:36','2015-03-11 00:37:36','',327,'http://localhost/blog/327-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(449,1,'2015-03-11 00:38:18','2015-03-11 00:38:18','','Finding Cheap Travel Options in Europe','','inherit','open','open','','437-revision-v1','','','2015-03-11 00:38:18','2015-03-11 00:38:18','',437,'http://localhost/blog/437-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(450,1,'2015-03-11 00:38:32','2015-03-11 00:38:32','It can be overwhelming to plan and budget travel in Europe. Any place imaginable is only a few hours away by train or plane, and there’s no shortage of exciting things to do in any destination. Sometimes there’s a place you just can’t leave Europe without visiting, and others it simply comes down to cost.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those who have a desire to travel but no specific destination in mind, Google flights is an amazing tool (<a href=\"http://www.google.com/flights\">www.google.com/flights</a>). You can type in your starting point and the dates you’d like to travel, and google will generate the lowest plane fares for multiple cities to give you the cheap travel destinations for that time. The tool starts with a nice map with the price of major cities easy to find and read, plus the option to zoom in on a specific areas to get information on smaller cities. Then it leads you right up to actually booking your flight, showing options for each direction of the trip and adjusting overall prices based on airlines and times you choose. It’s almost a better recipe for adventure than throwing a dart at a map...instead, decide when to travel, sit back, let Google tell you what your cheapest destination is, and just go. The tool is useful for comparing airlines if you’ve already got a place in mind, too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTo plan cheap travel with a set destination, or more than one destination, Rome2Rio (www.rome2rio.com) is a helpful resource to compile every option for getting from point A to point B. The biggest perk of this one is the inclusiveness of the cheap travel options it provides. Instead of searching airlines and trains and buses and rideshare websites all separately, Rome2Rio compares them all in one place. It displays all of these modes of travel, and every possible combination of them: a bus to one city then a train the the final destination, two different trains, etc. It’s also great for planning journeys with multiple stops since it’s geared toward one-way travel; I’ve planned a trip with a train to Paris, a flight to Budapest, and a bus to Prague. One downfall of the site is that with things like bus schedules that might operate on a weekly or even monthly basis, it can be difficult to get accurate options for the day you actually intend to travel. Their accuracy depends on how much information you give them; dates, for example, aren’t required in a search but will drastically impact the prices of flights and even train travel. Some things, like trains, are simple to book directly through Rome2Rio, but booking does get messy when it comes to buses and flights as information gets lost from one website to another. The format of the site as a whole is a bit more glitchy than good ol’ Google, but it’s a great place to start looking over options.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAside from those couple of search engines, it’s always a good idea to look for any sort of discount card you can purchase at the beginning of your travels. For example, in France there’s a “Carte Jeune” available for anyone age 12-27. It costs 50 euros but even after just a few trips with the TGV or TER in France, the savings quickly trump the price to make the cheap option of train travel even cheaper. The earlier in your travels you get one, the more savings you can take advantage of.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRyanair has a wide range of destinations and some good search options on <a href=\"http://www.ryanair.com\">www.ryanair.com</a>, and their tickets are often the cheapest option. It’s important to remember that you get the flight experience you pay for: Ryanair often flies out of more remote airports and runs a bit behind schedule with little communication with its customers. It’s a good idea to research the exact locations of the airport you’re considering flying through, and to check on the costs of transport into the city itself from the airport. There’s also something to be said for reading the fine print with Ryanair. Their “printing fees” and baggage policies can end up costing more than the ticket itself. Still, with the right research and preparation and a bit of patience at the airport, Ryanair is still a great option for traveling on a budget.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>The internet is a wonderful resource for travelers! I know I would be lost without it (and not in the good way), and these methods in particular have led me to some amazing, cheap travel experiences. The options are overwhelming and the destinations are endless - but that’s certainly not a bad thing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Elizabeth Thompson\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\nhttp://www.liveout.org','Finding Cheap Travel Options in Europe','','inherit','open','open','','437-revision-v1','','','2015-03-11 00:38:32','2015-03-11 00:38:32','',437,'http://localhost/blog/437-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(451,1,'2015-03-11 14:32:11','2015-03-11 14:32:11','Attractive girl enjoying travel to Europe, standing on wonderful colorful buildings background, famous street in Cinque Terre','Enjoying travel to Europe','','inherit','open','open','','enjoying-travel-to-europe','','','2015-03-11 14:32:11','2015-03-11 14:32:11','',437,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015