ong><strong> </strong></strong></em>\r\n\r\nBringing “grasswhoppers” and “cricket cookies” to market will surely be a challenge, but I am optimistic. It’s all about educating the consumer and making the product fun and delicious - and losing the “ick” factor. After all, successful marketing and branding brought bananas into american homes, and sushi and lobster to the tables of our finest restaurants. Slowly, insect protein will make its way into the public forum and before too long it could also be making its way into your hiking pack.\r\n\r\n<em><strong><strong> </strong></strong></em>\r\n\r\nAnd so, I ask you, the reader, the avid outdoorsman, the sustainable savior.. Would you try a cricket protein bar?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em><strong><strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-456\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Michaela Cook_Writer_Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network\" width=\"125\" height=\"125\" /></a></strong></strong></em>\r\n\r\n<b>Michaela Cook</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\"> http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor other comments, suggestions, or feedback related to this article, feel free to email me at michaela@liveout.org.\r\n\r\n<em><strong><strong> </strong></strong></em>\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nMichaela is an outdoor enthusiast, writer, and undergraduate marketing student in the Eller College of Management at the University of Arizona.\r\n\r\n<em> </em>','Would You Eat A Cricket Protein Bar?','','inherit','open','open','','455-revision-v1','','','2015-03-12 15:43:18','2015-03-12 15:43:18','',455,'http://localhost/blog/455-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(466,1,'2015-03-12 16:26:58','2015-03-12 16:26:58','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt’s that time of year – Spring Peepers are deafening campers in all their glory and college students are hovering on travel sites, waiting for a prime deals on epic spring breaks. This “oops, I learned that the hard way” list will help you avoid fun-ruining situations while traveling. Take my word for it, many situations can be avoided just by planning ahead. Don’t ever head out with an “I’ll figure it out as I go” attitude when it comes to where you are sleeping at night. From personal experience, you don’t want to end up setting up your hammock 20ft high in a tree in the middle of San Juan at 4AM.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThree main concerns when travelling:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>1. Hygiene.</b> (Not the ‘re-wearing clothes’ type of hygiene…that’s totally cool)\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>A First Aid Kit is a MUST.  Foreign bacteria can turn minor cuts into trip-ending infections. Put a small dollop of antibiotic cream on ANY open wound, stick a bandage on it, and carry on worry-free. *Carry double antibiotic cream, tweezers, bandages, and a clean rag with you at the very least</li>\r\n <li>Hand Sanitizer – buy it by the truckload. And use it.  Especially before you take your contacts out, and even if you washed your hands. Not every country has the same sanitary standards for their tap water.</li>\r\n <li>Bug Spray – don’t ever assume you will find bug spray where you think you will (Wal-Mart in Puerto Rico only carries wasp spray….). Bugs make camping miserable, and bug bites make everything else miserable. Don’t be miserable.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>2. Language and Culture. </b>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Planning is key! Make sure you research the area you are travelling beforehand, there are often safety concerns for tourists that can be avoided (sections of cities, areas to avoid at night, phrases you shouldn’t say)</li>\r\n  <li>Learn three basic phrases in the indigenous language:\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>“Where is the hospital?” (s*** happens, especially if you’re doing something active)</li>\r\n <li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">“Thank you!” </span></li>\r\n <li><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">“Which way is _____?” (trailhead / water / etc.)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n  <li>Bring two paper maps with you! Circle your intended trails and destinations on one and leave it at your campsite. Circle your campsite on the other and bring it with you. If you get lost, you want to give your search party some indication of where to start looking.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>3. Transportation and Location </b>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li>Figure out AHEAD of time where you are camping / hosteling / etc, and figure out how you are getting there. “I’ll figure it out as I go” is a recipe for disaster. *By the way, did you know that there is no public camping in France? It is super illegal to pitch a tent anywhere that is not specifically marked as a campsite by the government.</li>\r\n  <li>Carry an emergency contact card on your person at all time. Be sure to include your blood type, name, and emergency contact information. It takes like three seconds to make - don’t be lazy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>4. Unpredictable Weather</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Dry bags – you can get a set of three for as little as $10. Put your phone, emergency contact card, money, and First Aid kit in them. *HAVE EXTRA DRY BAGS – you never know when the skies might open up.</li>\r\n  <li>Small tarp – for as little as $6, you can get an emergency poncho, emergency rain fly, emergency bike cover, emergency rope cover, emergency ANYTHING. A tarp can make a flooded campsite manageable.</li>\r\n  <li>Emergency fire-starter, cordelette, and emergency blanket (in a dry bag)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFor the hefty cost of about $25 and about two hours of Google-ing, you can take some large steps towards having a smoother, safer spring break.  S*** happens, make sure you are prepared. And don’t forget to bring your camera!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAuthor: Sabine Connors\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-467\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Sabine Connors\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nSabine is an outdoor enthusiast, competitive climber, and student at Clemson University in South Carolina. She is a member of Clemson University’s Climbing Club, and likes to spend her free time running and traveling. She is an expert in forgetting to pack extra socks and losing chapstick tubes.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Oops, I learned that the hard way: Tips for Traveling this Spring Break','','publish','open','open','','oops-i-learned-that-the-hard-way-tips-for-traveling-this-spring-break','','','2015-03-12 18:52:11','2015-03-12 18:52:11','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=466',0,'post','',0),(467,1,'2015-03-12 16:26:16','2015-03-12 16:26:16','Sabine is an outdoor enthusiast, competitive climber, and student at Clemson University in South Carolina. She is a member of Clemson University’s Climbing Club, and likes to spend her free time running and traveling. She is an expert in forgetting to pack extra socks and losing chapstick tubes.','Sabine Connors_Writer_Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network','','inherit','open','open','','sabine-connors_writer_live-out_the-outdoor-social-network','','','2015-03-12 16:26:40','2015-03-12 16:26:40','',466,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(468,1,'2015-03-12 16:26:58','2015-03-12 16:26:58','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt’s that time of year – Spring Peep