ur own room or yard, at-home bodyweight workouts are convenient and can take as much time as you choose. The internet is full of <a href=\"http://www.fitnessblender.com/videos/belly-fat-burner-hiit-high-intensity-interval-training-workout-with-no-equipment\">good ideas</a>, from yoga to HIIT circuits, and getting even a few good moves in before a shower can end up being a game-changer! Running is an awesome way to burn off some local cuisine while exploring some side streets and getting to know your new town in a different way. For those who just can’t go a semester without a squat rack, there are often local gyms with student deals that can also be great for meeting locals.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBalancing cultural experiences with your fitness priorities is easier said than done. Time and diet management are both completely thrown off upon arrival, and sometimes they can take weeks or even months to pin down. Studying abroad is anything but routine, and it can be frustrating to notice changes in your body and feel powerless over meals and workout space. Keep in mind that there are plenty of options, be patient with yourself and your body, and remember to keep cultural experiences the first priority.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-494\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"120\" height=\"120\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAuthor: Elizabeth Thompson\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nElizabeth is a college student in love with mountains, oceans and everything in between. Her travel skills and expertise are constantly being refined while she studies abroad for the semester in Aix-en-Provence, France. At her home university in Colorado, she studies Creative Writing, French, and Business in between weekends on a snowboard and summers lost in the mountains.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Struggling to Stay Fit While Studying Abroad','','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-v1','','','2015-03-17 22:38:59','2015-03-17 22:38:59','',492,'http://localhost/blog/492-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(503,1,'2015-03-18 21:06:08','2015-03-18 21:06:08','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nChange is inevitable.  Everything in the entire cosmos is impermanent.  From the changing colors in leaves as Fall kisses Summer goodbye, to the old man staring at a photograph of himself as a boy; everything changes and goes on to contribute in some special way to the great universe that gives life to all. So why is it that we humans are so afraid of this natural cycle?  Is it the unknown?  Or is it some sort of preconditioned fear following us from our childhood?  I cannot precisely answer this question without delving deeper into my own human condition.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIt was late August of 2010. Some buddies and I had been planning a camping trip to the mountains for some time, and now it was time to go. I had suggested one of my favorite spots that I had been travelling to since boyhood: Raven Cliffs Wilderness. Raven Cliffs is located about ten minutes outside of Helen, GA on Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway. Noted as one of Georgia’s best camping and hiking sites, the U.S Congress designated Raven Cliffs as a national wilderness area in 1986 and it boasts over 9,000 acres of protected woodland.  The unique aspect of this area and one of the reasons it is so popular is it is free.  Not even so much as a donation box at the entrance, which is almost a staple of every other national parks recreation center.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAfter hearing about the free camping, my buddies were in. So we loaded up our packs and tents in the back of my friend Chris’ truck, made one last sweep of our checklist, and we were off. I rode shotgun with Chris, while his girlfriend Gabby and our other friend Dave followed behind us in a separate car.  As we were flying North on Interstate 400, windows down and wind screaming through my hair, I couldn’t help a feeling of relief saturate my bones. Life seemed to really be kicking me around at the time, and this is exactly the escape I desperately needed.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe arrived in the town of Helen, GA in mid afternoon and stopped at one of the local watering holes for a few beers then made one final stop at the package store for the nights festivities, before continuing on into the mountains.  As we approached Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway on our right, I asked Chris to turn the music off and roll the windows all the way down.  This was a tradition of mine that I had carried on since I was a kid.  My dad’s little 4-cylinder Toyota pickup would creak and wind its way around the narrow mountain roads, and I would sit there entranced by the sights and sounds of the majestic Chattahoochee National Forest.  So quiet and serene, yet completely alive and vibrant in the cool Appalachian air.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe drove in long “S” patterns up into the mountains, passing lookouts and stop-offs to small trailheads for about 3 or 4 miles until finally I saw the sign up ahead on our left that read, “Raven Cliffs Recreation Area”.  I felt so free and alive in that moment and was so eager to jump out of the truck and run into the woods!  We pulled down the extremely narrow and seemingly one lane road and crossed a small wooden bridge that leads to the main gravel parking area and pulled the truck to a halt right next to the vault-style restrooms.  I leaped out of the truck just as Gabby and Dave pulled in beside us.  Noticing a brightly colored sign pinned to the information billboard next to the bathroom, I walked over and saw that it read, “Beware: Aggressive bear activity in surrounding area.  Store all food in a safe place away from campsite.  Keep small children close and all pets on leashes…”, and on it went.  I thought to myself, “In all my years of coming here, I never once saw a bear. This could be fun!”  Chris came out of the bathroom and accidentally slammed the heavy metal door causing us all to jump a little.  “So where do we camp?”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBehind the restrooms on the other side of a makeshift wooden fence, there is a wide gravel road that stretches for miles and miles into the mountains.  There are campsites scattered on either side of the road for as far as one can drive, all of which have been pretty well established by previous campers or hunters.  During hunting season this whole area is open to hunt anywhere and any wildlife, including bears.  Most all of the campsites border little creeks that run off from the larger Dukes Creek nearby.  I looked at Chris and pointed my eager finger down the gravel road, “Anywhere down thar.” , I said in a country twang.  So we hopped in the truck and caravanned down the bumpy, winding gravel road.  It did not take long to find a really great site, and it was one I remembered camping at a few times before.  As we all piled out and began unloading the gear Gabby shrieked and said she saw a shape up on the road ahead.  We all stood in silence and squinted in the general direction of this supposed shape.  It was getting dark, and we were running out of time to set up camp, so everyone just laughed and commenced to start a fire and set the tents.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe fire began to take on a life of its own without any further coaxing, so we all poured a shot of whiskey and said cheers to the weekend.  That night was the picturesque scene of a group of buddies taking a camping trip.  S’mores, music, fire, creepy sounds coming from the dark forbidden forest, and of course glo-sticks.  My friend Chris has this thing with glowsticks.  Whenever he drinks he takes a string and ties multiple glo-sticks together and swings them around like nunchucks while dancing.  It is quite a hilarious site, and was actually really cool in the dark by a fire.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAfter Chris’ excellent display in the art of glowstick dance, I felt nature calling so I stumbled into the dark somewhere to relieve myself.  I remember looking up at the familiar picture of a million stars lighting up the sky.  They were truly the “Holes to Heaven” as the musician Jack Johnson once put it.  I started thinking to myself how amazing it would be to just live out here with nature, all the cares of my stressful life abandoned somewhere over a distant mountain.  That is the magic of places like these.  They cause the wanderlust in my soul to come alive and I am able to dream and just be free.  As I was daydreaming, (or night dreaming if you will), Gabby yelled at me from the fire to hurry up so I could play some more songs on my guitar.  And the night went on, the drinks got stronger, my music a little sloppier, and the fire slowly faded to ember as we all decided to retire for the night.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe next morning I awoke with a swimming head and a vague recollection of singing “Freebird” at the top of my lungs into the night.  It was a good night.  The first thing I noticed was the cool morning air, that clean, crisp air tinted with the fragrance of the surrounding fir trees and mountain laurel.  I was the first one to rise, so I kindled the fire a bit and made myself a hot dog on a stick over the flame.  Soon after, everyone else willed themselves back to life and joined me by the fire.  Birds were chirping from all directions and the sound of nearby Dukes Creek Falls rushed into our ears.  We decided to take a hike, and I mentioned a “secret” spot that my dad had shown me years prior.  We walked down the gravel road for about half a mile and I turned into a small trail that leads back to yet another campsite.  Arriving at the campsite, Dave looked at me and said, “This is your spot? Coool.”  Sarcasm was written all over his face.  I held my finger to my lips and told him be quiet and listen.  The sound of a waterfall was imminently close.  “That is Dukes Creek Falls my friends, and we are going to hike down that little trail over there to get to the very top of it.”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI led the way as we all carefully made our way down the steep, root-infested trail.  Finally the trail opened up and we looked over a massive valley split in two at the bottom by Dukes Creek.  I showed everyone down to the edge of the falls, where there are numerous spots to sit and look down 150 feet of rocky falls.  At the very bottom, barely visible, there are observation decks that mark the end of Dukes Creek Trail, where thousands of tourists come every year to snap photos of the mammoth natural structure.  My friends were amazed and so we stayed and hung out for a couple hours before heading back to camp.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe rest of the day went on as such: exploring, cooking over the fire, beers, music, etc.  As day gave way to night, we had exhausted ourselves and sat around the fire talking.  This trip had been just what I needed, but the thought of having to return to the real world in the morning almost sickened me.  I felt like something was missing.  I was having a fantastic time with good friends, but I did not feel connected to the nature around me and even felt distant from myself.  I grabbed a glass and poured some whiskey while pondering these thoughts. <i>Why do I feel this way? There has to be something more to this life. What if I just stayed here and let them leave? I have all the necessary equipment and food to be out here for at least a week. </i> It was then and there that I decided to take a leave of absence from society and reconnect with my Source.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nEver since I was a teenager, I have had dreams of hiking the Appalachian Trail, spending months out in the wilderness trekking north through the country.  New faces and amazing sights every day.  The personal freedom and accomplishment of doing something so ruggedly difficult and delicately human left me yearning to join those who had blazed the Trail before me.  Sitting there by the fire, I knew that I would not possibly be able to make that journey at this point in my life.  I simply did not have the means to do so, however maybe I could get a taste of what is like to be alone in the woods, even if only for a short time.  I gazed up at the friends around me and declared, “Guys, I’m staying here in the morning.  Go ahead and go home without me.  I need to do some soul searching.  I need some time away.”  I noticed Dave staring directly at me as the fire illuminated a massive grin on his face. “Who are you Jim Morrison? Ghandi?”  I did not say a word, and then he realized I was serious.  They berated me with the obvious questions and concerns, but I fended them off with the eloquent romance of a man who would not be deterred.  I was staying and that was that.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe next morning I helped everyone pack up their things and load them into the vehicles.  Chris handed me all of the food they had leftover and said, “Make sure to hang this up in case of a massive bear attack. Ya know just in case.”  He grinned at me and asked me if I had my cell phone. I told him I did and that it was off so I could conserve the battery.  It wouldn’t matter, however, because as I would later learn, there was no reception at all there.  That in itself is freedom to me.  We said our goodbyes and I watched them drive off down the gravel road.  When they were out of sight, I listened intently on the sounds of the forest and looked around in all directions.  I was completely alone; yet I felt as if I was accompanied by a silent companion, something much greater than myself.  I felt alive.\r\n\r\nThe next few days I was in a constant state of euphoria, taking in every moment as if it was the first time I had ever taken a breath.  I saw the beauty in everything: the sweet sound of a Meadowlark’s song, the constant rushing about of a mountain stream, even the myriads of dead leaves littering the forest floor.  I took long walks and had conversations with God, the trees, and at times even myself.  It was exhilarating.  The nights were a bit lonesome and scary as I was alone with a small fire in a sea of darkness.  The occasional rustle in the distant bush or spooky call of an owl, jolted me to my senses and put me on high alert, however I was never scared.  I felt at home out there.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nLater on in the week, I returned to my camp from a long morning hike at Raven Cliffs Trail Head.  It was a strenuous five mile in and out hike near the entrance of the recreation area.  The trail runs along a rushing creek and ends at Raven Cliffs, a massive 70 foot wall with a thundering waterfall slicing right through the center.  It was totally worth every step.  I was pretty hungry, so I decided to make myself a sandwich.  I sat by the fire eating and reading, when I happened to look up.  And there he was.  No more than thirty feet in front of me stood a 400-600 pound male blackbear on its hind legs gazing directly at me with his tongue hanging out of his mouth and panting like a dog.  I was frozen with fear.  I sat there for an eternity until I realized I was holding exactly what he wanted. Food.  I slowly rose from my chair and threw the sandwich in his general direction.  He plopped down on all fours and casually walked up to the sandwich and ate it in one bite.  My lack of experience with bears showed clearly in that moment as I turned around and bolted at the speed of light up the hill.  When I reached the gravel road, I turned to look back and saw him wandering through the campsite and then as fast as he had arrived he was gone.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSlowly walking back down to camp, I peered around in every direction suspiciously with senses on high alert.  He was nowhere to be found and I did not see him again that day.  Later I decided to give him a name: Paku.  Over the course of the next 4-5 days, Paku would venture into my camp at least once a day.  I once awoke to him sitting directly outside of my tent eating a candle I had left on one of the stones around the fire.  He ate every bit of that nicely fragranced wax.  My fear finally went away after about the third time seeing him.  He became a friend.  Not the kind of friend I would put my arm around and talk about life with, but a friend nonetheless.  He was a man just like me, scavenging and travelling his way through life in this harsh yet beautiful world.  I admired the kind of man he was as I watched him.  I often wonder how ol’ Paku is doing today.  Is he still out there on the grind, fighting for every morsel of food he can find, or has he found something better?  Easier?  I found a certain kind of truth in that bear that helped shape my character when I finally exited that wilderness.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSo, change.  Before taking that amazing trip, I was not happy with life and was not happy with the person I had become.  I went into it thinking of that forest as a means to escape while I emerged from that same forest with a new outlook on life and many lessons to accompany me on my journey.  The forest taught me that change is inevitable, and that the world around me is still going to spin through its cycles with or without me.  It was and is up to me to spin with it.  I had to return to the world with a resolve to better myself and change the situation I was in and change the boy I was into the man I needed to be.  Much like Paku.  Coming back into the real world, I remember seeing the beauty in the smallest things and the emptiness in the biggest of things.  I have carried these memories with me ever since.  I camped in Raven Cliffs Wilderness for 17 days total, completely alone and almost starving,  but completely at peace and taking in everything I could.  One day I walked out to a main road and got cell phone reception and rang an old friend who just happened to be in the mood for a night of camping.  So he drove up and we drank beer and sat by the fire catching up on life. We decided to leave the next morning and head back home.  I’ll never forget some of the first words he said to me that night: “You have been here how long? And who is Paku? You’re crazy man.”  -MW\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Matt-Wiegand_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-508\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Matt-Wiegand_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Matt Wiegand\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Matt Wiegand</strong>\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nMatt Wiegand is a freelance writer, blogger, and activist for the outdoors, specifically for the preservation of the Appalachian Trail. As a musician, writer, and world traveler, he has sought to better the world we live in by spreading a message of respect and care for our natural environment and our fellow human race.  Matt ,27, lives in Atlanta, GA.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Over the Cliff: A quest to rediscover nature, spirituality, and personal freedom in the Raven Cliffs Wilderness','','publish','open','open','','over-the-cliff','','','2015-03-18 21:29:03','2015-03-18 21:29:03','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=503',0,'post','',0),(504,1,'2015-03-18 20:59:04','2015-03-18 20:59:04','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>My quest to rediscover nature, spirituality, and personal freedom in the Raven Cliffs Wilderness. By Matt Wiegand</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nChange is inevitable.  Everything in the entire cosmos is impermanent.  From the changing colors in leaves as Fall kisses Summer goodbye, to the old man staring at a photograph of himself as a boy; everything changes and goes on to contribute in some special way to the great universe that gives life to all. So why is it that we humans are so afraid of this natural cycle?  Is it the unknown?  Or is it some sort of preconditioned fear following us from our childhood?  I cannot precisely answer this question without delving deeper into my own human condition.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIt was late August of 2010. Some buddies and I had been planning a camping trip to the mountains for some time, and now it was time to go. I had suggested one of my favorite spots that I had been travelling to since boyhood: Raven Cliffs Wilderness. Raven Cliffs is located about ten minutes outside of Helen, GA on Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway. Noted as one of Georgia’s best camping and hiking sites, the U.S Congress designated Raven Cliffs as a national wilderness area in 1986 and it boasts over 9,000 acres of protected woodland.  The unique aspect of this area and one of the reasons it is so popular is it is free.  Not even so much as a donation box at the entrance, which is almost a staple of every other national parks recreation center.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAfter hearing about the free camping, my buddies were in. So we loaded up our packs and tents in the back of my friend Chris’ truck, made one last sweep of our checklist, and we were off. I rode shotgun with Chris, while his girlfriend Gabby and our other friend Dave followed behind us in a separate car.  As we were flying North on Interstate 400, windows down and wind screaming through my hair, I couldn’t help a feeling of relief saturate my bones. Life seemed to really be kicking me around at the time, and this is exactly the escape I desperately needed.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe arrived in the town of Helen, GA in mid afternoon and stopped at one of the local watering holes for a few beers then made one final stop at the package store for the nights festivities, before continuing on into the mountains.  As we approached Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway on our right, I asked Chris to turn the music off and roll the windows all the way down.  This was a tradition of mine that I had carried on since I was a kid.  My dad’s little 4-cylinder Toyota pickup would creak and wind its way around the narrow mountain roads, and I would sit there entranced by the sights and sounds of the majestic Chattahoochee National Forest.  So quiet and serene, yet completely alive and vibrant in the cool Appalachian air.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe drove in long “S” patterns up into the mountains, passing lookouts and stop-offs to small trailheads for about 3 or 4 miles until finally I saw the sign up ahead on our left that read, “Raven Cliffs Recreation Area”.  I felt so free and alive in that moment and was so eager to jump out of the truck and run into the woods!  We pulled down the extremely narrow and seemingly one lane road and crossed a small wooden bridge that leads to the main gravel parking area and pulled the truck to a halt right next to the vault-style restrooms.  I leaped out of the truck just as Gabby and Dave pulled in beside us.  Noticing a brightly colored sign pinned to the information billboard next to the bathroom, I walked over and saw that it read, “Beware: Aggressive bear activity in surrounding area.  Store all food in a safe place away from campsite.  Keep small children close and all pets on leashes…”, and on it went.  I thought to myself, “In all my years of coming here, I never once saw a bear. This could be fun!”  Chris came out of the bathroom and accidentally slammed the heavy