e old man staring at a photograph of himself as a boy; everything changes and goes on to contribute in some special way to the great universe that gives life to all. So why is it that we humans are so afraid of this natural cycle?  Is it the unknown?  Or is it some sort of preconditioned fear following us from our childhood?  I cannot precisely answer this question without delving deeper into my own human condition.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIt was late August of 2010. Some buddies and I had been planning a camping trip to the mountains for some time, and now it was time to go. I had suggested one of my favorite spots that I had been travelling to since boyhood: Raven Cliffs Wilderness. Raven Cliffs is located about ten minutes outside of Helen, GA on Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway. Noted as one of Georgia’s best camping and hiking sites, the U.S Congress designated Raven Cliffs as a national wilderness area in 1986 and it boasts over 9,000 acres of protected woodland.  The unique aspect of this area and one of the reasons it is so popular is it is free.  Not even so much as a donation box at the entrance, which is almost a staple of every other national parks recreation center.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAfter hearing about the free camping, my buddies were in. So we loaded up our packs and tents in the back of my friend Chris’ truck, made one last sweep of our checklist, and we were off. I rode shotgun with Chris, while his girlfriend Gabby and our other friend Dave followed behind us in a separate car.  As we were flying North on Interstate 400, windows down and wind screaming through my hair, I couldn’t help a feeling of relief saturate my bones. Life seemed to really be kicking me around at the time, and this is exactly the escape I desperately needed.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe arrived in the town of Helen, GA in mid afternoon and stopped at one of the local watering holes for a few beers then made one final stop at the package store for the nights festivities, before continuing on into the mountains.  As we approached Richard B. Russell Scenic Highway on our right, I asked Chris to turn the music off and roll the windows all the way down.  This was a tradition of mine that I had carried on since I was a kid.  My dad’s little 4-cylinder Toyota pickup would creak and wind its way around the narrow mountain roads, and I would sit there entranced by the sights and sounds of the majestic Chattahoochee National Forest.  So quiet and serene, yet completely alive and vibrant in the cool Appalachian air.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWe drove in long “S” patterns up into the mountains, passing lookouts and stop-offs to small trailheads for about 3 or 4 miles until finally I saw the sign up ahead on our left that read, “Raven Cliffs Recreation Area”.  I felt so free and alive in that moment and was so eager to jump out of the truck and run into the woods!  We pulled down the extremely narrow and seemingly one lane road and crossed a small wooden bridge that leads to the main gravel parking area and pulled the truck to a halt right next to the vault-style restrooms.  I leaped out of the truck just as Gabby and Dave pulled in beside us.  Noticing a brightly colored sign pinned to the information billboard next to the bathroom, I walked over and saw that it read, “Beware: Aggressive bear activity in surrounding area.  Store all food in a safe place away from campsite.  Keep small children close and all pets on leashes…”, and on it went.  I thought to myself, “In all my years of coming here, I never once saw a bear. This could be fun!”  Chris came out of the bathroom and accidentally slammed the heavy metal door causing us all to jump a little.  “So where do we camp?”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBehind the restrooms on the other side of a makeshift wooden fence, there is a wide gravel road that stretches for miles and miles into the mountains.  There are campsites scattered on either side of the road for as far as one can drive, all of which have been pretty well established by previous campers or hunters.  During hunting season this whole area is open to hunt anywhere and any wildlife, including bears.  Most all of the campsites border little creeks that run off from the larger Dukes Creek nearby.  I looked at Chris and pointed my eager finger down the gravel road, “Anywhere down thar.” , I said in a country twang.  So we hopped in the truck and caravanned down the bumpy, winding gravel road.  It did not take long to find a really great site, and it was one I remembered camping at a few times before.  As we all piled out and began unloading the gear Gabby shrieked and said she saw a shape up on the road ahead.  We all stood in silence and squinted in the general direction of this supposed shape.  It was getting dark, and we were running out of time to set up camp, so everyone just laughed and commenced to start a fire and set the tents.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe fire began to take on a life of its own without any further coaxing, so we all poured a shot of whiskey and said cheers to the weekend.  That night was the picturesque scene of a group of buddies taking a camping trip.  S’mores, music, fire, creepy sounds coming from the dark forbidden forest, and of course glo-sticks.  My friend Chris has this thing with glowsticks.  Whenever he drinks he takes a string and ties multiple glo-sticks together and swings them around like nunchucks while dancing.  It is quite a hilarious site, and was actually really cool in the dark by a fire.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAfter Chris’ excellent display in the art of glowstick dance, I felt nature calling so I stumbled into the dark somewhere to relieve myself.  I remember looking up at the familiar picture of a million stars lighting up the sky.  They were truly the “Holes to Heaven” as the musician Jack Johnson once put it.  I started thinking to myself how amazing it would be to just live out here with nature, all the cares of my stressful life abandoned somewhere over a distant mountain.  That is the magic of places like these.  They cause the wanderlust in my soul to come alive and I am able to dream and just be free.  As I was daydreaming, (or night dreaming if you will), Gabby yelled at me from the fire to hurry up so I could play some more songs on my guitar.  And the night went on, the drinks got stronger, my music a little sloppier, and the fire slowly faded to ember as we all decided to retire for the night.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThe next morning I awoke with a swimming head and a vague recollection of singing “Freebird” at the top of my lungs into the night.  It was a good night.  The first thing I noticed was the cool morning air, that clean, crisp air tinted with the fragrance of the surrounding fir trees and mountain laurel.  I was the first one to rise, so I kindled the fire a bit and made myself a hot dog on a stick over the flame.  Soon after, everyone else willed themselves back to life and joined me by the fire.  Birds were chirping from all directions and the sound of nearby Dukes Creek Falls rushed into our ears.  We decided to take a hike, and I mentioned a “secret” spot that my dad had shown me years prior.  We walked down the gravel road for about half a mile and I turned into a small trail that leads back to yet another campsite.  Arriving at the campsite, Dave looked at me and said, “This is your spot? Coool.”  Sarcasm was written all over his face.  I held my finger to my lips and told him be quiet and listen.  The sound of a waterfall was imminently close.  “That is Dukes Creek Falls my friends, and we are going to hike down that little trail over there to get to the very top of it.”\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI led the way as we all carefully made our way down the steep, r