a candle I had left on one of the stones around the fire.  He ate every bit of that nicely fragranced wax.  My fear finally went away after about the third time seeing him.  He became a friend.  Not the kind of friend I would put my arm around and talk about life with, but a friend nonetheless.  He was a man just like me, scavenging and travelling his way through life in this harsh yet beautiful world.  I admired the kind of man he was as I watched him.  I often wonder how ol’ Paku is doing today.  Is he still out there on the grind, fighting for every morsel of food he can find, or has he found something better?  Easier?  I found a certain kind of truth in that bear that helped shape my character when I finally exited that wilderness.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSo, change.  Before taking that amazing trip, I was not happy with life and was not happy with the person I had become.  I went into it thinking of that forest as a means to escape while I emerged from that same forest with a new outlook on life and many lessons to accompany me on my journey.  The forest taught me that change is inevitable, and that the world around me is still going to spin through its cycles with or without me.  It was and is up to me to spin with it.  I had to return to the world with a resolve to better myself and change the situation I was in and change the boy I was into the man I needed to be.  Much like Paku.  Coming back into the real world, I remember seeing the beauty in the smallest things and the emptiness in the biggest of things.  I have carried these memories with me ever since.  I camped in Raven Cliffs Wilderness for 17 days total, completely alone and almost starving,  but completely at peace and taking in everything I could.  One day I walked out to a main road and got cell phone reception and rang an old friend who just happened to be in the mood for a night of camping.  So he drove up and we drank beer and sat by the fire catching up on life. We decided to leave the next morning and head back home.  I’ll never forget some of the first words he said to me that night: “You have been here how long? And who is Paku? You’re crazy man.”  -MW\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Matt-Wiegand_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-508\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Matt-Wiegand_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Matt Wiegand\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Matt Wiegand</strong>\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nMatt Wiegand is a freelance writer, blogger, and activist for the outdoors, specifically for the preservation of the Appalachian Trail. As a musician, writer, and world traveler, he has sought to better the world we live in by spreading a message of respect and care for our natural environment and our fellow human race.  Matt ,27, lives in Atlanta, GA.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Over the Cliff: A quest to rediscover nature, spirituality, and personal freedom in the Raven Cliffs Wilderness','','inherit','open','open','','503-revision-v1','','','2015-03-18 21:29:03','2015-03-18 21:29:03','',503,'http://localhost/blog/503-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(521,1,'2015-03-21 16:46:03','2015-03-21 16:46:03','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere’s a lot to love about night running. Free sidewalks, cool air, and the excitement of something making your night. For instance, during my first run, I witnessed interpretive dancers having a showcase in front of the court house. But perhaps that’s just my city.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI began running at night as a result of my overflowing schedule and have never looked back. I typically run near well-lit streets as a safety precaution. Busy night streets are intimidating in retrospect, but I found the sounds of cars on pavement to be a more suitable and safer substitute than wearing headphones. Not to mention the lights in my city, the blinking OPEN signs, hanging street lights, contrasting with the dark are really a sight to see. Plus, you don’t have to worry about getting sunburnt. Along with improved sleeping and breathing, night running also improves your sense of coordination. So what holds us back from running at night?\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSometimes, the cons to night running have a tendency to outshine the pros. Things like swerving cars and predators, both human and animal, can give exercising at night a negative stigma. While these threats are real, try not to let them hinder your freedom and goals. Take a look at these six tips to help limit your worries when out for a jog:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#1 Try running against traffic</strong>\r\n\r\nTypically, you want to avoid running along busy streets in the dark, but sometimes it is the only option if you crave a night run. Running the opposite way of traffic gives you a better, clearer view of oncoming cars. In the case of a rogue driver, you are better equipped to evade an incident.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#2 Wear Reflective Gear</strong>\r\n\r\nLet drivers know you’re there. Reflective clothes include anything neon or brightly colored. Shoes, jackets, hats. You may even consider a headlamp if you’re into that sort of thing. As long as drivers are alerted of your presence, the gear is doing its job. Check out Nike’s We Run the Night collection of gear <a href=\"http://www.nike.com/us/en_us/c/running/we-run-the-night\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#3 Headphones?</strong>\r\n\r\nNo headphones. While bringing along music is comforting on long runs, they are a safety hazard. If something is happening out of sight, you need to able to hear it, unlikely if your ears are plugged up. As expressed earlier, sometimes the night offers its own satisfying sounds, like crickets growing louder the darker it gets or the cluster of engines stopping and starting. Still, if you’re adamant about not having music for sing-a-long purposes, you can invest in an armband music holder for a device that plays out loud from Target or Bestbuy, or you can make one yourself like <a href=\"http://www.cnet.com/how-to/diy-a-dead-simple-workout-armband/\">this</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#4 Buddy System</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople are less likely to be attacked if they are not alone. I occasionally bring a buddy along, one that can keep up anyways. While I do prefer to go it alone, I understand that being 5’3’’ and 115 lbs. makes me an easy target. These next tips are precautions to take if heading out solo.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#5 Keep your ID on hand</strong>\r\n\r\nIf an incident does occur when you’re out, it is best to have an ID on you. In a matter involving the police or an ambulance they need to identify you to call your emergency contacts. Very intense, I know.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>#6 Carry a cellphone</strong>\r\n\r\nMake sure your I.C.E. or “in case of emergency” numbers are easily accessed for you or a helpful stranger. Also, if you have a less than perfect sense of direction, your phone’s GPS may come in handy. Program the route you’re taking before you head out and you’re set.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow I know this may seem like a lot to think about, but trust me taking the proper safety precautions can help free your worries and allow you to get more enjoyment out of your run.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-522\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Angela Bell\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Angela Bell</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAngela is graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','6 Safety Tips for Night Running','','publish','open','open','','6-safety-tips-for-night-running','','','2015-03-21 16:48:21','2015-03-21 16:48:21','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=521',0,'post','',0),(522,1,'2015-03-21 16:22:23','2015-03-21 16:22:23','Angela is graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.','Angela Bell_Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network','','inherit','open','open','','angela-bell_live-out_the-outdoor-social-network','','','2015-03-21 16:22:38','2015-03-21 16:22:38','',521,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(523,1,'2015-03-21 16:39:26','2015-03-21 16:39:26','','Empty street at night','','inherit','open','open','','empty-street-at-night','','','2015-03-21 16:39:26','2015-03-21 16:39:26','',521,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Night-running.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(524,1,'2015-03-21 16:42:28','2015-03-21 16:42:28','Shop Womens Running Clothes','Under Armour_Womens Run','','inherit','open','open','','under-armour_womens-run','','','2015-04-10 00:05:42','2015-04-10 00:05:42','',521,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Under-Armour_Womens-Run.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(525,1,'2015-03-21 16:45:46','2015-03-21 16:45:46','','Institue for Vibrant Living_Natural Health Supplements','','inherit','open','open','','institue-for-vibrant-living_natural-health-supple