ly wanted to pay a hundred dollars for something that was a glorified pedometer and an ugly accessory. I decided to let other people be the guinea pigs and wait for new bands with better technology.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nA year or so into the fitness tracker fad, I began to ask people what they thought of their trackers. Of all the people I asked, not one of them regretted getting it. Some people were even fiercely devoted to the brand of tracker they wore. After such a positive consensus I decided to invest in one.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDeciding what tracker to get can be difficult because of the abundance of trackers and their functions. Every tracker counts steps, but things like sleep monitoring, floors climbed, heart rate, water intake, and so many other options are not universally available. For example, Fitbit has different levels of trackers with more functions in the more complicated models. Nike has their FuelBand that awards Nike Fuel based on the users level of activity. Jawbone also has different models of trackers available, but none with a display screen. <a href=\"http://www.avantlink.com/click.php?tt=ml&amp;ti=3402&amp;pw=152369\">REI</a> has a great selection if you\'re looking for one that fits your needs.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI ended up picking the <a href=\"https://www.fitbit.com/flex#i.13aq7gfs6nctq1\">Fitbit flex</a> which tracks my steps, calories burned, distance traveled, active minutes and sleep. It also let me track my water and food intake. I bought the tracker about four or five months ago, and it has been on my wrist every day since. It syncs with my phone using Bluetooth, gives you access to a community of people online who have the same tracker, and lets you challenge people in your friends list.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs a competitive person, the tracker has been very beneficial. On days where I haven’t reached my goal, I walk extra laps around the floor I live on or I walk the long way home. I originally went with a simple step goal and raised the bar each time I reached my step goal for a week. I’ve now set my sights on taking at least 10,000 steps a day, having a minimum of 25 active minutes, and burning as close to 3,500 calories as possible (not counting my calorie intake for the day).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHaving a fitness tracker has been a wake up call and motivating factor on days where I haven’t needed to take as many steps. It encourages me to walk a few more steps to hit my goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile having a fitness tracker may not be a life-changing thing, it has been a great investment for me personally and I would highly recommend picking one up if you\'re looking to be more active, get outside more and achieve your fitness goals. Fitness trackers are available at most major retailers including Target, Walmart, Bestbuy, and the Apple store.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-550\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.','Fitness Trackers: Are They Worth it?','','publish','open','open','','fitness-trackers-are-they-worth-it','','','2015-03-30 18:26:49','2015-03-30 18:26:49','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=545',0,'post','',0),(546,1,'2015-03-23 19:51:52','2015-03-23 19:51:52','Outdoor gear','REI outdoor gear','','inherit','open','open','','rei-outdoor-gear','','','