eded to take as many steps. It encourages me to walk a few more steps to hit my goals.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile having a fitness tracker may not be a life-changing thing, it has been a great investment for me personally and I would highly recommend picking one up if you\'re looking to be more active, get outside more and achieve your fitness goals. Fitness trackers are available at most major retailers including Target, Walmart, Bestbuy, and the Apple store.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-550\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.','Fitness Trackers: Are They Worth it?','','inherit','open','open','','545-revision-v1','','','2015-03-23 20:13:46','2015-03-23 20:13:46','',545,'http://localhost/blog/545-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(554,1,'2015-03-26 18:26:33','2015-03-26 18:26:33','The dull days of winter will be out the door soon, but until then we have a few more cold, rainy days to deal with— why not bring your favorite outdoor activities inside? Use this ambivalent season to get in shape for your favorite spring and summer activities— and of course your favorite swimsuit— without spending an excess amount of money at the local gym.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nKayaking or rafting lover? Get those arms in shape so you can hit the rapids without waking up the next day to overused, limp muscles. Resistance bands are all the rage for a good reason. The inconsistent pull effectively mimics that of water rapids hitting your paddles at unexpected angles. So if you’re an avid rafter or kayaker— grab that resistant band and tone up your biceps, triceps and shoulders. This video has some resistance bands exercises that will tone you up fast: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts</a>. This guy uses a tree, but you can do the exercises indoors on a staircase post. It also wouldn’t hurt you to do some weighted rowing motions while you sit around watching TV. Throw in some stability ball exercises, and your balance will be set for whatever comes your way. Another great way to get those arms in shape is to punch it out on a weighted bag. Use all your favorite punches— jab, cross, hook and uppercut to prepare for all the arm muscles you\'ll be working this summer on the water.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf your greatest love is rock climbing, an easy and obvious fix is to go to the local indoor rock wall as much as possible. If there isn’t a climbing gym near you or you don’t want to fork out the money, practice these tips: Your hand strength will most likely be out of shape so practice hand techniques on a grip, a stress ball or by pinching putty— check out this inexpensive Gripmaster <a href=\"http://www.mmawarehouse.com/pro_hands_gripmaster_hand_exerciser/prh-1001-0001.html?gdftrk=gdfV23691_a_7c1696_a_7c7969_a_7cprh_d_1001_d_0001&amp;gclid=CPLw1cyWxMQCFUvl7AodaigA1w\">here</a>. Pull ups are an awesome way to get used to dragging your body weight up the rock and to work your whole upper body. If pull-ups are a breeze, then add a weight belt or vest. There is always a way to make your work out more challenging. You also use a surprising amount of core strength in climbing so grab a 10 pound medicine ball and bust out some sit ups and trunk twists. Last, but definitely not least, leg strength is vital to your performance. Strengthen your entire leg with deep squat jumps, weighted lunges, and intense mountain climbers— which will also work those abs. Also throw in some burpees for good measure. Make sure you are doing all these exercises in a sequence, so they are all worked equally in a timely manner. When you climb that mountain, you’ll be using these muscles all at the same time. Don’t forget to also condition your body for the stretch it will be making in reaching and stabilizing— yoga is an awesome go-to for this.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are an avid cyclist, you’ve probably been riding all winter despite the cold and wet. If you think it is something you’d like to start pursuing when the weather warms up— a bike trainer is a must (assuming you have a bike). If you don’t have a bike, maybe try out a stationary one before you make the big purchase. A trainer is an awesome investment because you can use it year-round. You can dictate the resistance and incline (add some books under the front wheel if you don’t have this feature) to make your workout more challenging. Just pop your bike into place and go. Turn on your favorite TV show and practice interval training— 10-15 intervals 30 seconds on then 30 seconds off or an even higher time frame depending on your skill level. If you don’t have a couple hundred dollars in your budget, look on Craigslist for a gently used trainer.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nA trip to the beach is in the near future for many of us so now is the ideal time to amp up our surfing readiness. Surfing is a fine combination of arm strength, core strength, and balance. The first tip is to condition your upper arms and pecs for paddling into those waves, which requires strength and endurance. Grab that resistance band we talked about earlier and a stability ball. Lie with your stomach on the ball and your chest lifted, legs planted. With a band handle in each hand and the middle of the band wrapped around a stair railing or another solid piece of furniture, create a pulley system. Pull your arms toward your legs in a swimming motion. This will take core strength and leg strength to keep yourself from rolling forward. It also adds an extra challenge similar to that of balancing on your board while you paddle. Since this one is a little complicated here is a photo:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://surfnsnowfitness.com/paddle-fitness-for-surfing/\">Photo cred</a>. You can also find more tips at that site.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSingle leg burpees will help strengthen your quads and hamstrings, as well as your arms, for those fluid pop ups. Speaking of pop ups, you can also practice them on your bed because it will add the advantage of balancing on an uneven service. There are numerous exercises you can do to prepare you for surfing if you have a <a href=\"http://iwellness.hu/termek/core-board/\">core board</a>, but these are quite an investment and not entirely necessary.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRegardless of your warm weather sport of choice, I hope this article served to remind you how important it is to condition and strengthen your body ahead of time so you can dive right in without leaving yourself bed ridden the next day. Be creative with your exercises, and prepare yourself to enjoy this coming spring and summer to the fullest by preventing injury and being the most fit you’ve ever been.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-555\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\" alt=\"syd photo\" width=\"180\" height=\"168\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Syd Kingrea</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nSydnah is a freelance writer, videographer, and photographer. As a fitness and nutrition enthusiast, she practices daily exercise and follows a whole food diet. She encourages spending as much time as possible outdoors, while also preserving and respecting nature. Her philosophy is to always keep your workout routine, and your life, new and exciting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Basic Indoor Conditioning for Your Favorite Outdoor Recreation','','publish','open','open','','basic-indoor-conditioning-for-your-favorite-outdoor-recreation','','','2015-03-26 18:31:00','2015-03-26 18:31:00','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=554',0,'post','',0),(555,1,'2015-03-26 17:24:17','2015-03-26 17:24:17','','syd photo','','inherit','open','open','','syd-photo','','','2015-03-26 17:24:17','2015-03-26 17:24:17','',554,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(556,1,'2015-03-26 17:25:16','2015-03-26 17:25:16','The dull days of winter will be out the door soon, but until then we have a few more cold, rainy days to deal with— why not bring your favorite outdoor activities inside? Use this ambivalent season to get in shape for your favorite spring and summer activities— and of course your favorite swimsuit— without spending an excess amount of money at the local gym.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nKayaking or rafting lover? Get those arms in shape so you can hit the rapids without waking up the next day to overused, limp muscles. Resistance bands are all the rage for a good reason. The inconsistent pull effectively mimics that of water rapids hitting your paddles at unexpected angles. So if you’re an avid rafter or kayaker— grab that resistant band and tone up your biceps, triceps and shoulders. This video has some resistance bands exercises that will tone you up fast: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts</a>. This guy uses a tree