ce imaginable is only a few hours away by train or plane, and there’s no shortage of exciting things to do in any destination. Sometimes there’s a place you just can’t leave Europe without visiting, and others it simply comes down to cost.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those who have a desire to travel but no specific destination in mind, Google flights is an amazing tool (<a href=\"http://www.google.com/flights\">www.google.com/flights</a>). You can type in your starting point and the dates you’d like to travel, and google will generate the lowest plane fares for multiple cities to give you the cheap travel destinations for that time. The tool starts with a nice map with the price of major cities easy to find and read, plus the option to zoom in on a specific areas to get information on smaller cities. Then it leads you right up to actually booking your flight, showing options for each direction of the trip and adjusting overall prices based on airlines and times you choose. It’s almost a better recipe for adventure than throwing a dart at a map...instead, decide when to travel, sit back, let Google tell you what your cheapest destination is, and just go. The tool is useful for comparing airlines if you’ve already got a place in mind, too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTo plan cheap travel with a set destination, or more than one destination, Rome2Rio (<a href=\"http://www.rome2rio.com\">www.rome2rio.com</a>) is a helpful resource to compile every option for getting from point A to point B. The biggest perk of this one is the inclusiveness of the cheap travel options it provides. Instead of searching airlines and trains and buses and rideshare websites all separately, Rome2Rio compares them all in one place. It displays all of these modes of travel, and every possible combination of them: a bus to one city then a train the the final destination, two different trains, etc. It’s also great for planning journeys with multiple stops since it’s geared toward one-way travel; I’ve planned a trip with a train to Paris, a flight to Budapest, and a bus to Prague. One downfall of the site is that with things like bus schedules that might operate on a weekly or even monthly basis, it can be difficult to get accurate options for the day you actually intend to travel. Their accuracy depends on how much information you give them; dates, for example, aren’t required in a search but will drastically impact the prices of flights and even train travel. Some things, like trains, are simple to book directly through Rome2Rio, but booking does get messy when it comes to buses and flights as information gets lost from one website to another. The format of the site as a whole is a bit more glitchy than good ol’ Google, but it’s a great place to start looking over options.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAside from those couple of search engines, it’s always a good idea to look for any sort of discount card you can purchase at the beginning of your travels. For example, in France there’s a “Carte Jeune” available for anyone age 12-27. It costs 50 euros but even after just a few trips with the TGV or TER in France, the savings quickly trump the price to make the cheap option of train travel even cheaper. The earlier in your travels you get one, the more savings you can take advantage of.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRyanair has a wide range of destinations and some good search options on <a href=\"http://www.ryanair.com\">www.ryanair.com</a>, and their tickets are often the cheapest option. It’s important to remember that you get the flight experience you pay for: Ryanair often flies out of more remote airports and runs a bit behind schedule with little communication with its customers. It’s a good idea to research the exact locations of the airport you’re considering flying through, and to check on the costs of transport into the city itself from the airport. There’s also something to be said for reading the fine print with Ryanair. Their “printing fees” and baggage policies can end up costing more than the ticket itself. Still, with the right research and preparation and a bit of patience at the airport, Ryanair is still a great option for traveling on a budget.\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>The internet is a wonderful resource for travelers! I know I would be lost without it (and not in the good way), and these methods in particular have led me to some amazing, cheap travel experiences. The options are overwhelming and the destinations are endless - but that’s certainly not a bad thing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nArticle by Elizabeth Thompson\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>','Finding Cheap Travel Options in Europe','','inherit','open','open','','437-revision-v1','','','2015-03-26 17:40:42','2015-03-26 17:40:42','',437,'http://localhost/blog/437-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(558,1,'2015-03-26 18:20:37','2015-03-26 18:20:37','Indoor conditioning tips','Live Out_The Outdoor Social Network_Indoor conditioning tips','','inherit','open','open','','live-out_the-outdoor-social-network_indoor-conditioning-tips','','','2015-03-26 18:21:07','2015-03-26 18:21:07','',554,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Indoor-conditioning-tips.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(560,1,'2015-03-26 18:24:09','2015-03-26 18:24:09','','Under Armour','','inherit','open','open','','under-armour','','','2015-03-26 18:24:38','2015-03-26 18:24:38','',554,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Under-Armour.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(561,1,'2015-03-26 18:25:46','2015-03-26 18:25:46','','Under Armour_Womens apparel','','inherit','open','open','','under-armour_womens-apparel','','','2015-03-26 18:25:58','2015-03-26 18:25:58','',554,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Under-Armour_Womens-apparel.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(562,1,'2015-03-26 18:26:33','2015-03-26 18:26:33','The dull days of winter will be out the door soon, but until then we have a few more cold, rainy days to deal with— why not bring your favorite outdoor activities inside? Use this ambivalent season to get in shape for your favorite spring and summer activities— and of course your favorite swimsuit— without spending an excess amount of money at the local gym.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nKayaking or rafting lover? Get those arms in shape so you can hit the rapids without waking up the next day to overused, limp muscles. Resistance bands are all the rage for a good reason. The inconsistent pull effectively mimics that of water rapids hitting your paddles at unexpected angles. So if you’re an avid rafter or kayaker— grab that resistant band and tone up your biceps, triceps and shoulders. This video has some resistance bands exercises that will tone you up fast: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pgt86Y-M4Ts</a>. This guy uses a tree, but you can do the exercises indoors on a staircase post. It also wouldn’t hurt you to do some weighted rowing motions while you sit around watching TV. Throw in some stability ball exercises, and your balance will be set for whatever comes your way. Another great way to get those arms in shape is to punch it out on a weighted bag. Use all your favorite punches— jab, cross, hook and uppercut to prepare for all the arm muscles you\'ll be working this summer on the water.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf your greatest love is rock climbing, an easy and obvious fix is to go to the local indoor rock wall as much as possible. If there isn’t a climbing gym near you or you don’t want to fork out the money, practice these tips: Your hand strength will most likely be out of shape so practice hand techniques on a grip, a stress ball or by pinching putty— check out this inexpensive Gripmaster <a href=\"http://www.mmawarehouse.com/pro_hands_gripmaster_hand_exerciser/prh-1001-0001.html?gdftrk=gdfV23691_a_7c1696_a_7c7969_a_7cprh_d_1001_d_0001&amp;gclid=CPLw1cyWxMQCFUvl7AodaigA1w\">here</a>. Pull ups are an awesome way to get used to dragging your body weight up the rock and to work your whole upper body. If pull-ups are a breeze, then add a weight belt or vest. There is always a way to make your work out more challenging. You also use a surprising amount of core strength in climbing so grab a 10 pound medicine ball and bust out some sit ups and trunk twists. Last, but definitely not least, leg strength is vital to your performance. Strengthen your entire leg with deep squat jumps, weighted lunges, and intense mountain climbers— which will also work those abs. Also throw in some burpees for good measure. Make sure you are doing all these exercises in a sequence, so they are all worked equally in a timely manner. When you climb that mountain, you’ll be using these muscles all at the same time. Don’t forget to also condition your body for the stretch it will be making in reaching and stabilizing— yoga is an awesome go-to for this.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are an avid cyclist, you’ve probably been riding all winter despite the cold and wet. If you think it is something you’d like to start pursuing when the weather warms up— a bike trainer is a must (assuming you have a bike). If you don’t have a bike, maybe try out a stationary one before you make the big purchase. A trainer is an awesome investment because you can use it year-round. You can dictate the resistance and incline (add some books under the front wheel if you don’t have this feature) to make your workout more challenging. Just pop your bike into place and go. Turn on your favorite TV show and practice interval training— 10-15 intervals 30 seconds on then 30 seconds off or an even higher time frame depending on your skill level. If you don’t have a couple hundred dollars in your budget, look on Craigslist for a gently used trainer.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nA trip to the beach is in the near future for many of us so now is the ideal time to amp up our surfing readiness. Surfing is a fine combination of arm strength, core strength, and balance. The first tip is to condition your upper arms and pecs for paddling into those waves, which requires strength and endurance. Grab that resistance band we talked about earlier and a stability ball. Lie with your stomach on the ball and your chest lifted, legs planted. With a band handle in each hand and the middle of the band wrapped around a stair railing or another solid piece of furniture, create a pulley system. Pull your arms toward your legs in a swimming motion. This will take core strength and leg strength to keep yourself from rolling forward. It also adds an extra challenge similar to that of balancing on your board while you paddle. Since this one is a little complicated here is a photo:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://surfnsnowfitness.com/paddle-fitness-for-surfing/\">Photo cred</a>. You can also find more tips at that site.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSingle leg burpees will help strengthen your quads and hamstrings, as well as your arms, for those fluid pop ups. Speaking of pop ups, you can also practice them on your bed because it will add the advantage of balancing on an uneven service. There are numerous exercises you can do to prepare you for surfing if you have a <a href=\"http://iwellness.hu/termek/core-board/\">core board</a>, but these are quite an investment and not entirely necessary.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRegardless of your warm weather sport of choice, I hope this article served to remind you how important it is to condition and strengthen your body ahead of time so you can dive right in without leaving yourself bed ridden the next day. Be creative with your exercises, and prepare yourself to enjoy this coming spring and summer to the fullest by preventing injury and being the most fit you’ve ever been.\r\n\r\nSydnah is a freelance writer, videographer, and photographer. As a fitness and nutrition enthusiast, she practices daily exercise and follows a whole food diet. She encourages spending as much time as possible outdoors, while also preserving and respecting nature. Her philosophy is to always keep your workout routine, and your life, new and exciting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-555\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\" alt=\"syd photo\" width=\"180\" height=\"168\" /></a>','Basic Indoor Conditioning for Your Favorite Outdoor Recreation','','inherit','open','open','','554-revision-v1','','','2015-03-26 18:26:33','2015-03-26 18:26:33','',554,'http://localhost/blog/554-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(563,1,'2015-03-26 18:28:13','2015-03-26 18:28:13','Mid adult woman exercising on Pilate ball with man at home','Woman Exercising On Pilate Ball With Man At Home','','inherit','open','open','','woman-exercising-on-pilate-ball-with-man-at-home','','','2015-03-26 18:28:13','2015-03-26 18:28:13','',554,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network_Indoor-workout-tips.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(564,1,'2015-03-26 18:29:31','2015-03-26 18:29:31','The dull days of winter will be out the door soon, but until then we have a few more cold, rainy days to deal with— why not bring your favorite outdoor activities inside? Use this ambivalent season to get in shape for your favorite spring and summer activities— and of course your favorite swimsuit— without spending an excess amount of money at the local gym.\n\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n\nKayaking or rafting lover? Get those arms in shape so you can hit the rapids without waking up the next day to over