ut some sit ups and trunk twists. Last, but definitely not least, leg strength is vital to your performance. Strengthen your entire leg with deep squat jumps, weighted lunges, and intense mountain climbers— which will also work those abs. Also throw in some burpees for good measure. Make sure you are doing all these exercises in a sequence, so they are all worked equally in a timely manner. When you climb that mountain, you’ll be using these muscles all at the same time. Don’t forget to also condition your body for the stretch it will be making in reaching and stabilizing— yoga is an awesome go-to for this.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are an avid cyclist, you’ve probably been riding all winter despite the cold and wet. If you think it is something you’d like to start pursuing when the weather warms up— a bike trainer is a must (assuming you have a bike). If you don’t have a bike, maybe try out a stationary one before you make the big purchase. A trainer is an awesome investment because you can use it year-round. You can dictate the resistance and incline (add some books under the front wheel if you don’t have this feature) to make your workout more challenging. Just pop your bike into place and go. Turn on your favorite TV show and practice interval training— 10-15 intervals 30 seconds on then 30 seconds off or an even higher time frame depending on your skill level. If you don’t have a couple hundred dollars in your budget, look on Craigslist for a gently used trainer.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nA trip to the beach is in the near future for many of us so now is the ideal time to amp up our surfing readiness. Surfing is a fine combination of arm strength, core strength, and balance. The first tip is to condition your upper arms and pecs for paddling into those waves, which requires strength and endurance. Grab that resistance band we talked about earlier and a stability ball. Lie with your stomach on the ball and your chest lifted, legs planted. With a band handle in each hand and the middle of the band wrapped around a stair railing or another solid piece of furniture, create a pulley system. Pull your arms toward your legs in a swimming motion. This will take core strength and leg strength to keep yourself from rolling forward. It also adds an extra challenge similar to that of balancing on your board while you paddle. Since this one is a little complicated here is a photo:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://surfnsnowfitness.com/paddle-fitness-for-surfing/\">Photo cred</a>. You can also find more tips at that site.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSingle leg burpees will help strengthen your quads and hamstrings, as well as your arms, for those fluid pop ups. Speaking of pop ups, you can also practice them on your bed because it will add the advantage of balancing on an uneven service. There are numerous exercises you can do to prepare you for surfing if you have a <a href=\"http://iwellness.hu/termek/core-board/\">core board</a>, but these are quite an investment and not entirely necessary.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nRegardless of your warm weather sport of choice, I hope this article served to remind you how important it is to condition and strengthen your body ahead of time so you can dive right in without leaving yourself bed ridden the next day. Be creative with your exercises, and prepare yourself to enjoy this coming spring and summer to the fullest by preventing injury and being the most fit you’ve ever been.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-555\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/syd-photo.jpg\" alt=\"syd photo\" width=\"180\" height=\"168\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Syd Kingrea</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nSydnah is a freelance writer, videographer, and photographer. As a fitness and nutrition enthusiast, she practices daily exercise and follows a whole food diet. She encourages spending as much time as possible outdoors, while also preserving and respecting nature. Her philosophy is to always keep your workout routine, and your life, new and exciting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Basic Indoor Conditioning for Your Favorite Outdoor Recreation','','inherit','open','open','','554-revision-v1','','','2015-03-26 18:31:00','2015-03-26 18:31:00','',554,'http://localhost/blog/554-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(567,1,'2015-04-13 16:45:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00','While packing for a week-long climbing trip to Texas, I took on a challenge…finding the best snacks (All-important. Who doesn’t like food?)  I needed relatively cheap snacks capable of surviving ten days in the desert and 24 hours in a car crammed to the gills. This list is realistic (candy on a road trip is a no-brainer) and geared towards people like me, who can’t usually afford the amazing snacks found in the aisles of Whole Foods.\r\n\r\nI’ve perfected the good (avocados), the bad (SourPatch Kids), and the ugly (excessive amounts of Twizzlers) of snacking during six days of climbing sandwiched between looong drives.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Road Trip Candy</b> – Twizzlers v SourPatch Kids\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Twizzlers</b> won this battle hands down. SourPatch Kids make your tongue hurt, and they aren’t as fun to eat when you’re bored to tears somewhere in the middle of Louisiana.\r\n\r\n<i>Pro Tip </i> -No one should eat two pounds of these suckers in 24 hours. There IS such a thing as too many Twizzlers.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Indestructible Sandwiches</b> – Bread v Tortilla Wraps\r\n\r\nI have determined that there is <i>nothing worse</i> than squished bread. My crumbly, dense, and fragile bread got completed <i>stomped</i> by <b>tortillas</b>. The tortillas survived being crammed into various nooks and crannies in the car and didn’t get soggy or pulverized during the trip.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Sweet and Salty</b> - Nutella and Wheat Thins v Trail Mix\r\n\r\nIf you have somewhere you can store a dirty spoon in your car during your trip, invest in a jar of <b>Nutella</b>. Dipping a Wheat Thin or Triscuit in some Nutella completely trumps a generic bag of trail mix. Much tastier, and much more appealing to my taste buds.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Bars</b> - Pro Bar v Clif Builders Bar\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAs loyal as I am to Clif Bar, the <b>Pro Bar</b> won this fair and square. Builders Bars, though packed with protein and yummy goodness (especially the mint!), melt in the heat and turn into tooth-breaking bricks when temps dip. Pro Bar didn’t melt, and tasted like a Ben and Jerrys truck landed in my climbing bag. Much less messy and just as tasty.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Random Cravings</b>- Cheese v Avocado\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAround 3AM, the crazies hit. With the crazies came the munchies, and all I had was cheese and an avocado. Room temp cheese gets that strange amount of spongy, looks greasy, and really doesn’t seem as appealing as devouring an entire avocado. Not only was the <b>avocado</b> delicious, it really did seem less strange to eat than room temp cheese…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>Pro Tip </i> - Avocados are squishable. Avoid squishing.\r\n\r\n<b>Energy</b> - Red Bull v Coffee v Healthy Energy Boosting Drinks\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nGas station coffee is bad 9 times out of 10. Don’t trust it. Always choose Waffle House coffee. It’s the best.  <b>Red Bull</b> is tasty, gave me a swift kick in the rear, and definitely tastes the same no matter when or where you buy it. The healthy “energy boost” drinks honestly weren’t that great. Truth be told, fruit juice just fills up your bladder waaay faster and doesn’t give you that manic energy necessary to pump up the jams and push through until the next Waffle House comes into sight….\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n*Not everyone agrees with the use of caffeine, especially energy drinks. Don’t ever drive if you\r\n\r\nare sleepy, do what you need to do to keep you and your passengers safe on the road.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Ultimate Climbing Snack</b> - Almonds v Granola Bar\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThis ultimate climbing snack can also apply to just about any sport. I just happened to be climbing this week!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Almonds</b> were both much more satisfying to eat (crunch, crunch, crunch) and less susceptible to destruction than granola bars. I seriously pulverized my granola bars to the point that I put them into my yogurt the next day as regular granola. I recommend either raw almonds or the cocoa roasted ones. But I have a sweet tooth…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the end, eat what makes you feel the best. There is always room in the car for <i>one </i>more thing, right?  I agree that most of the options on this list aren’t the healthiest, but life is for living and Twizzlers are tasty.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAuthor: Sabine Connors\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-467\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Networ