e some tips to help you get back on the bike..\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nFirst things first, check your tires, are they worn down, cracked, or warped? Check the pressure. Narrow tires need more pressure than wider ones; mountain tires require the least amount of pressure, about 30 to 50 psi, road tires require the most at 80 to 130 psi, and hybrid tires fall right in the middle at 50 to 70 psi. You can grab a tire pressure gauge at your local Wal-Mart if you don’t already have one.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nYou should also always have a LED light on your bike, which you can purchase at just about any large retailer. Even if you don’t do any night riding, you never know when you could get stuck in a situation where you might need it. If you are someone who likes to ride at night or before sunrise, you might want to keep a few things in mind. Light is everything. You can never have too many reflectors or lights on your bike or on your person. Many car and bike collisions occur because motorists never see the bicycles at all. Making yourself as visible as possible to motorists and fellow night riders will decrease your risk of an unfortunate incident. In addition to keeping yourself well lit, if it is at all possible consider changing your route to one that includes more roads that have street lights.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nIf you’re into long distance trekking, it’s also a good idea to have an on-the-go tool kit. I would recommend the Topeak Survival Wedge Pack II Seat Bag with tool kit. It’s the perfect size and shape to fit on any bike and has an expanding panel that’s great for storing some tasty treats. It is a 17 piece tool kit that includes 6 Allen wrenches, a phillips and a flathead screwdriver, a universal chain tool with chain hook, 2 tire levers, and glueless patch.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nIf you’re looking to set goals or track your progress, why not try a cyclometer? I recommend the <a href=\"http://hyperlink\">CatEye Strada Wireless Bicycle Computer</a>. It’s great for beginners that are looking for something that’s easy to use. It’ll only cost you about $40 on Amazon, and it’s wireless so the only installation that you have to do is clip it on your bike. It will record your average, maximum, and current speed, distance traveled for two trips at the same time, as well as the total distance traveled- and it has a clock.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nWhat if you pull your bike out of the garage, dust it off, and decide it’s better suited for the annual neighborhood yard sale than for your spring adventures? No worries, there are plenty of affordable options out there if you’re looking for a new ride. For all you mountain bikers out there, I would recommend<a href=\"http://www.devinci.com/bikes/scategory_149\"> Devinci Spartan Carbon SX.</a> Don’t let this bike’s light design fool you! It’s built for pedaling and descending and comes with a lifetime warranty. And for you sun loving beach bunnies check out the <a href=\"http://www.bikesdirect.com/products/gravity/ezcruz_cruisers.htm\">Gavity EX Cruz 1.</a> Costing you only about $160, this super cute bike comes in a TON of colors- and not all of them are girly!\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"><strong><strong> </strong></strong></span>\r\n\r\nAlright, hope this helps.. Now get out there and ride! And don’t forget your helmet ;)\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"> </span>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-456\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_L