INSERT INTO `mm_posts` VALUES (618,1,'2015-04-09 18:10:50','2015-04-09 18:10:50','<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Tup2ixKn5KocPpoNM1pJ_685lquH-myGfxNwcLl4z7k.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-616\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Tup2ixKn5KocPpoNM1pJ_685lquH-myGfxNwcLl4z7k.jpg\" alt=\"Tup2ixKn5KocPpoNM1pJ_685lquH-myGfxNwcLl4z7k\" width=\"575\" height=\"348\" /></a>\r\n\r\nEveryone falls into slumps with their daily workouts. Whether it is just a drag to do the same old thing or you hit a plateau in your weight loss goals, don’t let boredom or disappointment mess up your game. Check out our tips for spicing things up.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Don’t be afraid to switch things up. </b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou have all heard the mantra that muscle confusion is the best way to get an entire quality body workout that produces results. This is true, but it is also an excellent way to keep your workout exciting. Many people think this saying refers to weight training only. But if you have been weight training for a month straight with no other activity, maybe it is time to confuse your muscles in a new way. If you have a gym membership that offers a variety of fitness classes, go to some! Put your money to good use by taking a yoga class Monday, a cycling class Tuesday, and a boxing class Wednesday! If you don’t have a membership, many local organizations provide fun fitness classes. Check out your local martial arts center and pay a one time fee for a workout that you will learn something during. Do Zumba at your local dance studio. Or even visit a Curves gym nearby. Yes, none of these are related. And yes, you will probably be working out with people you have never met before. But finding some random classes near you can be a great way to take a break from your everyday Insanity DVDs or your normal weightlifting regimen. It is also fun to learn new things with people you normally wouldn’t surround yourself with. Plus, you will probably end up working out body parts you forgot you had.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Change your workout schedule.</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThis may be an obvious option, but if you normally have a legs day, then an arms day, take a day to combine both, and do it in a location your normally wouldn’t. It will add an extra edge to your workout and the different level of intensity will be a nice change. If you have been repeating the same daily routine for a few months, change up the schedule or add on extra days or longer hours. Schedule your workout with a friend. Or workout in the morning instead of at night. Simple changes can lead to a big difference in the way you mentally prepare for a workout.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Get outside.</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nCuring workout boredom could be as simple as taking a hike when you would normally take a yoga class. Or throw in a long trail run when would normally be in the gym. Climb that mountain you have been thinking about for a year. Adding some fresh air and new views really invigorates your body and mind in a way you may have forgotten about during your winter workout videos.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Add a new challenge. </b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAnother simple way to add a tougher element could even just be to add a balance challenge to your normal weights workout. Try performing your moves slowly and accurately on a Bosu ball or a stability ball. Keep your good form at all costs, so transition slowly. Adding balance to the mix can work your muscles in new, refreshing ways and make things more fun.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Get a new playlist.       </b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nMusic can really help you push through when you are worn out. Listening to your favorite jams helps you tune out the voices in your head telling you it is not possible to complete another rep. But sometimes your favorite songs start all sounding the same. Have a friend with different music tastes than you make you a new workout playlist. The choices will surprise you and keep you listening when you would otherwise be focusing on how impossible your workout feels. If you end up hating their song choices, that is okay too. The anger will fuel your workout until you can get back to the music you like next time.\r\n\r\nHopefully these tips will give you some easy fixes to boring workout days. For more great ideas, check out this article on <a href=\"http://thoughtcatalog.com/tina-alexander/2014/03/15-ways-to-make-working-out-fun-really/\">15 Ways To Make Working Out Fun</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>','Ways to Spice Up Your Workout Routine','','inherit','open','open','','615-revision-v1','','','2015-04-09 18:10:50','2015-04-09 18:10:50','',615,'http://localhost/blog/615-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(619,1,'2015-04-09 18:22:15','2015-04-09 18:22:15','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you are Costa Rica bound or have had thoughts about visiting, I’m here to encourage you to do so. You will be amazed at the safety and beauty of the country. If you have concerns about theft or violence, I can assure you that I never once felt threatened. Of course it is always smart to take precautions in any country you visit. You will also be pleasantly surprised with what accommodations, food, and adventures your budget might get you. So go take an adventure. Don’t worry about work for a week. Save up for a month or two, and you’ll have plenty of money to spare. Read below for some information about fairly inexpensive places to stay and visit.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou can find flights online for shockingly inexpensive if you do your research. I bought my ticket from Delta about three weeks before I left. Even that close to my departure date, the round-trip ticket was a little under $500. You can find tickets for less than $400 if you buy them a month or two in advance (from the Atlanta airport). I can’t voucher for other cities. At that point in time, Delta did not have any baggage fees for International flights. That is most likely still the case. It was a short flight to San Jose. You can exchange your money at the airport for a fee, or if you know someone in the area you can let them exchange it for you at their bank for free.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nOnce you arrive if you want to fully enjoy your experience, I suggest you rent a car. I wanted to get the most of my stay so I rented. Car rentals are cheap, especially if you don’t buy the high-end insurance to go with it. I got mid-grade insurance just to play it safe. There are tons of motorbikes and crazy drivers on the roads so I will leave that up to your discretion. I used<a href=\"https://www.dollarcostarica.com\"> Dollar Rent A Car</a> and paid about $180 for 6 days. You can up your ride to a SUV for a little more. It may be worth your money because the roads can get rough. You’ll have to arrange transportation to this rental center— it is not that far from the airport though. Make sure you get your credit card unlocked beforehand because the place will probably require a card payment.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you plan to drive, you may want to keep in mind the benefit of having an international GPS. It will be an investment, but it will also make future travels easier. If you want to have fun getting lost on your trip, making it into more of an adventure, you can find several free maps at the car rental center. The roads are not marked extremely well, but they are fairly easy to figure out.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are easy to please, staying in hostel is a great way to go. There are many kinds of hostels: a few are solely dormitory style, others have private rooms, but most have both options. Many people are wary of this option, but I can assure you, I always feel safe at hostels. The hostels in Costa Rica are very clean and beautiful—regardless of whether they are on the high end or low end of the cost spectrum. Even the most inexpensive can be much nicer than a cheap hotel in the USA. These people do things right! If you want to read more about what a hostel is, check out this article:<a href=\"http://blog.wehostels.com/what-is-a-hostel/\"> http://blog.wehostels.com/what-is-a-hostel/</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou will fly into San Jose. This is the metropolis of Costa Rica. If you want to get souvenirs for friends and family check out the local markets. They have affordable pricing, and many of the people speak english. San Jose is also home to some beautiful parks. It is a really neat city, full of culture, but there is definitely more to Costa Rica than the capital. Here is a photo of the Rainbow Eucalyptus trees at the local park.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n</strong></strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Costa-Rica_Rainbow-Eucalyptus-trees.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-630\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Costa-Rica_Rainbow-Eucalyptus-trees.jpg\" alt=\"Rainbow Eucalyptus trees\" width=\"400\" height=\"592\" /></a> <strong><strong>\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOnce you are finished exploring San Jose, I suggest you head toward the coast. The beauty of  the west coast of Costa Rica is in the many types of geography in such a small span of land— all easy to drive to. You will see mountainous regions, rain forests, fields, and beaches. The east coast is most likely a little farther from San Jose, but probably also worth a trip. Below is a map of some places that would be easy to visit on your way to the coast. You don’t have to follow the exact routes. There is always more than one way to go, but this maps covers some main highways which are easier to navigate.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica-travel-map.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-631\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica-travel-map.jpg\" alt=\"costa rica\" width=\"400\" height=\"227\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn your trip, you should definitely visit La Fortuna and Arenal Volcano. This trip will be around 4 hours from San Jose— but can be quicker if you are following a GPS. Once you arrive, I definitely encourage you to check out the Arenal Backpackers’ Resort. You can find more information about it here:<a href=\"http://www.arenalbackpackersresort.com\"> http://www.arenalbackpackersresort.com</a>. This hostel was one of the more expensive ones I stayed in, but I also stayed in a private room. They had tent quarters that were as low as $10 a night and cheap dorm rooms with eight bunks per room. The private room was about $55. Like I said, I splurged on this one. The accommodations were fantastic: hot water, air-conditioned rooms, and a beautiful view of Arenal Volcano. They also had a nice pool and minibar. Once you have your accommodations for the night settled, you should look for any local “Soda” shops for dinner. They are cheap and very authentic. Most have a buffet that includes different rice, bean and empanada options. It normally cost about $3 for a huge plate and drink.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhile you are there, check out Arenal Volcano. You can hike or go rafting in the national park. This website has great suggestions <a href=\"http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attractions-g309236-Activities-Arenal_Volcano_National_Park_Province_of_Alajuela.html\">http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attractions-g309236-Activities-Arenal_Volcano_National_Park_Province_of_Alajuela.html</a>. You will see tons of signs for the local natural hot springs. Don’t go to a resort and pay, just find a place off the road to jump in. You can ask some locals where to find a free entrance— many of them will even take you there in exchange for a couple bucks which is better than paying for a ritzy resort stay. The hot springs were just perfect, so that should be a must-see for your visit—below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica-waterfall.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-628\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica-waterfall.jpg\" alt=\"costa rica\" width=\"400\" height=\"533\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAfter a fun-filled stayed in La Fortuna, head toward Monteverde. This trip will be about 5 hours because the road is a bumpy, dirt track. If you didn’t already rent a SUV, you’ll start to wish you had. Once you get to Monteverde, head to<a href=\"http://www.hotelelsuenocr.com/rates/\"> Hotel El Sueno</a>. This is one of the few places to stay right in town, most are off the beaten path. I paid about $40 for my room, but you can share a room for as low as $20 a person. This hotel did not have hot water, but they did have a free breakfast. There are some surprisingly delicious pizza joints in Monteverde for a reasonable price of $10-$15 per huge pizza.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhile you are in the area, visit the local cloud forest. This is a beautiful rain forest. You can pay to have a guide, but you can also take your own route. You’ll see some really unique wildlife, trees 10 times your size, and large waterfalls. I definitely suggest you do this. This photo doesn’t do it justice:\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are also other ways to explore the cloud forest, like via<a href=\"http://www.selvatura.com/tours-activities-and-monteverde/zip-line/\"> zip line</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_cloud-forest.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-632\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_cloud-forest.jpg\" alt=\"cloud forest\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAfter a relaxing day in the cloud forest, you’ll probably be ready to head to the beach. This can be a 3-5 hour drive, but most of the roads are more highway like.  Once you get to Tamarindo, stay a night at<a href=\"http://www.puravidahostel.com/contact-us/\"> Pura Vida Hostel</a>. This hostel is about $25 a night, and you’ll probably make some life-long friends. It isn’t right on the beach, but it just takes 5 minutes or less to walk there. If you want to switch things up, spend a different night at<a href=\"http://www.hotelpasatiempo.com\"> Hotel Pasatiempo.</a> This was my favorite stay in Costa Rica. It is a short walk to the beach, but the accommodations are fantastic for a truly reasonable price. It has hot water, a full service bar, a great pool, and air-conditioning. The owner is a surfer from California who moved to Tamarindo to surf all day and to get away from the money-crazed, appearance-obsessed culture he had lived in. This is one of the more expensive places to stay, but it is worth the price— it is about $70 for a private room. Keep in mind this isn’t technically a hostel. You won’t be able to get enough of the gorgeous ocean, mountains, and crazy monkeys that will visit you on the beach in Tamarindo.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_-Tamarindo-beach.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-633\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_-Tamarindo-beach.jpg\" alt=\"amarindo beach\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSailboaters anchor to the sandbar near Tamarindo shore and come to land for the day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you aren’t done traveling, head on down to Manuel Antonio. My friends in the area love this beach. It is a bit more touristy, so prepare for higher prices on accommodations and food, but it is equally beautiful and special.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of other hostel options you can find in all of the towns. If you are open to a dorm room, you can stay places for $10 a night and you’ll meet some awesome people. Also keep in mind, most higher priced places include a great breakfast so that is one less thing you’ll have to worry about. There are also plenty of hostels right on the beach. Definitely check out your options before you settle because you can spend a lot less than I did or a lot more depending on what activities you want to do. You can even arrange bus trips or taxis if you don’t want to drive yourself. My trip total was around $1,100 including food and gas. It was a great experience because I did my own thing, wasn’t obligated to sleep in the same place every night, and I got to see so many beautiful places on my drives. If you have the opportunity to visit, go. I don’t speak a lick of Spanish and I figured out my way around. The people are some of the friendliest you’ll ever meet and you won’t find better food or views. If you would rather play it safe, or think about plans less, check out this great deal that will take you to some similar places: http://www.adventurelink.com/trip/146184\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/syd-kingrea-writer-live-out-the-outdoor-social-network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-641\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/syd-kingrea-writer-live-out-the-outdoor-social-network.jpg\" alt=\"syd kingrea\" width=\"180\" height=\"168\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Syd Kingrea</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nSydnah is a freelance writer, videographer, and photographer. As a fitness and nutrition enthusiast, she practices daily exercise and follows a whole food diet. She encourages spending as much time as possible outdoors, while also preserving and respecting nature. Her philosophy is to always keep your workout routine, and your life, new and exciting.','Costa Rica Under $1,200','','publish','open','open','','costa-rica-under-1200','','http://www.selvatura.com/tours-activities-and-monteverde/zip-line/\nhttp://blog.wehostels.com/what-is-a-hostel/','2015-04-10 00:16:46','2015-04-10 00:16:46','',0,'http://localhost/blog/?p=619',0,'post','',0),(620,1,'2015-04-09 18:16:56','2015-04-09 18:16:56','','article1','','inherit','open','open','','article1','','','2015-04-09 18:16:56','2015-04-09 18:16:56','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(621,1,'2015-04-09 18:17:38','2015-04-09 18:17:38','','article2','','inherit','open','open','','article2','','','2015-04-09 18:17:38','2015-04-09 18:17:38','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(622,1,'2015-04-09 18:18:57','2015-04-09 18:18:57','','article3','','inherit','open','open','','article3','','','2015-04-09 18:18:57','2015-04-09 18:18:57','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(623,1,'2015-04-09 18:19:53','2015-04-09 18:19:53','','article4','','inherit','open','open','','article4','','','2015-04-09 18:19:53','2015-04-09 18:19:53','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(624,1,'2015-04-09 18:20:36','2015-04-09 18:20:36','','article5','','inherit','open','open','','article5','','','2015-04-09 18:20:36','2015-04-09 18:20:36','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(625,1,'2015-04-09 18:21:52','2015-04-09 18:21:52','If you are Costa Rica bound or have had thoughts about visiting, I’m here to encourage you to 