rica_cloud-forest.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-632\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_cloud-forest.jpg\" alt=\"cloud forest\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAfter a relaxing day in the cloud forest, you’ll probably be ready to head to the beach. This can be a 3-5 hour drive, but most of the roads are more highway like.  Once you get to Tamarindo, stay a night at<a href=\"http://www.puravidahostel.com/contact-us/\"> Pura Vida Hostel</a>. This hostel is about $25 a night, and you’ll probably make some life-long friends. It isn’t right on the beach, but it just takes 5 minutes or less to walk there. If you want to switch things up, spend a different night at<a href=\"http://www.hotelpasatiempo.com\"> Hotel Pasatiempo.</a> This was my favorite stay in Costa Rica. It is a short walk to the beach, but the accommodations are fantastic for a truly reasonable price. It has hot water, a full service bar, a great pool, and air-conditioning. The owner is a surfer from California who moved to Tamarindo to surf all day and to get away from the money-crazed, appearance-obsessed culture he had lived in. This is one of the more expensive places to stay, but it is worth the price— it is about $70 for a private room. Keep in mind this isn’t technically a hostel. You won’t be able to get enough of the gorgeous ocean, mountains, and crazy monkeys that will visit you on the beach in Tamarindo.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_-Tamarindo-beach.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-633\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/costa-rica_-Tamarindo-beach.jpg\" alt=\"amarindo beach\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSailboaters anchor to the sandbar near Tamarindo shore and come to land for the day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you aren’t done traveling, head on down to Manuel Antonio. My friends in the area love this beach. It is a bit more touristy, so prepare for higher prices on accommodations and food, but it is equally beautiful and special.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of other hostel options you can find in all of the towns. If you are open to a dorm room, you can stay places for $10 a night and you’ll meet some awesome people. Also keep in mind, most higher priced places include a great breakfast so that is one less thing you’ll have to worry about. There are also plenty of hostels right on the beach. Definitely check out your options before you settle because you can spend a lot less than I did or a lot more depending on what activities you want to do. You can even arrange bus trips or taxis if you don’t want to drive yourself. My trip total was around $1,100 including food and gas. It was a great experience because I did my own thing, wasn’t obligated to sleep in the same place every night, and I got to see so many beautiful places on my drives. If you have the opportunity to visit, go. I don’t speak a lick of Spanish and I figured out my way around. The people are some of the friendliest you’ll ever meet and you won’t find better food or views. If you would rather play it safe, or think about plans less, check out this great deal that will take you to some similar places: http://www.adventurelink.com/trip/146184','Costa Rica Under $1,200','','inherit','open','open','','619-revision-v1','','','2015-04-09 23:58:05','2015-04-09 23:58:05','',619,'http://localhost/blog/619-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(636,1,'2015-04-10 00:01:34','2015-04-10 00:01:34','','trivago travel reservations','','inherit','open','open','','trivago-travel-reservations','','','2015-04-10 00:01:43','2015-04-10 00:01:43','',619,'http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/trivago-travel-reservations.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(637,1,'2015-04-10 00:03:30','2015-04-10 00:03:30','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you are Costa Rica bound or have had thoughts about visiting, I’m here to encourage you to do so. You will be amazed at the safety and beauty of the country. If you have concerns about theft or violence, I can assure you that I never once felt threatened. Of course it is always smart to take precautions in any country you visit. You will also be pleasantly surprised with what accommodations, food, and adventures your budget might get you. So go take an adventure. Don’t worry about work for a week. Save up for a month or two, and you’ll have plenty of money to spare. Read below for some information about fairly inexpensive places to stay and visit.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou can find flights online for shockingly inexpensive if you do your research. I bought my ticket from Delta about three weeks before I left. Even that close to my departure date, the round-trip ticket was a little under $500. You can find tickets for less than $400 if you buy them a month or two in advance (from the Atlanta airport). I can’t voucher for other cities. At that point in time, Delta did not have any baggage fees for International flights. That is most likely still the case. It was a short flight to San Jose. You can exchange your money at the airport for a fee, or if you know someone in the area you can let them exchange it for you at their bank for free.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nOnce you arrive if you want to fully enjoy your experience, I suggest you rent a car. I wanted to get the most of my stay so I rented. Car rentals are cheap, especially if you don’t buy the high-end insurance to go with it. I got mid-grade insurance just to play it safe. There are tons of motorbikes and crazy drivers on the roads so I will leave that up to your discretion. I used<a href=\"https://www.dollarcostarica.com\"> Dollar Rent A Car</a> and paid about $180 for 6 days. You can up your ride to a SUV for a little more. It may be worth your money because the roads can get rough. You’ll have to arrange transportation to this rental center— it is not that far from the airport though. Make sure you get your credit card unlocked beforehand because the place will probably require a card payment.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you plan to drive, you may want to keep in mind the benefit of having an international GPS. It will be an investment, but it will also make future travels easier. If you want to have fun getting lost on your trip, making it into more of an adventure, you can find several free maps at the car rental center. The roads are not marked extremely well, but they are fairly easy to figure out.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you are easy to please, staying in hostel is a great way to go. There are many kinds of hostels: a few are solely dormitory style, others have private rooms, but most have both options. Many people are wary of this option, but I can assure you, I always feel safe at hostels. The hostels in Costa Rica are very clean and beautiful—regardless of whether they are on the high end or low end of the cost spectrum. Even the most inexpensive can be much nicer than a cheap hotel in the USA. These people do things right! If you want to read more about what a hostel is, check out this article:<a href=\"http://blog.wehostels.com/what-is-a-hostel/\"> http://blog.wehostels.com/what-is-a-hostel/</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nYou will fly into San Jose. This is the metropolis of Costa Rica. If you want to get souvenirs for friends and family check out the local markets. They have affordable pricing, and many of the people speak english. San Jose is also home to some beautiful parks. It is a really neat city, full of culture, but there is definitely more to Costa Rica than the capital. Here is a photo of the Rainbow Eucalyptus trees at the local park.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n</strong></strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploa