s, executing flawlessly despite a (comparative) lack of course experience, and keeping cool under the immense pressure that surrounds The Masters and the media - not that he’s watching.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Tiger-Woods-2015-Masters-charge.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-654\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Tiger-Woods-2015-Masters-charge.jpg\" alt=\"Tiger Woods \" width=\"630\" height=\"420\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPhoto: <a href=\"http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2427009-tiger-woods-new-reality-will-2015-masters-trigger-next-phase-of-his-career\">BleacherReport</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tiger</b>\r\n\r\nIt’s been 10 years since Tiger’s last Masters win - he didn’t even play last year following back surgery. He hasn’t won a major since 2009. Wood’s hasn’t looked like himself since 2013, when he finished with 5 titles and coming off perhaps his worst year yet in 2014, he vowed he would not return until he felt he could compete again at the very highest level. It’s safe to say he’s proven he can.\r\n\r\nTiger, 10 shots back will need some luck and a heck of rally to win, but a top three finish is within his reach. He’s played better every day this week and put himself in position to be in the hunt going into Sunday. Is this the beginning of the Tiger come-back?\r\n\r\n\"I\'m gonna have to post something low tomorrow. ... At least give myself a chance going into the back nine. It\'s in Jordan\'s hands right now, but you just never know. That\'s the thing about this golf course...”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/CCV_MAAWAAAohhM.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-652\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/CCV_MAAWAAAohhM.jpg\" alt=\"Phil Mickelson\" width=\"599\" height=\"337\" /></a></strong></strong>\r\n\r\nPhoto: <a href=\"http://www.golfdigest.com/blogs/the-loop/2015/04/track-all-the-action-from-day-1.html\">Golf Digest</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Phil</b>\r\n\r\nHow about the way Phil is playing?! What an unbelievable show he’s putting on - the putt from Phil on 16 from 41 feet - it doesn’t get any better than that! Phil’s playing at the top of his game and has a lot of momentum coming in to Sunday - no doubt he believes he can win this thing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/rory-mcilroy-2015-masters-bleacher-report.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-655\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/rory-mcilroy-2015-masters-bleacher-report.jpg\" alt=\"rory mcilroy\" width=\"630\" height=\"420\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPhoto: <a href=\"http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2427637-rory-mcilroy-at-masters-2015-leaderboard-score-twitter-reaction-from-saturday\">BleacherReport</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Rory</b>\r\n\r\nAnd then there’s McIlroy. Tied and paired with Tiger coming in, he’ll need a huge rally and some help from Spieth to win his third straight major and complete the career Grand Slam. He got off to a slow start on Thursday but has since rallied back - making a huge charge on Saturday nearly capping a flawless round until bogey’s on 2 of the last 3 holes forced him to ‘settle’ for a 68.\r\n\r\nIf anybody understands the pressure Spieth is under today, it’s McIlroy. In 2011 at age 21 he went into the final round at The Masters with a 4 shot cushion, and ended up shooting the worst final round score in Master history (t80).\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/rory-mcilroy-2011-masters-meltdown.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-656\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/rory-mcilroy-2011-masters-meltdown.jpg\" alt=\"rory mcilroy \" width=\"634\" height=\"354\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPhoto: <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-1375545/THE-MASTERS-2011-Rory-McIlroy-chokes-Charl-Schwartzel-clinches-glory.html\">Reuters</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIt was about as hard as golf gets to watch. Hooking the ball uncontrollably, taking seven putts to over two holes on Amens corner to cover 15 feet. Despite the scars, Rory has forged on to the world’s top spot and claimed all 3 majors since - only the elusive Masters Championship remains.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhen asked about Spieth’s position in relation to his in 2011, Rory remarked that Spieth is more mature than Rory was at 21 - and more prepared. Especially having been in the final pairing on Sunday in his debut last year and learning from that experience.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNo doubt Spieth’s got a target on his back going into Sunday. Phil, Tiger, Rory are all looking to make a run at him and compete for the top spots. If Spieth can hold on and post something under par he’ll be the first player to win the master wire-to-wire since 1976, the second youngest ever to win the Masters and break the all-time record held by Tiger Woods at 18 under par for lowest round at the Masters. Despite all appearances, the largest deficit overcome is 8 and it’s still a long 18 holes from over, folks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHere’s a look at today’s schedule:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>FEATURED GROUPS</b>\r\n\r\n<b>GROUP 1:</b>\r\n\r\nTee time/ Coverage begins (approximately)\r\n\r\n10:40 a.m./Jason Dufner, Jimmy Walker\r\n\r\n12:10 p.m./ Henrik Stenson, Brooks Koepka\r\n\r\n2:40 p.m./Phil Mickelson, Charley Hoffman\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>GROUP 2:</b>\r\n\r\nTee time/ Coverage begins (approximately)\r\n\r\n11:10 a.m./Ryan Palmer, Matt Kuchar\r\n\r\n12:20 p.m./Adam Scott, Lee Westwood\r\n\r\n2:50 p.m./Jordan Spieth, Justin Rose\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nDownload The Master App to watch it live.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://