2015/04/rory-mcilroy-2011-masters-meltdown.jpg\" alt=\"rory mcilroy \" width=\"634\" height=\"354\" /></a>\r\n\r\nPhoto: <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/golf/article-1375545/THE-MASTERS-2011-Rory-McIlroy-chokes-Charl-Schwartzel-clinches-glory.html\">Reuters</a>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIt was about as hard as golf gets to watch. Hooking the ball uncontrollably, taking seven putts to over two holes on Amens corner to cover 15 feet. Despite the scars, Rory has forged on to the world’s top spot and claimed all 3 majors since - only the elusive Masters Championship remains.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhen asked about Spieth’s position in relation to his in 2011, Rory remarked that Spieth is more mature than Rory was at 21 - and more prepared. Especially having been in the final pairing on Sunday in his debut last year and learning from that experience.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNo doubt Spieth’s got a target on his back going into Sunday. Phil, Tiger, Rory are all looking to make a run at him and compete for the top spots. If Spieth can hold on and post something under par he’ll be the first player to win the master wire-to-wire since 1976, the second youngest ever to win the Masters and break the all-time record held by Tiger Woods at 18 under par for lowest round at the Masters. Despite all appearances, the largest deficit overcome is 8 and it’s still a long 18 holes from over, folks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Scott-McGuire_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-600\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Scott-McGuire_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Scott McGuire\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Scott McGuire</strong>\r\n\r\nWriter, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\