There are six major things to know before embarking on this crazy climb.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n <li><strong>Parking is hard. Especially since the Incline became public property, there is really no time that isn’t crazy busy.</strong> There are a few paid parking spots right at the trailhead, which will more than likely be full. Just mentally prepare yourself for an extra mile or so of hiking to and from the trailhead.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li><strong>There is a false summit. It is completely believable and absolutely heartbreaking.</strong> Once you begin the steepest section, when you look up you will be able to consistently see this false summit. A few times I’ve had random people tell me that it’s not the real summit, just because we all know how soul shattering it is to be staring down your goal during the toughest part of the hike, only to find out that’s not actually the goal. You’ll know the real summit by the crowds of people taking pictures from the top.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li><strong>After you hit the false summit, you’re more than three quarters done!</strong> The trail levels out – as much as it can while still deserving the name “The Incline” – and it really is easier going, and not that far, after that. Even though I know it’s a false summit, I always find myself comforted by getting closer and closer to it just because I know that’s the end of the most challenging chunk.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n  <li><strong>There is an exit point onto Barr Trail about three quarters of the way up. </strong>If you’re considering not finishing, try to find that rather than turning around and making your way down the incline. It’ll be on your left; you’ll see parts of the Barr Trail railing, made of a dark wood, and you’ll be able to safely cross over to Barr Trail and head back down if you need to. If you’re not turning back, it’s still nice to know that when you see Barr Trail you’re almost done!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n <li><strong>It’s a lot safer and easier on the body to walk or jog down Barr Trail once you finish rather than going back down the railway ties.</strong> I’ve seen countless people go tumbling after just a small misstep, and it’s just rough on the joints to descend such a steep incline. To get to Barr Trail from the summit of the Incline, just go right (if you’re facing down the incline), and hug the trees on the face of the mountain a few meters until you hit the trail. Take a left onto it and start the three-mile descent back toward real life and a celebratory Slurpee.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n  <li><strong>The weather plays a huge role in how doable or enjoyable the Incline will be.</strong> I’ve noticed drastic changes in my times simply due to cloud cover or a nice breeze. Obviously we can’t control the weather, but it’s nice to go early in the morning before the day gets too hot and the crowds get too thick. Part of the reason the weather makes such a huge difference is because the trail is so exposed: there’s hardly any shade and no form of protection on the climb up the sheer face of the mountain. Sunscreen is an absolute must, and layers are a good idea too.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-494\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Elizabeth Thompson</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nElizabeth is a college student in love with mountains, oceans and everything in between. 