do is a must for any outdoor junkie, and Mount Sherman is a perfect mountain to begin with, or to add to your repertoire without too much fuss.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMount Sherman is conveniently located in Colorado on the Mosquito range, not far from Fairplay or Leadville. It’s close to a few other Fourteeners such as Mounts Democrat and Lincoln, so take a few days to stay nearby, start with Sherman, and if you decide hiking Fourteeners is for you, head over to the others.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAt 14,036 feet, Sherman is just high enough to qualify for the category of a Fourteener. In fact, if you know where to look, you can see the small parking lot from the summit. At 2,100 feet, the elevation gain isn’t too demanding. The <a href=\"http://www.14ers.com/routemain.php?route=sher1&amp;peak=mt.+sherman\">trail</a> isn’t needlessly long, resulting in a round trip of just 5.25 miles, but it’s still a gradual enough slope to allow for a steady pace.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne perk to Sherman is that there’s plenty to look at along the way. The majority of the trail is above tree line, for starters. While hiking through dense, green forests and crossing beautiful little streams is lovely for a while, it can be tiresome to spend hours below tree line at the beginning of a Fourteener. The real feeling of climbing isn’t quite there until you can see the summit (or at least the false summit) and watch it draw closer each time you look up from the trail. The views from the summit are incredible, and the visibility the whole way provides for plenty of breathless moments of awe. Plus, there’s an old mining site a ways up that makes for a historic resting point.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn a more basic note, there are a few important beginner hiking tips to keep in mind no matter which Fourteener you decide to start with. The first and most important Fourteener tip is probably obvious: bring a lot of water. Do not be that person halfway to the summit swallowing your last sip and looking around at everyone else’s multiple full Nalgene bottles. You will, and should, drink more than you might be expecting if it’s your first time. Plan on around half a liter per hour, especially on the way up. This will depend on your personal level of exertion, on how warm or dry the day is, and plenty of other factors. Hydrating before the hike is huge, too; by the time you notice yourself getting thirsty, dehydration is already settling in. Being attentive to your body and planning ahead is the key. Although it seems like a drag to lug a few liters of water to the top of the mountain, it would be a much bigger drag to get halfway up the mountain and have to turn around because you’re out of water and dangerously dehydrated.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSpecifically for those coming from out of state, altitude sickness is another possible obstacle to be aware of. Symptoms are sometimes described to be similar to a hangover: headache, dizziness, nausea and vomiting are all signs of altitude sickness. Although these seem to be simply uncomfortable, another challenge to push through, altitude sickness can also result in edema which can be life-threatening. Again, listening to your body is the most important step in keeping yourself safe. If you’re coming from low altitude and haven’t been at Colorado altitude for a few days or so, take it slow to let yourself acclimate gradually. Staying hydrated helps here, too.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe last thing I’ll mention to be aware of is snow. Even if it’s the middle of June and 80 degrees in Leadville, the summit of Sherman is likely somewhere around 20 degrees and windy, with snow falling every now and then. It’s a good idea to do a bit of time-specific research before embarking on a hike to make sure the trail is completely accessible without snowshoes. Beyond that, just be ready to do a bit of slipping through snow banks! Bring a few layers for the summit, especially if you plan on resting and eating lunch there.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are few things more exhilarating and rewarding than submitting a Fourteener and signing your name on the hiking registry. It may take a lot of sweat and a fair amount of planning, but mountain climbing is a hobby well worth the work it demands.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-494\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Elizabeth Thompson</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nElizabeth is a college student in love with mountains, oceans and everything in between. Her travel skills and expertise are constantly being refined while she studies abroad for the semester in Aix-en-Provence, France. At her home university in Colorado, she studies Creative Writing, French, and Business in between weekends on a snowboard and summers lost in the mountains.','Mount Sherman: The Ideal First Fourteener','','publish','open','open','','mount-sherman-the-ideal-first-fourteener-2','','','2015-04-14 15:39:30','2015-04-14 15:39:30','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=667',0,'post','',0),(668,1,'2015-04-12 20:21:28','2015-04-12 20:21:28','The concept of hiking Fourteeners seems threatening. Climbing a mountain whose summit is at least 14,000 feet above sea level involves determination above all, along with a solid amount of physical fitness and preparation. Still, there are Fourteeners of all difficulty levels out there, and it’s all about starting out with something that feels doable while still offering the rush and accomplishment of summiting a Fourteener. Hiking in Colorado is a must for any outdoor junkie, and Mount Sherman is a perfect mountain to begin with, or to add to your repertoire without too much fus