not rewarding. Hiking the incline can be tricky logistically, too. There are six major things to know before embarking on this crazy climb.\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>    Parking is hard.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEspecially since the Incline became public property, there is really no time that isn’t crazy busy. There are a few paid parking spots right at the trailhead, which will more than likely be full. Just mentally prepare yourself for an extra mile or so of hiking to and from the trailhead.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>    There is a false summit.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIt is completely believable and absolutely heartbreaking. Once you begin the steepest section, when you look up you will be able to consistently see this false summit. A few times I’ve had random people tell me that it’s not the real summit, just because we all know how soul shattering it is to be staring down your goal during the toughest part of the hike, only to find out that’s not actually the goal. You’ll know the real summit by the crowds of people taking pictures from the top.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>    After you hit the false summit, you’re more than three quarters done!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe trail levels out – as much as it can while still deserving the name “The Incline” – and it really is easier going, and not that far, after that. Even though I know it’s a false summit, I always find myself comforted by getting closer and closer to it just because I know that’s the end of the most challenging chunk.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n  <li>    There is an exit point onto Barr Trail about three quarters of the way up.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf you’re considering not finishing, try to find that rather than turning around and making your way down the incline. It’ll be on your left; you’ll see parts of the Barr Trail railing, made of a dark wood, and you’ll be able to safely cross over to Barr Trail and head back down if you need to.\r\n\r\nIf you’re not turning back, it’s still nice to know that when you see Barr Trail you’re almost done!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n  <li>    It’s a lot safer and easier on the body to walk or jog down Barr Trail once you finish rather than going back down the railway ties. I’ve seen countless people go tumbling after just a small misstep, and it’s just rough on the joints to descend such a steep incline. To get to Barr Trail from the summit of the Incline, just go right (if you’re facing down the incline), and hug the trees on the face of the mountain a few meters until you hit the trail. Take a left onto it and start the three-mile descent back toward real life and a celebratory Slurpee.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n <li>    The weather plays a huge role in how doable or enjoyable the Incline will be. I’ve noticed drastic changes in my times simply due to cloud cover or a nice breeze. Obviously we can’t control the weather, but it’s nice to go early in the morning before the day gets too hot and the crowds get too thick. Part of the reason the weather makes such a huge difference is because the trail is so exposed: there’s hardly any shade and no form of protection on the climb up the sheer face of the mountain. Sunscreen is an absolute must, and layers are a good idea too.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBio:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-494\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Elizabeth is a college student in love with mountains, oceans and everything in between. Her travel skills and expertise are constantly being refined while she studies abroad for the semester in Aix-en-Provence, France. At her home university in Colorado, she studies Creative Writing, French, and Business in between weekends on a snowboard and summers lost in the mountains.</strong>','6 Tips for Climbing the Manitou Incline','','inherit','open','open','','665-revision-v1','','','2015-04-12 20:40:50','2015-04-12 20:40:50','',665,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/665-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(671,1,'2015-04-14 16:15:55','2015-04-14 16:15:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLast summer I wandered around Europe and visited four different countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling in pairs:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Look out for each other. Who you’re with is your best resource. Take care of them and they’ll do the same for you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>If one of you notices that something feels wrong, don’t ignore that feeling. If you feel like it’s not just the two of you, look around and make sure you have a plan in case something were to happen.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Try and stick as close together as possible, without suffocating each other. Leave room to explore on your own, but be close enough that you can be helpful if anything happens.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling alone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Don\'t stare at your phone for too long. It\'s rare that you’re fully alone, so make sure you\'re <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D66L1o-uES0\">paying attention to what\'s around you</a>. Give a paper map a shot and keep your phone tucked away. Be in the experience.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>Sit at the end of a row on public transportation. That way you have the wall or aisle on one side of you and only have to sit next to one person. This reduces the odds you\'ll find yourself sitting next to someone who makes you uncomfortable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>If you can\'t find a seat at the end, then sit next to a mom or someone in a business suit. Moms are always on the lookout because they want their kids to be safe. She\'ll be alert and you\'ll know if something is wrong. If a mom isn\'t available then sit next to a professional looking man or woman. They spend a lot of the ride staring at their phone, so you won\'t have to worry about interacting. It’s not a foolproof method, but it’s worked pretty well so far.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for everyone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>If you really want to listen to music while you’re on the go, keep the volume to the lowest level possible. You need to be able to hear what’s going on around you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>Attract as little attention as possible. Quietly slip on and off transportation, don\'t talk too loudly, and pay attention to the things around you. Meeting people is one of the best parts of going on an adventure, just make sure to meet the right people!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Have at least one <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ooeAzo2oVJU\">go to self-defense move</a>. If the worst does happen then you need one move that you feel confident enough in to execute properly. You never know what’s going to happen, but at least you know you’re not helpless.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTraveling alone or with someone else is a great opportunity to learn about yourself and each other. It’s something everyone should experience, but you should always be safe about it. Time to start planning your next big adventure!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Safety Tips for Traveling Alone or in Pairs','','publish','open','open','','safety-tips-for-traveling-alone-or-in-pairs','','','2015-04-14 16:52:54','2015-04-14 16:52:54','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=671',0,'post','',0),(672,1,'2015-04-13 16:42:22','2015-04-13 16:42:22','Last summer I wandered around Europe and visited four different countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips