hallenge…finding the best snacks (All-important. Who doesn’t like food?)  I needed relatively cheap snacks capable of surviving ten days in the desert and 24 hours in a car crammed to the gills. This list is realistic (candy on a road trip is a no-brainer) and geared towards people like me, who can’t usually afford the amazing snacks found in the aisles of Whole Foods.\r\n\r\nI’ve perfected the good (avocados), the bad (SourPatch Kids), and the ugly (excessive amounts of Twizzlers) of snacking during six days of climbing sandwiched between looong drives.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Road Trip Candy</b> – Twizzlers v SourPatch Kids\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Twizzlers</b> won this battle hands down. SourPatch Kids make your tongue hurt, and they aren’t as fun to eat when you’re bored to tears somewhere in the middle of Louisiana.\r\n\r\n<i>Pro Tip </i> -No one should eat two pounds of these suckers in 24 hours. There IS such a thing as too many Twizzlers.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Indestructible Sandwiches</b> – Bread v Tortilla Wraps\r\n\r\nI have determined that there is <i>nothing worse</i> than squished bread. My crumbly, dense, and fragile bread got completed <i>stomped</i> by <b>tortillas</b>. The tortillas survived being crammed into various nooks and crannies in the car and didn’t get soggy or pulverized during the trip.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Sweet and Salty</b> - Nutella and Wheat Thins v Trail Mix\r\n\r\nIf you have somewhere you can store a dirty spoon in your car during your trip, invest in a jar of <b>Nutella</b>. Dipping a Wheat Thin or Triscuit in some Nutella completely trumps a generic bag of trail mix. Much tastier, and much more appealing to my taste buds.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Bars</b> - Pro Bar v Clif Builders Bar\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAs loyal as I am to Clif Bar, the <b>Pro Bar</b> won this fair and square. Builders Bars, though packed with protein and yummy goodness (especially the mint!), melt in the heat and turn into tooth-breaking bricks when temps dip. Pro Bar didn’t melt, and tasted like a Ben and Jerrys truck landed in my climbing bag. Much less messy and just as tasty.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Random Cravings</b>- Cheese v Avocado\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAround 3AM, the crazies hit. With the crazies came the munchies, and all I had was cheese and an avocado. Room temp cheese gets that strange amount of spongy, looks greasy, and really doesn’t seem as appealing as devouring an entire avocado. Not only was the <b>avocado</b> delicious, it really did seem less strange to eat than room temp cheese…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<i>Pro Tip </i> - Avocados are squishable. Avoid squishing.\r\n\r\n<b>Energy</b> - Red Bull v Coffee v Healthy Energy Boosting Drinks\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nGas station coffee is bad 9 times out of 10. Don’t trust it. Always choose Waffle House coffee. It’s the best.  <b>Red Bull</b> is tasty, gave me a swift kick in the rear, and definitely tastes the same no matter when or where you buy it. The healthy “energy boost” drinks honestly weren’t that great. Truth be told, fruit juice just fills up your bladder waaay faster and doesn’t give you that manic energy necessary to pump up the jams and push through until the next Waffle House comes into sight….\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n*Not everyone agrees with the use of caffeine, especially energy drinks. Don’t ever drive if you\r\n\r\nare sleepy, do what you need to do to keep you and your passengers safe on the road.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Ultimate Climbing Snack</b> - Almonds v Granola Bar\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThis ultimate climbing snack can also apply to just about any sport. I just happened to be climbing this week!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Almonds</b> were both much more satisfying to eat (crunch, crunch, crunch) and less susceptible to destruction than granola bars. I seriously pulverized my granola bars to the point that I put them into my yogurt the next day as regular granola. I recommend either raw almonds or the cocoa roasted ones. But I have a sweet tooth…\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the end, eat what makes you feel the best. There is always room in the car for <i>one </i>more thing, right?  I agree that most of the options on this list aren’t the healthiest, but life is for living and Twizzlers are tasty.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAuthor: Sabine Connors\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">http://www.liveout.org</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-467\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Sabine-Connors_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Sabine Connors\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a></strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSabine is an outdoor enthusiast, competitive climber, and student at Clemson University in South Carolina. She is a member of Clemson University’s Climbing Club, and likes to spend her free time running and traveling. She is an expert in forgetting to pack extra socks and losing chapstick tubes.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Trip Tested – Best Snacks to Road Trip With','','inherit','open','open','','567-revision-v1','','','2015-04-13 16:45:49','2015-04-13 16:45:49','',567,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/567-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(675,1,'2015-04-13 16:48:50','2015-04-13 16:48:50','','article7','','inherit','open','open','','article7','','','2015-04-13 16:48:50','2015-04-13 16:48:50','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/article7.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(677,1,'2015-04-14 16:34:55','2015-04-14 16:34:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn average, American’s spend only three hours a day being active or standing. According to <a href=\"http://annals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2091327\">a study</a> released in January, sitting for too long increases your risk of getting diabetes, heart disease, cancer, and can result in premature death. To not be considered sedentary, it’s essential to get one hundred and fifty minutes of moderate activity a week or seventy-five minutes of vigorous activity a week - spread out over the course of the week to avoid being sedentary. While exercise is an important part of a healthy lifestyle, there are more effective ways to combat the impacts of prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can be done to reduce the effects of prolonged sitting? Rather than adding more time to your workout, simple lifestyle adjustments at work or at home can have a more positive impact on your quality of life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at work, consider a standing desk. Instead of sitting in a chair all day, it would help to spend that time on your feet. This option can be daunting to people who currently spend that time in a chair. Eight hours of sitting straight to standing is difficult. If you want to take a slower approach, then go for a walk around the office every hour. Once fully adjusted to that, increase the frequency of the walks to every forty-five minutes, every half an hour, and every fifteen minutes. Even if in the middle of a task, going for a walk can lead to a refreshed mind and better productivity. You can then move to sitting on an exercise ball or something that wobbles before moving to standing at your desk. As you being to stand, go in smaller intervals to guarantee your success. Start at five minutes every hour and slowly increase by five minutes each time you become consistent. Finally, if you need to talk to a coworker, get or give something to them, or have a question, walk over to people’s desk rather than emailing or calling them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at home, don’t fast forward through the commercials. Use that time to do a quick workout or activity, clean something, take a small walk around the house, or just spend that time standing. Also consider beginning to incorporate yoga poses that stretch your back. Also, try walking, biking, or using public transportation to get around. As you’re standing on the subway carrying a few bags of groceries you’ll be making a healthier choice than taking a car. Another option is to call friends and family, but stand for the duration of the phone call. Anytime you want to use your phone at all, even texting or checking social media, spend that time on your feet. Also try and take a walk for at least ten minutes once a day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhether you choose to make a small change or have a complete lifestyle change, it’s important to begin to move towards a life with less time sitting and From student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Kendal Eisenberg</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Sit Less, Stand More','','publish','open','open','','sit-less-stand-more','','','2015-04-14 16:52:25','2015-04-14 16:52:25','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=677',0,'post','',0),(678,1,'2015-04-13 17:57:26','2015-04-13 17:57:26','From student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nOn average, American’s spend only three hours a day being active or standing. According to <a href=\"http://annals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2091327\">a study</a> released in January, sitting for too long increases your risk of getting diabetes, heart disease, cancer, and can result in premature death. To not be considered sedentary, it’s essential to get one hundred and fifty minutes of moderate activity a week or seventy-five minutes of vigorous activity a week - spread out over the course of the week to avoid being sedentary. While exercise is an important part of a healthy lifestyle, there are more effective ways to combat the impacts of prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nSo what can be done to reduce the effects of prolonged sitting? Rather than adding more time to your workout, simple lifestyle adjustments at work or at home can have a more positive impact on your quality of life.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhile at work, consider a standing desk. Instead of sitting in a chair all day, it would help to spend that time on your feet. This option can be daunting to people who currently spend that time in a chair. Eight hours of sitting straight to standing is difficult. If you want to take a slower approach, then go for a walk around the office every hour. Once fully adjusted to that, increase the frequency of the walks to every forty-five minutes, every half an hour, and every fifteen minutes. Even if in the middle of a task, going for a walk can lead to a refreshed mind and better productivity. You can then move to sitting on an exercise ball or something that wobbles before moving to standing at your desk. As you being to stand, go in smaller intervals to guarantee your success. Start at five minutes every hour and slowly increase by five minutes each time you become consistent. Finally, if you need to talk to a coworker, get or give something to them, or have a question, walk over to people’s desk rather than emailing or calling them.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhile at home, don’t fast forward through the commercials. Use that time to do a quick workout or activity, clean something, take a small walk around the house, or just spend that time standing. Also consider beginning to incorporate yoga poses that stretch your back. Also, try walking, biking, or using public transportation to get around. As you’re standing on the subway carrying a few bags of groceries you’ll be making a healthier choice than taking a car. Another option is to call friends and family, but stand for the duration of the phone call. Anytime you want to use your phone at all, even texting or checking social media, spend that time on your feet. Also try and take a walk for at least ten minutes once a day.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhether you choose to make a small change or have a complete lifestyle change, it’s important to begin to move towards a life with less time sitting and From student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Kendal Eisenberg</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Sit Less, Stand More','','inherit','open','open','','677-revision-v1','','','2015-04-13 17:57:26','2015-04-13 17:57:26','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/677-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(679,1,'2015-04-14 16:50:00','2015-04-14 16:50:00','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBefore last summer, I had only visited the Florida Everglades once at the age of ten. To say I did not fully appreciate it would be an understatement. On my second visit, I learned to appreciate it fully. The humidity that weekend should have been nearly unbearable, but we were driven to complete the hike across the Otter Cave Hammock Trail in Shark Valley. The trail itself was not difficult. It was structured in a loop so it was easy to follow, and the terrain was reasonable. The Everglades presents an opportunity to do things you may never have dreamed of doing. Walking among snakes longer than your body was even a common experience, but they didn’t mind you in their territory.You’ll never see more iguanas and, depending on the trail, spiders in one place. You will learn to not fear because the animals were accommodating.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of things you can do when you visit the Everglades. Several canoeing and kayaking trails are offered. They could take multiple days to complete, depending on the depth of the trail itself. The Flamingo Canoe Trails are the most popular multi-day canoe trails. Its longest, The Nine Mile Pond, is a 5.2 mile loop which delves into freshwater marsh and is overflowing with docile alligators during the winter months.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those looking for a tamer scene: bird watching is all the rage. Purple Gallinules and Anhingas can be spotted across The Anhinga Trail during the winter season. Snake Bight Trail is known for Mangrove Cuckoos and Warblers wading in the morning. Check out the National Park Service for the Everglades’ impressive <a href=\"http://www.nps.gov/ever/planyourvisit/everglades-national-park-big-day-bird-count-february-15-2014.htm\">bird count</a> last year.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTours offer visitors interested in sightseeing a gander into the marshy, tropical habitats throughout the park. Led by a naturalist, <a href=\"http://www.sharkvalleytramtours.com/tramtours.html\">Shark Valley Tram Tours</a> give you a chance to take in the plant life and the ever-changing species that migrate there. Not to mention a breathtaking view of the Everglades through the Shark Valley observation tower.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBringing home souvenirs in the Everglades can get complicated due to matter of wildlife preservation. Species like seahorses, tropical fish, orchids, starfish, and coral are prohibited for collection. Tempting as it may be to pick up and take home a piece of beautiful coral, it’s illegal to remove it from the park. However, when it comes to fishing, snapper, bluegill, and bass are for the taking.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAuthor and environmentalist, Marjory Stoneman Douglas, wrote, “There are no other Everglades in the world. They are, they have always been, one of the unique regions of the earth, remote, never wholly known. Nothing anywhere else is like them.” Now, I haven’t seen the entire world, but I have entered into the belly of the Everglades, coming out covered in mud and itching all over. If given the chance to do it all over again, no doubt, I would take it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-522\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Angela Bell\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a></strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> Author: Angela Bell</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAngela is a graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','The Florida Everglades Are Calling Your Name','','publish','open','open','','florida-everglades','','','2015-04-14 16:52:05','2015-04-14 16:52:05','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=679',0,'post','',0),(680,1,'2015-04-14 14:44:22','2015-04-14 14:44:22','Before last summer, I had only visited the Florida Everglades once at the age of ten. To say I did not fully appreciate it would be an understatement. On my second visit, I learned to appreciate it fully. The humidity that weekend should have been nearly unbearable, but we were driven to complete the hike across the Otter Cave Hammock Trail in Shark Valley. The trail itself was not difficult. It was structured in a loop so it was easy to follow, and the terrain was reasonable. The Everglades presents an opportunity to do things you may never have dreamed of doing. Walking among snakes longer than your body was even a common experience, but they didn’t mind you in their territory.You’ll never see more iguanas and, depending on the trail, spiders in one place. You will learn to not fear because the animals were accommodating.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of things you can do when you visit the Everglades. Several canoeing and kayaking trails are offered. They could take multiple days to complete, depending on the depth of the trail itself. The Flamingo Canoe Trails are the most popular multi-day canoe trails. Its longest, The Nine Mile Pond, is a 5.2 mile loop which delves into freshwater marsh and is overflowing with docile alligators during the winter months.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those looking for a tamer scene: bird watching is all the rage. Purple Gallinules and Anhingas can be spotted across The Anhinga Trail during the winter season. Snake Bight Trail is known for Mangrove Cuckoos and Warblers wading in the morning. Check out the National Park Service for the Everglades’ impressive <a href=\"http://www.nps.gov/ever/planyourvisit/everglades-national-park-big-day-bird-count-february-15-2014.htm\">bird count</a> last year.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTours offer visitors interested in sightseeing a gander into the marshy, tropical habitats throughout the park. Led by a naturalist, <a href=\"http://www.sharkvalleytramtours.com/tramtours.html\">Shark Valley Tram Tours</a> give you a chance to take in the plant life and the ever-changing species that migrate there. Not to mention a breathtaking view of the Everglades through the Shark Valley observation tower.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBringing home souvenirs in the Everglades can get complicated due to matter of wildlife preservation. Species like seahorses, tropical fish, orchids, starfish, and coral are prohibited for collection. Tempting as it may be to pick up and take home a piece of beautiful coral, it’s illegal to remove it from the park. However, when it comes to fishing, snapper, bluegill, and bass are for the taking.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAuthor and environmentalist, Marjory Stoneman Douglas, wrote, “There are no other Everglades in the world. They are, they have always been, one of the unique regions of the earth, remote, never wholly known. Nothing anywhere else is like them.” Now, I haven’t seen the entire world, but I have entered into the belly of the Everglades, coming out covered in mud and itching all over. If given the chance to do it all over again, no doubt, I would take it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-522\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Angela Bell\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n</strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Angela Bell</b>\r\n\r\nAngela is a graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Florida Everglades Are Calling Your Name','','inherit','open','open','','679-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 14:44:22','2015-04-14 14:44:22','',679,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/679-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(681,1,'2015-04-14 15:30:09','2015-04-14 15:30:09','Backpacking gear & apparel','Patagonia Backpacking','','inherit','open','open','','patagonia-backpacking','','','2015-04-14 15:30:25','2015-04-14 15:30:25','',667,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Patagonia-Backpacking.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(682,1,'2015-04-14 15:33:07','2015-04-14 15:33:07','50 percent off sale','Patagonia 50 percent off','','inherit','open','open','','patagonia-50-percent-off','','','2015-04-14 15:33:22','2015-04-14 15:33:22','',667,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Patagonia-50-percent-off.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(683,1,'2015-04-14 15:35:02','2015-04-14 15:35:02','','Mount Sherman Colorado\'s Easiest Fourteener','','inherit','open','open','','mount-sherman-colorados-easiest-fourteener','','','2015-04-14 15:35:12','2015-04-14 15:35:12','',667,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Mount-Sherman-Colorados-Easiest-Fourteener.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(684,1,'2015-04-14 15:35:23','2015-04-14 15:35:23','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe concept of hiking Fourteeners seems threatening. Climbing a mountain whose summit is at least 14,000 feet above sea level involves determination above all, along with a solid amount of physical fitness and preparation. Still, there are Fourteeners of all difficulty levels out there, and it’s all about starting out with something that feels doable while still offering the rush and accomplishment of summiting a Fourteener. Hiking in Colorado is a must for any outdoor junkie, and Mount Sherman is a perfect mountain to begin with, or to add to your repertoire without too much fuss.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMount Sherman is conveniently located in Colorado on the Mosquito range, not far from Fairplay or Leadville. It’s close to a few other Fourteeners such as Mounts Democrat and Lincoln, so take a few days to stay nearby, start with Sherman, and if you decide hiking Fourteeners is for you, head over to the others.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAt 14,036 feet, Sherman is just high enough to qualify for the category of a Fourteener. In fact, if you know where to look, you can see the small parking lot from the summit. At 2,100 feet, the elevation gain isn’t too demanding. The <a href=\"http://www.14ers.com/routemain.php?route=sher1&amp;peak=mt.+sherman\">trail</a> isn’t needlessly long, resulting in a round trip of just 5.25 miles, but it’s still a gradual enough slope to allow for a steady pace.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOne perk to Sherman is that there’s plenty to look at along the way. The majority of the trail is above tree line, for starters. While hiking through dense, green forests and crossing beautiful little streams is lovely for a while, it can be tiresome to spend hours below tree line at the beginning of a Fourteener. The real feeling of climbing isn’t quite there until you can see the summit (or at least the false summit) and watch it draw closer each time you look up from the trail. The views from the summit are incredible, and the visibility the whole way provides for plenty of breathless moments of awe. Plus, there’s an old mining site a ways up that makes for a historic resting point.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn a more basic note, there are a few important beginner hiking tips to keep in mind no matter which Fourteener you decide to start with. The first and most important Fourteener tip is probably obvious: bring a lot of water. Do not be that person halfway to the summit swallowing your last sip and looking around at everyone else’s multiple full Nalgene bottles. You will, and should, drink more than you might be expecting if it’s your first time. Plan on around half a liter per hour, especially on the way up. This will depend on your personal level of exertion, on how warm or dry the day is, and plenty of other factors. Hydrating before the hike is huge, too; by the time you notice yourself getting thirsty, dehydration is already settling in. Being attentive to your body and planning ahead is the key. Although it seems like a drag to lug a few liters of water to the top of the mountain, it would be a much bigger drag to get halfway up the mountain and have to turn around because you’re out of water and dangerously dehydrated.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSpecifically for those coming from out of state, altitude sickness is another possible obstacle to be aware of. Symptoms are sometimes described to be similar to a hangover: headache, dizziness, nausea and vomiting are all signs of altitude sickness. Although these seem to be simply uncomfortable, another challenge to push through, altitude sickness can also result in edema which can be life-threatening. Again, listening to your body is the most important step in keeping yourself safe. If you’re coming from low altitude and haven’t been at Colorado altitude for a few days or so, take it slow to let yourself acclimate gradually. Staying hydrated helps here, too.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe last thing I’ll mention to be aware of is snow. Even if it’s the middle of June and 80 degrees in Leadville, the summit of Sherman is likely somewhere around 20 degrees and windy, with snow falling every now and then. It’s a good idea to do a bit of time-specific research before embarking on a hike to make sure the trail is completely accessible without snowshoes. Beyond that, just be ready to do a bit of slipping through snow banks! Bring a few layers for the summit, especially if you plan on resting and eating lunch there.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThere are few things more exhilarating and rewarding than submitting a Fourteener and signing your name on the hiking registry. It may take a lot of sweat and a fair amount of planning, but mountain climbing is a hobby well worth the work it demands.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-494\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Elizabeth Thompson</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nElizabeth is a college student in love with mountains, oceans and everything in between. Her travel skills and expertise are constantly being refined while she studies abroad for the semester in Aix-en-Provence, France. At her home university in Colorado, she studies Creative Writing, French, and Business in between weekends on a snowboard and summers lost in the mountains.','Mount Sherman: The Ideal First Fourteener','','inherit','open','open','','667-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 15:35:23','2015-04-14 15:35:23','',667,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/667-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(685,1,'2015-04-14 15:50:24','2015-04-14 15:50:24','A good challenge for Colorado hikers','Manitou Incline_A good challenge for Colorado hikers','','inherit','open','open','','manitou-incline_a-good-challenge-for-colorado-hikers','','','2015-04-14 15:50:32','2015-04-14 15:50:32','',665,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Manitou-Incline_A-good-challenge-for-Colorado-hikers.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(686,1,'2015-04-14 15:52:35','2015-04-14 15:52:35','','REI.com_REI-Outlet Top Brand Closeouts','','inherit','open','open','','rei-com_rei-outlet-top-brand-closeouts','','','2015-04-14 15:52:46','2015-04-14 15:52:46','',665,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/REI.com_REI-Outlet-Top-Brand-Closeouts.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(687,1,'2015-04-14 15:53:25','2015-04-14 15:53:25','REI for active families','REI.com_REI for active families','','inherit','open','open','','rei-com_rei-for-active-families','','','2015-04-14 15:53:33','2015-04-14 15:53:33','',665,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/REI.com_REI-for-active-families.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(688,1,'2015-04-14 15:53:52','2015-04-14 15:53:52','<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you’ve ever been hiking in Colorado, it’s very likely you’ve heard of The Incline. The Manitou Springs Incline has gained quite a bit of attention in the hiking community, and for good reason. The trail, made of old railway ties, is only a mile long, but it covers almost 2,000 vertical feet. Doing the Incline means hiking Pikes Peak’s steepest section in the form of over 2,000 stair-like steps; it’s no easy feat, and nothing if not rewarding. Hiking the incline can be tricky logistically, too. There are six major things to know before embarking on this crazy climb.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>    Parking is hard.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEspecially since the Incline became public property, there is really no time that isn’t crazy busy. There are a few paid parking spots right at the trailhead, which will more than likely be full. Just mentally prepare yourself for an extra mile or so of hiking to and from the trailhead.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>    There is a false summit.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIt is completely believable and absolutely heartbreaking. Once you begin the steepest section, when you look up you will be able to consistently see this false summit. A few times I’ve had random people tell me that it’s not the real summit, just because we all know how soul shattering it is to be staring down your goal during the toughest part of the hike, only to find out that’s not actually the goal. You’ll know the real summit by the crowds of people taking pictures from the top.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>    After you hit the false summit, you’re more than three quarters done!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe trail levels out – as much as it can while still deserving the name “The Incline” – and it really is easier going, and not that far, after that. Even though I know it’s a false summit, I always find myself comforted by getting closer and closer to it just because I know that’s the end of the most challenging chunk.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n  <li>    There is an exit point onto Barr Trail about three quarters of the way up.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf you’re considering not finishing, try to find that rather than turning around and making your way down the incline. It’ll be on your left; you’ll see parts of the Barr Trail railing, made of a dark wood, and you’ll be able to safely cross over to Barr Trail and head back down if you need to.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIf you’re not turning back, it’s still nice to know that when you see Barr Trail you’re almost done!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n  <li>    It’s a lot safer and easier on the body to walk or jog down Barr Trail once you finish rather than going back down the railway ties. I’ve seen countless people go tumbling after just a small misstep, and it’s just rough on the joints to descend such a steep incline. To get to Barr Trail from the summit of the Incline, just go right (if you’re facing down the incline), and hug the trees on the face of the mountain a few meters until you hit the trail. Take a left onto it and start the three-mile descent back toward real life and a celebratory Slurpee.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n <li>    The weather plays a huge role in how doable or enjoyable the Incline will be. I’ve noticed drastic changes in my times simply due to cloud cover or a nice breeze. Obviously we can’t control the weather, but it’s nice to go early in the morning before the day gets too hot and the crowds get too thick. Part of the reason the weather makes such a huge difference is because the trail is so exposed: there’s hardly any shade and no form of protection on the climb up the sheer face of the mountain. Sunscreen is an absolute must, and layers are a good idea too.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-494\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Bio-pic.jpeg\" alt=\"Bio pic\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Elizabeth Thompson</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http:/