rent countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling in pairs:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Look out for each other. Who you’re with is your best resource. Take care of them and they’ll do the same for you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>If one of you notices that something feels wrong, don’t ignore that feeling. If you feel like it’s not just the two of you, look around and make sure you have a plan in case something were to happen.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Try and stick as close together as possible, without suffocating each other. Leave room to explore on your own, but be close enough that you can be helpful if anything happens.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling alone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Don\'t stare at your phone for too long. It\'s rare that you’re fully alone, so make sure you\'re <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D66L1o-uES0\">paying attention to what\'s around you</a>. Give a paper map a shot and keep your phone tucked away. Be in the experience.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>Sit at the end of a row on public transportation. That way you have the wall or aisle on one side of you and only have to sit next to one person. This reduces the odds you\'ll find yourself sitting next to someone who makes you uncomfortable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>If you can\'t find a seat at the end, then sit next to a mom or someone in a business suit. Moms are always on the lookout because they want their kids to be safe. She\'ll be alert and you\'ll know if something is wrong. If a mom isn\'t available then sit next to a professional looking man or woman. They spend a lot of the ride staring at their phone, so you won\'t have to worry about interacting. It’s not a foolproof method, but it’s worked pretty well so far.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for everyone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>If you really want to listen to music while you’re on the go, keep the volume to the lowest level possible. You need to be able to hear what’s going on around you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>Attract as little attention as possible. Quietly slip on and off transportation, don\'t talk too loudly, and pay attention to the things around you. Meeting people is one of the best parts of going on an adventure, just make sure to meet the right people!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Have at least one <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ooeAzo2oVJU\">go to self-defense move</a>. If the worst does happen then you need one move that you feel confident enough in to execute properly. You never know what’s going to happen, but at least you know you’re not helpless.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTraveling alone or with someone else is a great opportunity to learn about yourself and each other. It’s something everyone should experience, but you should always be safe about it. Time to start planning your next big adventure!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Safety Tips for Traveling Alone or in Pairs','','inherit','open','open','','671-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:15:55','2015-04-14 16:15:55','',671,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/671-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(695,1,'2015-04-14 16:30:06','2015-04-14 16:30:06','&nbsp;\n\nLast summer I wandered around Europe and visited four different countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\n\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n\n<b>Tips for traveling in pairs:</b>\n\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol>\n <li>Look out for each other. Who you’re with is your best resource. Take care of them and they’ll do the same for you.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n <li>If one of you notices that something feels wrong, don’t ignore that feeling. If you feel like it’s not just the two of you, look around and make sure you have a plan in case something were to happen.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n  <li>Try and stick as close together as possible, without suffocating each other. Leave room to explore on your own, but be close enough that you can be helpful if anything happens.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Tips for traveling alone:</b>\n\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol>\n <li>Don\'t stare at your phone for too long. It\'s rare that you’re fully alone, so make sure you\'re <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D66L1o-uES0\">paying attention to what\'s around you</a>. Give a paper map a shot and keep your phone tucked away. Be in the experience.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n <li>Sit at the end of a row on public transportation. That way you have the wall or aisle on one side of you and only have to sit next to one person. This reduces the odds you\'ll find yourself sitting next to someone who makes you uncomfortable.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n <li>If you can\'t find a seat at the end, then sit next to a mom or someone in a business suit. Moms are always on the lookout because they want their kids to be safe. She\'ll be alert and you\'ll know if something is wrong. If a mom isn\'t available then sit next to a professional looking man or woman. They spend a lot of the ride staring at their phone, so you won\'t have to worry about interacting. It’s not a foolproof method, but it’s worked pretty well so far.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<b>Tips for everyone:</b>\n\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol>\n <li>If you really want to listen to music while you’re on the go, keep the volume to the lowest level possible. You need to be able to hear what’s going on around you.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n  <li>Attract as little attention as possible. Quietly slip on and off transportation, don\'t talk too loudly, and pay attention to the things around you. Meeting people is one of the best parts of going on an adventure, just make sure to meet the right people!</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n  <li>Have at least one <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ooeAzo2oVJU\">go to self-defense move</a>. If the worst does happen then you need one move that you feel confident enough in to execute properly. You never know what’s going to happen, but at least you know you’re not helpless.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\n\nTraveling alone or with someone else is a great opportunity to learn about yourself and each other. It’s something everyone should experience, but you should always be safe about it. Time to start planning your next big adventure!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Author: Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>About</strong>\n\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\n\n&nbsp;','Safety Tips for Traveling Alone or in Pairs','','inherit','open','open','','671-autosave-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:30:06','2015-04-14 16:30:06','',671,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/671-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(696,1,'2015-04-14 16:30:41','2015-04-14 16:30:41','Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network','Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network','','inherit','open','open','','kendall-eisenberg_writer_live-out-the-outdoor-social-network-2','','','2015-04-14 16:30:55','2015-04-14 16:30:55','',671,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(697,1,'2015-04-14 16:31:17','2015-04-14 16:31:17','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLast summer I wandered around Europe and visited four different countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling in pairs:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Look out for each other. Who you’re with is your best resource. Take care of them and they’ll do the same for you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>If one of you notices that something feels wrong, don’t ignore that feeling. If you feel like it’s not just the two of you, look around and make sure you have a plan in case something were to happen.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Try and stick as close together as possible, without suffocating each other. Leave room to explore on your own, but be close enough that you can be helpful if anything happens.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling alone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Don\'t stare at your phone for too long. It\'s rare that you’re fully alone, so make sure you\'re <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D66L1o-uES0\">paying attention to what\'s around you</a>. Give a paper map a shot and keep your phone tucked away. Be in the experience.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>Sit at the end of a row on public transportation. That way you have the wall or aisle on one side of you and only have to sit next to one person. This reduces the odds you\'ll find yourself sitting next to someone who makes you uncomfortable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>If you can\'t find a seat at the end, then sit next to a mom or someone in a business suit. Moms are always on the lookout because they want their kids to be safe. She\'ll be alert and you\'ll know if something is wrong. If a mom isn\'t available then sit next to a professional looking man or woman. They spend a lot of the ride staring at their phone, so you won\'t have to worry about interacting. It’s not a foolproof method, but it’s worked pretty well so far.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for everyone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>If you really want to listen to music while you’re on the go, keep the volume to the lowest level possible. You need to be able to hear what’s going on around you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>Attract as little attention as possible. Quietly slip on and off transportation, don\'t talk too loudly, and pay attention to the things around you. Meeting people is one of the best parts of going on an adventure, just make sure to meet the right people!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Have at least one <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ooeAzo2oVJU\">go to self-defense move</a>. If the worst does happen then you need one move that you feel confident enough in to execute properly. You never know what’s going to happen, but at least you know you’re not helpless.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTraveling alone or with someone else is a great opportunity to learn about yourself and each other. It’s something everyone should experience, but you should always be safe about it. Time to start planning your next big adventure!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Safety Tips for Traveling Alone or in Pairs','','inherit','open','open','','671-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:31:17','2015-04-14 16:31:17','',671,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/671-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(699,1,'2015-04-14 16:34:50','2015-04-14 16:34:50','Bored Boy has no success at the computer and gets an error message','Desperate Man sitting at the Computer','','inherit','open','open','','desperate-man-sitting-at-the-computer','','','2015-04-14 16:34:50','2015-04-14 16:34:50','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Desperate-Man-sitting-at-the-Computer.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(700,1,'2015-04-14 16:34:55','2015-04-14 16:34:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn average, American’s spend only three hours a day being active or standing. According to <a href=\"http://annals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2091327\">a study</a> released in January, sitting for too long increases your risk of getting diabetes, heart disease, cancer, and can result in premature death. To not be considered sedentary, it’s essential to get one hundred and fifty minutes of moderate activity a week or seventy-five minutes of vigorous activity a week - spread out over the course of the week to avoid being sedentary. While exercise is an important part of a healthy lifestyle, there are more effective ways to combat the impacts of prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can be done to reduce the effects of prolonged sitting? Rather than adding more time to your workout, simple lifestyle adjustments at work or at home can have a more positive impact on your quality of life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at work, consider a standing desk. Instead of sitting in a chair all day, it would help to spend that time on your feet. This option can be daunting to people who currently spend that time in a chair. Eight hours of sitting straight to standing is difficult. If you want to take a slower approach, then go for a walk around the office every hour. Once fully adjusted to that, increase the frequency of the walks to every forty-five minutes, every half an hour, and every fifteen minutes. Even if in the middle of a task, going for a walk can lead to a refreshed mind and better productivity. You can then move to sitting on an exercise ball or something that wobbles before moving to standing at your desk. As you being to stand, go in smaller intervals to guarantee your success. Start at five minutes every hour and slowly increase by five minutes each time you become consistent. Finally, if you need to talk to a coworker, get or give something to them, or have a question, walk over to people’s desk rather than emailing or calling them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at home, don’t fast forward through the commercials. Use that time to do a quick workout or activity, clean something, take a small walk around the house, or just spend that time standing. Also consider beginning to incorporate yoga poses that stretch your back. Also, try walking, biking, or using public transportation to get around. As you’re standing on the subway carrying a few bags of groceries you’ll be making a healthier choice than taking a car. Another option is to call friends and family, but stand for the duration of the phone call. Anytime you want to use your phone at all, even texting or checking social media, spend that time on your feet. Also try and take a walk for at least ten minutes once a day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhether you choose to make a small change or have a complete lifestyle change, it’s important to begin to move towards a life with less time sitting and From student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Kendal Eisenberg</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Sit Less, Stand More','','inherit','open','open','','677-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:34:55','2015-04-14 16:34:55','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/677-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(701,1,'2015-04-14 16:37:58','2015-04-14 16:37:58','Fitness activity monitors','Fitness activity monitors at CleverTraining','','inherit','open','open','','fitness-activity-monitors-at-clevertraining','','','2015-04-14 16:38:10','2015-04-14 16:38:10','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Fitness-activity-monitors-at-CleverTraining.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(702,1,'2015-04-14 16:39:39','2015-04-14 16:39:39','','Mediafast Advantage Program','','inherit','open','open','','mediafast-advantage-program','','','2015-04-14 16:39:59','2015-04-14 16:39:59','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Mediafast-Advantage-Program.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(703,1,'2015-04-14 16:40:30','2015-04-14 16:40:30','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. Whi