g, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Sit Less, Stand More','','inherit','open','open','','677-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:40:30','2015-04-14 16:40:30','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/677-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(704,1,'2015-04-14 16:47:56','2015-04-14 16:47:56','fan-boat-airboat','fan-boat-airboat-everglades','','inherit','open','open','','fan-boat-airboat-everglades','','','2015-04-14 16:48:15','2015-04-14 16:48:15','',679,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/fan-boat-airboat-everglades.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(705,1,'2015-04-14 16:49:48','2015-04-14 16:49:48','','AdventureLink_Adventure Without Risk','','inherit','open','open','','adventurelink_adventure-without-risk','','','2015-04-14 16:49:56','2015-04-14 16:49:56','',679,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/AdventureLink_Adventure-Without-Risk.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(706,1,'2015-04-14 16:50:00','2015-04-14 16:50:00','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBefore last summer, I had only visited the Florida Everglades once at the age of ten. To say I did not fully appreciate it would be an understatement. On my second visit, I learned to appreciate it fully. The humidity that weekend should have been nearly unbearable, but we were driven to complete the hike across the Otter Cave Hammock Trail in Shark Valley. The trail itself was not difficult. It was structured in a loop so it was easy to follow, and the terrain was reasonable. The Everglades presents an opportunity to do things you may never have dreamed of doing. Walking among snakes longer than your body was even a common experience, but they didn’t mind you in their territory.You’ll never see more iguanas and, depending on the trail, spiders in one place. You will learn to not fear because the animals were accommodating.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of things you can do when you visit the Everglades. Several canoeing and kayaking trails are offered. They could take multiple days to complete, depending on the depth of the trail itself. The Flamingo Canoe Trails are the most popular multi-day canoe trails. Its longest, The Nine Mile Pond, is a 5.2 mile loop which delves into freshwater marsh and is overflowing with docile alligators during the winter months.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those looking for a tamer scene: bird watching is all the rage. Purple Gallinules and Anhingas can be spotted across The Anhinga Trail during the winter season. Snake Bight Trail is known for Mangrove Cuckoos and Warblers wading in the morning. Check out the National Park Service for the Everglades’ impressive <a href=\"http://www.nps.gov/ever/planyourvisit/everglades-national-park-big-day-bird-count-february-15-2014.htm\">bird count</a> last year.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTours offer visitors interested in sightseeing a gander into the marshy, tropical habitats throughout the park. Led by a naturalist, <a href=\"http://www.sharkvalleytramtours.com/tramtours.html\">Shark Valley Tram Tours</a> give you a chance to take in the plant life and the ever-changing species that migrate there. Not to mention a breathtaking view of the Everglades through the Shark Valley observation tower.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBringing home souvenirs in the Everglades can get complicated due to matter of wildlife preservation. Species like seahorses, tropical fish, orchids, starfish, and coral are prohibited for collection. Tempting as it may be to pick up and take home a piece of beautiful coral, it’s illegal to remove it from the park. However, when it comes to fishing, snapper, bluegill, and bass are for the taking.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAuthor and environmentalist, Marjory Stoneman Douglas, wrote, “There are no other Everglades in the world. They are, they have always been, one of the unique regions of the earth, remote, never wholly known. Nothing anywhere else is like them.” Now, I haven’t seen the entire world, but I have entered into the belly of the Everglades, coming out covered in mud and itching all over. If given the chance to do it all over again, no doubt, I would take it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-522\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Angela Bell\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a></strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> Author: Angela Bell</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAngela is a graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.','The Florida Everglades Are Calling Your Name','','inherit','open','open','','679-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:50:00','2015-04-14 16:50:00','',679,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/679-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(707,1,'2015-04-14 16:52:05','2015-04-14 16:52:05','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBefore last summer, I had only visited the Florida Everglades once at the age of ten. To say I did not fully appreciate it would be an understatement. On my second visit, I learned to appreciate it fully. The humidity that weekend should have been nearly unbearable, but we were driven to complete the hike across the Otter Cave Hammock Trail in Shark Valley. The trail itself was not difficult. It was structured in a loop so it was easy to follow, and the terrain was reasonable. The Everglades presents an opportunity to do things you may never have dreamed of doing. Walking among snakes longer than your body was even a common experience, but they didn’t mind you in their territory.You’ll never see more iguanas and, depending on the trail, spiders in one place. You will learn to not fear because the animals were accommodating.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are plenty of things you can do when you visit the Everglades. Several canoeing and kayaking trails are offered. They could take multiple days to complete, depending on the depth of the trail itself. The Flamingo Canoe Trails are the most popular multi-day canoe trails. Its longest, The Nine Mile Pond, is a 5.2 mile loop which delves into freshwater marsh and is overflowing with docile alligators during the winter months.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nFor those looking for a tamer scene: bird watching is all the rage. Purple Gallinules and Anhingas can be spotted across The Anhinga Trail during the winter season. Snake Bight Trail is known for Mangrove Cuckoos and Warblers wading in the morning. Check out the National Park Service for the Everglades’ impressive <a href=\"http://www.nps.gov/ever/planyourvisit/everglades-national-park-big-day-bird-count-february-15-2014.htm\">bird count</a> last year.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTours offer visitors interested in sightseeing a gander into the marshy, tropical habitats throughout the park. Led by a naturalist, <a href=\"http://www.sharkvalleytramtours.com/tramtours.html\">Shark Valley Tram Tours</a> give you a chance to take in the plant life and the ever-changing species that migrate there. Not to mention a breathtaking view of the Everglades through the Shark Valley observation tower.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nBringing home souvenirs in the Everglades can get complicated due to matter of wildlife preservation. Species like seahorses, tropical fish, orchids, starfish, and coral are prohibited for collection. Tempting as it may be to pick up and take home a piece of beautiful coral, it’s illegal to remove it from the park. However, when it comes to fishing, snapper, bluegill, and bass are for the taking.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAuthor and environmentalist, Marjory Stoneman Douglas, wrote, “There are no other Everglades in the world. They are, they have always been, one of the unique regions of the earth, remote, never wholly known. Nothing anywhere else is like them.” Now, I haven’t seen the entire world, but I have entered into the belly of the Everglades, coming out covered in mud and itching all over. If given the chance to do it all over again, no doubt, I would take it.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-522\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Angela-Bell_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.png\" alt=\"Angela Bell\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a></strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> Author: Angela Bell</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAngela is a graduating senior majoring in Mass Communications and minoring in Creative Writing. In the future, she plans to get her MA in Publishing and Writing and travel overseas for volunteer work. Her hobbies include running, filming, and writing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','The Florida Everglades Are Calling Your Name','','inherit','open','open','','679-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:52:05','2015-04-14 16:52:05','',679,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/679-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(708,1,'2015-04-14 16:52:25','2015-04-14 16:52:25','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn average, American’s spend only three hours a day being active or standing. According to <a href=\"http://annals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2091327\">a study</a> released in January, sitting for too long increases your risk of getting diabetes, heart disease, cancer, and can result in premature death. To not be considered sedentary, it’s essential to get one hundred and fifty minutes of moderate activity a week or seventy-five minutes of vigorous activity a week - spread out over the course of the week to avoid being sedentary. While exercise is an important part of a healthy lifestyle, there are more effective ways to combat the impacts of prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can be done to reduce the effects of prolonged sitting? Rather than adding more time to your workout, simple lifestyle adjustments at work or at home can have a more positive impact on your quality of life.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at work, consider a standing desk. Instead of sitting in a chair all day, it would help to spend that time on your feet. This option can be daunting to people who currently spend that time in a chair. Eight hours of sitting straight to standing is difficult. If you want to take a slower approach, then go for a walk around the office every hour. Once fully adjusted to that, increase the frequency of the walks to every forty-five minutes, every half an hour, and every fifteen minutes. Even if in the middle of a task, going for a walk can lead to a refreshed mind and better productivity. You can then move to sitting on an exercise ball or something that wobbles before moving to standing at your desk. As you being to stand, go in smaller intervals to guarantee your success. Start at five minutes every hour and slowly increase by five minutes each time you become consistent. Finally, if you need to talk to a coworker, get or give something to them, or have a question, walk over to people’s desk rather than emailing or calling them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile at home, don’t fast forward through the commercials. Use that time to do a quick workout or activity, clean something, take a small walk around the house, or just spend that time standing. Also consider beginning to incorporate yoga poses that stretch your back. Also, try walking, biking, or using public transportation to get around. As you’re standing on the subway carrying a few bags of groceries you’ll be making a healthier choice than taking a car. Another option is to call friends and family, but stand for the duration of the phone call. Anytime you want to use your phone at all, even texting or checking social media, spend that time on your feet. Also try and take a walk for at least ten minutes once a day.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhether you choose to make a small change or have a complete lifestyle change, it’s important to begin to move towards a life with less time sitting and From student to seasoned professional, many people spend a majority of their day sitting behind a desk. While everyone knows the benefits of being active, very few realize the consequences from prolonged sitting.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Kendal Eisenberg</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Sit Less, Stand More','','inherit','open','open','','677-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:52:25','2015-04-14 16:52:25','',677,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/677-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(709,1,'2015-04-14 16:52:54','2015-04-14 16:52:54','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLast summer I wandered around Europe and visited four different countries. During each visit I was either traveling by myself or with a friend. It can be really dangerous to travel alone - or even with a friend. This doesn\'t mean you need to be scared every time you get on a metro; you just need to be paying attention. Whether you’re wandering through the city or taking a hike you’ve always dreamed of, it’s important to be aware. Here are some safety tips that can work for the city or even the most rural settings.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling in pairs:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Look out for each other. Who you’re with is your best resource. Take care of them and they’ll do the same for you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>If one of you notices that something feels wrong, don’t ignore that feeling. If you feel like it’s not just the two of you, look around and make sure you have a plan in case something were to happen.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Try and stick as close together as possible, without suffocating each other. Leave room to explore on your own, but be close enough that you can be helpful if anything happens.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for traveling alone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>Don\'t stare at your phone for too long. It\'s rare that you’re fully alone, so make sure you\'re <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D66L1o-uES0\">paying attention to what\'s around you</a>. Give a paper map a shot and keep your phone tucked away. Be in the experience.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n <li>Sit at the end of a row on public transportation. That way you have the wall or aisle on one side of you and only have to sit next to one person. This reduces the odds you\'ll find yourself sitting next to someone who makes you uncomfortable.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n <li>If you can\'t find a seat at the end, then sit next to a mom or someone in a business suit. Moms are always on the lookout because they want their kids to be safe. She\'ll be alert and you\'ll know if something is wrong. If a mom isn\'t available then sit next to a professional looking man or woman. They spend a lot of the ride staring at their phone, so you won\'t have to worry about interacting. It’s not a foolproof method, but it’s worked pretty well so far.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Tips for everyone:</b>\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n <li>If you really want to listen to music while you’re on the go, keep the volume to the lowest level possible. You need to be able to hear what’s going on around you.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n  <li>Attract as little attention as possible. Quietly slip on and off transportation, don\'t talk too loudly, and pay attention to the things around you. Meeting people is one of the best parts of going on an adventure, just make sure to meet the right people!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n  <li>Have at least one <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ooeAzo2oVJU\">go to self-defense move</a>. If the worst does happen then you need one move that you feel confident enough in to execute properly. You never know what’s going to happen, but at least you know you’re not helpless.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nTraveling alone or with someone else is a great opportunity to learn about yourself and each other. It’s something everyone should experience, but you should always be safe about it. Time to start planning your next big adventure!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-696\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Kendall-Eisenberg_Writer_Live-Out-The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Kendall Eisenberg\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Kendall Eisenberg</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nKendall is a freshman at the University of Miami studying entrepreneurship. With a motto of “try everything at least once,” she’s participated in soccer, basketball, rock climbing, rowing, and much more. Her hobbies include traveling, writing, reading, and sports.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Safety Tips for Traveling Alone or in Pairs','','inherit','open','open','','671-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 16:52:54','2015-04-14 16:52:54','',671,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/671-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(711,1,'2015-04-30 17:16:44','2015-04-30 17:16:44','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBeyond the mainland of North Carolina sits a string of islands known as the Outer Banks. These islands act as a buffer between the monotony of mainland life and the vastness of the Atlantic. People flock here to experience the warm spring days, the dazzling sunsets, and a multitude of outdoor activities. Here is a list of five outdoor activities that you won’t want to miss on the Outer Banks.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Swim in the Ocean</b>\r\n\r\nWhen my cousins and I were kids, there were few things we enjoyed more than to wade out into the ocean and let the waves slam into us. It’s an exhilarating experience to let those massive walls of water knock you offto your feet and let them wash you back to shore. Boogie boarding is also popular; this is where you use large blocks of foam to ride the waves at tremendous velocities. More coordinated people can try surfing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPopular culture has instilled many fearful images in our minds of monstrous sharks that drag you to the bottom of the ocean. The reality is that sharks are generally docile creatures, and media reports of shark attacks are often overblown.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Relax on the Beach</b>\r\n\r\nFor those who may be freaked out about going in the water, relaxing on the beach is always an option. Not only can you lay around and contemplate the meaning of existence, but you can also wander the beach in search of a huge variety of colorful seashells. If you have small kids (or even if you don’t), it’s always fun to construct a sandcastle. For an extra challenge, build it in a tidal area and construct barriers to hold off the water.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Go Hiking</b>\r\n\r\nSeveral parts of the Outer Banks include hiking areas in the maritime forests. On Ocracoke Island, Springer’s Point leads hikers through a labyrinthine mass of trees and shrubs before opening up onto a beach in front of Pamlico Sound. There are many nooks and crannies to discover on these islands, and hikers will not be disappointed.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Visit a Lighthouse</b>\r\n\r\nThere are several lighthouses on the Outer Banks, and some of them are open to the public. At Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, guests can climb all the way to the top and get a magnificent view of the surrounding area. In addition, there are many old stories and legends that go along with these lighthouses.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Go Fishing</b>\r\n\r\nFishing is a popular pastime on the Outer Banks, whether it be from the shore or from a boat. With a proper license, visitors can cast their lines out into the sea to try and hook a wide array of exotic creatures such as flounder and bluefish. Obviously you can eat most of them, but observing the variety of ocean life that you pull in is half the fun.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThese are just a few of the things that you can do on the Outer Banks of North Carolina. With a bit of exploration, it’s easy to uncover a plethora of other activities just waiting to be discovered!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Andrew McClure</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAndrew McClure graduated from Western Carolina University with a B.A. in English, a concentration in professional writing, and a minor in biology. He is currently trying to enter the world of freelance writing. In his free time, he enjoys reading and studying alongside his dogs, Pepper and Little Ann.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Top Five Things to Do on the Outer Banks','','publish','open','open','','top-five-things-to-do-on-the-outer-banks','','','2015-04-30 17:35:44','2015-04-30 17:35:44','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=711',0,'post','',0),(712,1,'2015-04-27 17:08:51','2015-04-27 17:08:51','Beyond the mainland of <b>North Carolina</b> sits a string of islands known as the <b>Outer Banks</b>. These islands act as a buffer between the monotony of mainland life and the vastness of the Atlantic. People flock here to experience the warm spring days, the dazzling sunsets, and a multitude of outdoor activities. Here is a list of five outdoor activities that you won’t want to miss on the <b>Outer Banks</b>.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Swim in the Ocean</b>\r\n\r\nWhen my cousins and I were kids, there were few things we enjoyed more than to wade out into the <b>ocean</b> and let the waves slam into us. It’s an exhilarating experience to let those massive walls of water knock you offto your feet and let them wash you back to shore. <b>Boogie boarding</b> is also popular; this is where you use large