ir lines out into the sea to try and hook a wide array of exotic creatures such as flounder and bluefish. Obviously you can eat most of them, but observing the variety of ocean life that you pull in is half the fun.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThese are just a few of the things that you can do on the <b>Outer Banks</b> of <b>North Carolina</b>. With a bit of exploration, it’s easy to uncover a plethora of other activities just waiting to be discovered!\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\nAndrew McClure graduated from Western Carolina University with a B.A. in English, a concentration in professional writing, and a minor in biology. He is currently trying to enter the world of freelance writing. In his free time, he enjoys reading and studying alongside his dogs, Pepper and Little Ann. </strong>','Top Five Things to Do on the Outer Banks','','inherit','open','open','','711-revision-v1','','','2015-04-27 17:08:51','2015-04-27 17:08:51','',711,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/711-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(713,1,'2015-04-30 17:32:57','2015-04-30 17:32:57','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs a snow lover, do you go on the same vacation every year? Hitting the slopes of your favorite resort by day, and enjoying a nice soak in the hot tub by night? Despite the fact that you love to get outdoors and enjoy the slopes, going on the same vacation every year, and sliding down the same runs over and over can get boring! And you’re not a boring person! You’re adventurous and love a challenge!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhy don’t you mix things up on your next snowy trip! I’m not talking about snowshoeing or cross-country skiing (my preferred icy sporty), but about the latest snowy trend and fastest growing segment of the sport of skiing according to Snowsports Industries of America: <i>uphill </i>skiing.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nUphill skiing; AKA <i>Alpine Touring, </i>mixes the great work out and the sense of exploration and adventure that snowshoeing and cross-country skiing provide with the exhilaration and wind-in-your-face sensation of the classic downhill style. By skipping the chair lift and trekking up the mountain in order to smoothly sail down it, you can enjoy the best of both worlds.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI know what you’re thinking, how does one keep from just sliding backwards down the mountain after every step? There’s gear for that silly! The first thing that you’ll need are some removable strips that will help you grip. These are called climbing skins. Most climbing skins are made from nylon and are smooth in one direction and rough in the other. This design allows the wearer to easily slide up the mountain but also stay in place once they put their feet down. (Make sure you put the climbing strips on in the right direction. They should feel smooth if you run your finger along your ski from tip to tail).\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are several online retailers that offer alpine touring equipment. If you are new to the sport and don’t really know what you’re looking for, I would recommend not buying the first gear that you see on Amazon. The outdoor retailer <a href=\"http://www.evo.com/\">evo</a> has a very articulate guide to buy the right skins for your skis and how to fit them properly on their website. Buying the proper gear and knowing how to use it correctly is essential if you want to have a great experience with this fun sport.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlong with the very essential climbing skins, you’re also going to want to get some new bindings and boots. They make special bindings that have levers to release the back of the binding but keep the toe attached, making your uphill hike <i>much </i>more comfortable. For alpine touring, a lighter boot is best, one where you can release the cuff for more mobility in your ankle.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlpine touring can take awhile to get used to, especially if you\'ve never been cross country skiing, but like every other adventurous outdoor activity you\'ve tackled thus far, you’ll get the hang of it in no time!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNext time you get the itch to play in some snow, why don’t you grab some friends and try out alpine touring? By the end of the trip you will all be able to cross off another great adventure on your bucket list! Who knows? Maybe you’ll make some new friends along the way too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you go: Do your research; some ski spots do not allow any alpine touring at all, while others have designated trails, or times of day when it is permitted. And be sure to take an avalanche class and carry the proper emergency essentials.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-456\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Michaela Cook\" width=\"125\" height=\"125\" /></a></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Michaela Cook</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nMichaela is an outdoor enthusiast, writer, and undergraduate marketing student in the Eller College of Management at the University of Arizona.','Uphill Skiing','','publish','open','open','','uphill-skiing','','','2015-04-30 17:32:57','2015-04-30 17:32:57','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=713',0,'post','',0),(714,1,'2015-04-28 17:33:11','2015-04-28 17:33:11','As a snow lover, do you go on the same vacation every year? Hitting the slopes of your favorite resort by day, and enjoying a nice soak in the hot tub by night? Despite the fact that you love to get outdoors and enjoy the slopes, going on the same vacation every year, and sliding down the same runs over and over can get boring! And you’re not a boring person! You’re adventurous and love a challenge!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nWhy don’t you mix things up on your next snowy trip! I’m not talking about snowshoeing or cross-country skiing (my prefered icy sporty), but about the latest snowy trend and fastest growing segment of the sport of skiing according to Snowsports Industries of America: <i>uphill </i>skiing.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nUphill skiing; AKA <i>Alpine Touring, </i>mixes the great work out and the sense of exploration and adventure that snowshoeing and cross-country skiing provide with the exhilaration and wind-in-your-face sensation of the classic downhill style. By skipping the chair lift and trekking up the mountain in order to smoothly sail down it, you can enjoy the best of both worlds.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI know what you’re thinking, how does one keep from just sliding backwards down the mountain after every step? There’s gear for that silly! The first thing that you’ll need are some removable strips that will help you grip. These are called climbing skins. Most climbing skins are made from nylon and are smooth in one direction and rough in the other. This design allows the wearer to easily slide up the mountain but also stay in place once they put their feet down. (Make sure you put the climbing strips on in the right direction. They should feel smooth if you run your finger along your ski from tip to tail).\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are several online retailers that offer alpine touring equipment. If you are new to the sport and don’t really know what you’re looking for, I would recommend not buying the first gear that you see on Amazon. The outdoor retailer <a href=\"http://www.evo.com/\">evo</a> has a very articulate guide to buy the right skins for your skis and how to fit them properly on their website. Buying the proper gear and knowing how to use it correctly is essential if you want to have a great experience with this fun sport.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlong with the very essential climbing skins, you’re also going to want to get some new bindings and boots. They make special bindings that have levers to release the back of the binding but keep the toe attached, making your uphill hike <i>much </i>more comfortable. For alpine touring, a lighter boot is best, one where you can release the cuff for more mobility in your ankle.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlpine touring can take awhile to get used to, especially if you’ve never been cross country skiing, but like every other adventurous outdoor activity you’ve tackled thus far, you’ll get the hang of it in no time!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNext time you get the itch to play in some snow, why don’t you grab some friends and try out alpine touring? By the end of the trip you will all be able to cross off another great adventure on your bucket list! Who knows? Maybe you’ll make some new friends along the way too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you go: Do your research; some ski spots do not allow any alpine touring at all, while others have designated trails, or times of day when it is permitted. It is also recommended that you take an avalanche class and carry the proper emergency essentials.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Uphill Skiing','','inherit','open','open','','713-revision-v1','','','2015-04-28 17:33:11','2015-04-28 17:33:11','',713,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/713-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(715,1,'2015-04-28 18:03:56','2015-04-28 18:03:56','As a snow lover, do you go on the same vacation every year? Hitting the slopes of your favorite resort by day, and enjoying a nice soak in the hot tub by night? Despite the fact that you love to get outdoors and enjoy the slopes, going on the same vacation every year, and sliding down the same runs over a