ng></strong>\r\n\r\nUphill skiing; AKA <i>Alpine Touring, </i>mixes the great work out and the sense of exploration and adventure that snowshoeing and cross-country skiing provide with the exhilaration and wind-in-your-face sensation of the classic downhill style. By skipping the chair lift and trekking up the mountain in order to smoothly sail down it, you can enjoy the best of both worlds.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nI know what you’re thinking, how does one keep from just sliding backwards down the mountain after every step? There’s gear for that silly! The first thing that you’ll need are some removable strips that will help you grip. These are called climbing skins. Most climbing skins are made from nylon and are smooth in one direction and rough in the other. This design allows the wearer to easily slide up the mountain but also stay in place once they put their feet down. (Make sure you put the climbing strips on in the right direction. They should feel smooth if you run your finger along your ski from tip to tail).\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThere are several online retailers that offer alpine touring equipment. If you are new to the sport and don’t really know what you’re looking for, I would recommend not buying the first gear that you see on Amazon. The outdoor retailer <a href=\"http://www.evo.com/\">evo</a> has a very articulate guide to buy the right skins for your skis and how to fit them properly on their website. Buying the proper gear and knowing how to use it correctly is essential if you want to have a great experience with this fun sport.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlong with the very essential climbing skins, you’re also going to want to get some new bindings and boots. They make special bindings that have levers to release the back of the binding but keep the toe attached, making your uphill hike <i>much </i>more comfortable. For alpine touring, a lighter boot is best, one where you can release the cuff for more mobility in your ankle.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nAlpine touring can take awhile to get used to, especially if you\'ve never been cross country skiing, but like every other adventurous outdoor activity you\'ve tackled thus far, you’ll get the hang of it in no time!\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNext time you get the itch to play in some snow, why don’t you grab some friends and try out alpine touring? By the end of the trip you will all be able to cross off another great adventure on your bucket list! Who knows? Maybe you’ll make some new friends along the way too.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nIf you go: Do your research; some ski spots do not allow any alpine touring at all, while others have designated trails, or times of day when it is permitted. And be sure to take an avalanche class and carry the proper emergency essentials.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-456\" src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Michaela-Cook_Writer_Live-Out_The-Outdoor-Social-Network.jpg\" alt=\"Michaela Cook\" width=\"125\" height=\"125\" /></a></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Author: Michaela Cook</b>\r\n\r\nContributor, Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>About</b>\r\n\r\nMichaela is an outdoor enthusiast, writer, and undergraduate marketing student in the Eller College of Management at the University of Arizona.','Uphill Skiing','','inherit','open','open','','713-revision-v1','','','2015-04-30 17:32:57','2015-04-30 17:32:57','',713,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/713-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(727,1,'2015-04-30 17:35:44','2015-04-30 17:35:44','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBeyond the mainland of North Carolina sits a string of islands known as the Outer Banks. These islands act as a buffer between the monotony of mainland life and the vastness of the Atlantic. People flock here to experience the warm spring days, the dazzling sunsets, and a multitude of outdoor activities. Here is a list of five outdoor activities that you won’t want to miss on the Outer Banks.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Swim in the Ocean</b>\r\n\r\nWhen my cousins and I were kids, there were few things we enjoyed more than to wade out into the ocean and let the waves slam into us. It’s an exhilarating experience to let those massive walls of water knock you offto your feet and let them wash you back to shore. Boogie boarding is also popular; this is where you use large blocks of foam to ride the waves at tremendous velocities. More coordinated people can try surfing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPopular culture has instilled many fearful images in our minds of monstrous sharks that drag you to the bottom of the ocean. The reality is that sharks are generally docile creatures, and media reports of shark attacks are often overblown.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Relax on the Beach</b>\r\n\r\nFor those who may be freaked out about going in the water, relaxing on the beach is always an option. Not only can you lay around and contemplate the meaning of existence, but you can also wander the beach in search of a huge variety of colorful seashells. If you have small kids (or even if you don’t), it’s always fun to construct a sandcastle. For an extra challenge, build it in a tidal area and construct barriers to hold off the water.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Go Hiking</b>\r\n\r\nSeveral parts of the Outer Banks include hiking areas in the maritime forests. On Ocracoke Island, Springer’s Point leads hikers through a labyrinthine mass of trees and shrubs before opening up onto a beach in front of Pamlico Sound. There are many nooks and crannies to discover on these islands, and hikers will not be disappointed.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Visit a Lighthouse</b>\r\n\r\nThere are several lighthouses on the Outer Banks, and some of them are open to the public. At Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, guests can climb all the way to the top and get a magnificent view of the surrounding area. In addition, there are many old stories and legends that go along with these lighthouses.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Go Fishing</b>\r\n\r\nFishing is a popular pastime on the Outer Banks, whether it be from the shore or from a boat. With a proper license, visitors can cast their lines out into the sea to try and hook a wide array of exotic creatures such as flounder and bluefish. Obviously you can eat most of them, but observing the variety of ocean life that you pull in is half the fun.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\nThese are just a few of the things that you can do on the Outer Banks of North Carolina. With a bit of exploration, it’s easy to uncover a plethora of other activities just waiting to be discovered!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Andrew McClure</strong>\r\n\r\nContributor, <a href=\"http://www.liveout.org\">Live Out: The Outdoor Social Network</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAndrew McClure graduated from Western Carolina University with a B.A. in English, a concentration in professional writing, and a minor in biology. He is currently trying to enter the world of freelance writing. In his free time, he enjoys reading and studying alongside his dogs, Pepper and Little Ann.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Top Five Things to Do on the Outer Banks','','inherit','open','open','','711-revision-v1','','','2015-04-30 17:35:44','2015-04-30 17:35:44','',711,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/711-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(729,1,'2015-05-06 17:52:15','2015-05-06 17:52:15','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAsheville sits in the heart of the mountains of Western North Carolina; it’s an urban retreat in the midst of the vast rural foothills in the region. Asheville is home to an eclectic blend of natural beauty and urban life, resulting in a vibrant atmosphere of city people who are well connected to nature. If you ever plan on visiting Asheville, here is a list of five outdoor activities that you won’t want to pass up.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Hiking</b>\r\n\r\nThere are many hiking areas to explore around Asheville. In the fall, tourists flock to Asheville to see the foliage and wildlife, but it’s beautiful year round as well. When the leaves reach their peak and burst into color, many hikers head out into the forests to enjoy the experience of being surrounded by the colorful leaves. If you do go out into the woods, make sure that you follow all hiking safety procedures: stay together, prepare for emergencies, and ensure that you can find your way back.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Rafting and Swimming</b>\r\n\r\nAsheville lies close to several different rafting locations, such as the French Broad and Nantahala rivers. These rafting locations include both placid stretches of water for beginners and whitewater rapids for those who seek more of a thrill. In addition, there are also swimming holes and waterfalls near Asheville, such as in the Graveyard Fields area. Not only are these great areas to explore, but you can also cool off on a hot day and enjoy the magnificent waterfalls. You must exercise proper caution around waterfalls however, since it’s easy to get hurt on them.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Wildlife Observation</b>\r\n\r\nWestern North Carolina hosts a wide array of animal life, which can be seen out on nature trails and backroads. Small animals such as squirrels, chipmunks, and mice can be seen skittering across the forest floor. Larger animals can also be seen, such as deer, wild pigs, and even bears. If you don’t have the kind of patience that it takes to wait around for animals to show up, you can always visit the WNC Nature Center in Asheville. Here guests can find wolves, bears, otters, and even cougars.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Biking</b>\r\n\r\nAsheville also includes many good places to bike. Not only could you use your bike to explore urban and residential areas, but there are also cycling routes that take you through the forests. Biking in Asheville is a nice way to get your exercise in while exploring one of the most beautiful areas in the United States.\r\n\r\n<strong><strong> </strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Stargazing</b>\r\n\r\nSince Asheville doesn’t produce much light pollution, it’s easy to find a place where you can turn your telescope to the sky to observe the glistening moon, stars, and planets. The surrounding mountains also provide high elevations and isolated areas for you to go and stare into the depths of the cosmos.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/andrew.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-734\" src=\"http://www.liveout.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/andrew.jpg\" alt=\"Andrew McClure\" width=\"180\" height=\"180\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Author: Andrew McClure</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>About</strong>\r\n\r\nAndrew McClure graduated from Western Carolina University with a B.A. in English, a concentration in professional writing, and a minor in biology. He is currently trying to enter the world of freelance writing. In his free time, he enjoys reading and studying alongside his dogs, Pepper and Little Ann.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLeave a comment!','Top Five Outdoor Activities in Asheville, North Carolina','','publish','open','open','','top-five-outdoor-activities-in-asheville-north-carolina','','','2015-05-06 17:53:41','2015-05-06 17:53:41','',0,'http://www.liveout.org/blog/?p=729',0,'post','',0),(730,1,'2015-05-05 23:50:40','2015-05-05 23:50:40','','IMG_0743','','inherit','open','open','','img_0743','','','2015-05-0